<HEADLINE>Pro-Europe Tories demand Ministers take positive line</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY Party divisions on Europe re-opened last night as Europhile MPs
demanded Ministers publicly stand up for Britain's membership of the
Community.
A statement by the Positive European Group signed by 52 MPs called on
the Government to take action to counter the ''relentlessly negative''
attitudes of the Euro-scpetics.
The move comes as a clear show of strength by the pro-Europeans amid
growing concern at the increasingly Euro-sceptic drift of ministerial
pronouncements.
There are fears that the debate within the party has been hijacked by
the Euro-sceptics since the nine rebel MPs lost the whip.
The group's statement strongly denounced the rebels' policies saying
they would alienate Britain's allies and warning of the ''serious''
economic consequences if Britain was forced to leave the EU.
It said Ministers must make clear that compromise is an essential part
of working together in a community of 15 nations.
''They must also be much more willing to remind the electorate of the
advantage to Britain of Union membership and counter the relentlessly
negative attitudes, often based on misrepresentations, of the media and
the Euro-sceptics,'' it said.
It warned that it would be ''folly'' for Britain, as a trading nation
and financial centre, to rule out now joining a future European single
currency.
Any decision -- when it arose -- must take full account of Britian's
national interests and the impact on the economy.
The statement emphasised the growing support for Britain's vision of a
community of nation states and backed the ''positive but pragmatic''
approach adopted by successive Conservative Prime Ministers from Sir
Edward Heath, through Margaret Thatcher to John Major.
''We can still be 'at the heart of Europe' provided we have enough
belief in ourselves to understand that co-operation does not mean
centralisation ... It is time for us to press forward with confidence,''
it added.
The group chairman Ray Whitney said that they wanted to ensure that
the ''tenor and tone of the debate relating to Europe becomes more
positive.''
They received an early indication of support last night in the form of
a letter released by Energy Minister Tim Eggar to his constituency party
chairman strongly emphasising the benefits of EU membership.
''Our economic self-interest is plain -- we are inextricably bound to
the European Union,'' Mr Eggar wrote.
''The tide of arguement and events is with us. An economically
stronger Europe -- our sort of Europe -- is within our grasp. Yet many
in our party are too bogged down in internal debate over what might
never be to recognise the opportunities that are there to be grasped.''
At Prime Minister's Questions yesterday, Mr Major stoutly defended
Britain's membership of the EU and the UK's opt-out from the Maastricht
Treaty's Social Cchapter which lays down general working conditions.
Mr James Couchman (Gillingham -- Con.) suggested: ''The 40% of
American and Japanese investment in Europe that comes to the UK is
essentially dependent on our membership of the EU.
''If we ceased to be at the heart of Europe, those investors will
rethink their European operations locations.''
Mr Major replied: ''It depends on two points, both our membership of
the EU and the conditions of our membership of the EU.
''Certainly the fact that we are members has helped attract a great
deal of investment into this country.
''But it would be lost if the conditions of our membership were to
include the Social Chapter.''
He referred to the recent threat by the chairman of Daimler-Benz to
move out of Germany because of the cost of the social chapter provisions
in force there.
</TEXT>
