<HEADLINE>North Sea workers voice fears on helicopter safety</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041871</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONLY 50% of North Sea workers feel safe on the helicopter journeys to
and from their platforms, according to the first study to be carried out
on the perception and feelings of the UK offshore workforce.
The findings of the study were presented at a seminar in Aberdeen
yesterday when its authors, Professor Rhona Flin and Dr Kathryn Mearns,
also revealed it was still seen as ''politically incorrect'' for workers
to complain about safety issues.
The research was carried out by The Offshore Management Centre of The
Robert Gordon University, which organised yesterday's conference.
The background to its research, which involved 622 employees working
on six production platforms, was the need of those who promote and
regulate health and safety to understand how people think about and
respond to risk.
The Health and Safety Executive has indicated that risk perceptions
and attitudes form a special problem and that people are bad at judging
probability and particularly at judging risk.
''Typically, they are too frightened of strange situations and too
casual about familiar ones,'' it stated.
''They also underestimate risks they choose to take compared with
those imposed upon them.''
The UK study was modelled on Norwegian research and 40% of 1550
carefully developed questionnaires were returned. The average age of the
respondents was 40, and 98% were male. On average, they had worked
offshore for 10 years and on the same platform for the previous five.
The survey covered all occupations and included contractor and operator
personnel.
The research suggested that those who responded to the questionnaire
tended to feel safe working offshore but were aware of the hazards.
''The majority of respondents indicated they generally felt safe when
carrying out their work tasks. However, working with radioactive
materials, completing a task started by others, and when drilling is
taking place, only produced feelings of safety in about half the
sample,'' they told the conference.
''Similarly, only 50% of the respondents reported feeling safe in
relation to helicopter travel. This may be an accurate judgment of the
relative risks as helicopter flight is one of the most hazardous aspects
of offshore life for a number of installations across the North Sea.''
The findings showed that 44% agreed with the statement ''there is
sometimes pressure to put production before safety'' and 48% felt
''rules and instructions relating to safety sometimes make it difficult
to keep up with production targets'', with only 25% disagreeing with
these statements.
Professor Terence Lee, of St Andrews University, said that inquiries
into highly publicised accidents in recent years like Flixborough,
Bhopal, Kings Cross, Herald of Free Enterprise, Clapham Junction and
Piper Alpha had all come up with the same verdict -- that despite the
full range of engineering and technical safeguards complex systems broke
down disastrously because people running them failed to do what they
were supposed to.
He said these were not simple individual errors but malpractices which
corrupted large parts of the social system which made an industrial or
service organisation function.
</TEXT>
