<HEADLINE>Europe spur for leaders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041872</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOTH the principal prizes in the domestic men's indoor hockey season,
the league and the cup, will be decided within 24 hours this weekend
with Menzieshill again likely to figure prominently.
Already they have a two-point lead over Indespension, Western, and MIM
in the League. The Taysiders would have to drop three points in their
last two matches to miss taking the title for the fourth time in five
years.
Menzieshill are desperate to get back into Europe, and it's difficult
to envisage them failing at this late stage.
Menzieshill meet MIM in the final game at the Bell's Sports Centre,
Perth, tomorrow, but the leaders' clash with local rivals Torbrex
Wanderers could decide the issue.
A win for the favourites would almost certainly seal the fate of their
contenders, whose goal difference is inferior.
* EDINBURGH Ladies' target of winning the indoor women's hockey
league-and-cup double for the first time is looking forlorn.
Three of their key players Diane Renilson, Janet Jack, and Pauline
Robertson have spent the last two weeks in San Diego with the Great
Britain squad. If the tension, emotional stress, and pressure of
competition at times in extreme heat against the USA has not taken the
edge off their game, the fact that they don't return home until 24 hours
before Sunday's finals of the cup most certainly will.
The players, however, are keen to get involved and they have a
semi-final tie against Clydesdale in which to make the adjustments.
Western Klick Photopoint, the defending champions will have a more
difficult semi against Bonagrass Grove, and they should pick up their
first trophy of the season now that Wendy Fraser is fast becoming an
influence again after injury.
</TEXT>
