<HEADLINE>Ex-officer dies 52 years later from war wounds</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041873</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A WAR hero died on Christmas Day as a result of wounds he received
more than 50 years ago in North Africa, a coroner decided yesterday.
Captain Leslie Farmiloe, 79, was wounded during the siege of Tobruk in
1942 defending a gun emplacement.
Portsmouth coroner James Kenroy recorded a verdict of ''death by enemy
action while on active service'' -- which is extremely rare in
peacetime.
The acting captain was the only man left alive in his unit when a
German shell landed near him. He was wounded by fragments of exploding
ammunition boxes.
Captain Farmiloe was awarded the Military Cross but unknown to him the
shrapnel in his body from the ammunition boxes contained asbestos which
eventually killed him.
A family friend, Dr Richard Nainby-Luxmoore, of Southwick, Hampshire,
said that Mr Farmiloe kept his bravery a secret until a few days before
his death.
Doctors did not discover asbestos poisoning until Mr Farmiloe, of
Castle Gardens, Petersfield, Hampshire, who served with the 25th Light
Royal Artillery, became ill last year.
Pathologist Dr Margaret Jeffrey said he died of an asbestos-related
disease.
Mr Farmiloe is survived by his wife Hazel and two sons.
</TEXT>
