<HEADLINE>Middle East summit seeks to save peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SAMIA NAKHOUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Cairo, Thursday
THE leaders of Israel and its three Arab peace partners met in Cairo
today for a historic summit to speed up the Middle East peace process.
Tonight, after five hours of talks, they were said to have agreed on a
joint communique.
Egyptian newspapers described the meeting of the leaders of Israel,
Egypt, Jordan, and the Palestinians ''a summit to save the peace''.
Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said he expected the talks to
redraw the political map of the Middle East and build a ''coalition for
peace''.
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin, PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, and King Hussein of Jordan have their
own domestic agendas. However all share a desire to see more rapid
progress towards peace between Israel and the Palestinians, who are
anxiously awaiting the extension of self-rule to parts of the West Bank
now under occupation.
Before leaving Israel, Rabin said he would demand that the PLO do more
to stop Palestinian attacks on Israelis.
He told veterans of his Labour Party in Tel Aviv: ''We have a demand
of the Palestinian Authority -- and we will present it at every meeting
-- that the people under its authority do not carry out murderous
attacks.''
At the same time, Israeli Police Minister Moshe Shahal said Israel
could consider as early as tomorrow easing the closure it imposed on the
occupied West Bank and self-ruled Gaza Strip after the last Palestinian
attack.
However Islamic Jihad, the militant organisation which has rocked
Israel with suicide bombings, denounced the summit, saying the Arab
leaders were just trying to improve Rabin's image.
Egyptian and Israeli officials were drafting a communique calling for
an end to political violence, perseverance with PLO-Israeli agreements,
and more international funding for the Palestinian Authority.
Palestinian officials said they were unhappy with the proposed
emphasis on terrorism, saying it diverted attention from their main
concern of extending Palestinian authority over the Israeli occupied
territories.
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak had separate meetings with the three
visitors before all four came together for iftar, the meal which opens
the festival of Ramadan.
Ramadan is a month of peace for Muslims and Rabin's presence at the
meal is widely seen as a sign of acceptance by his Muslim neighbours, a
gesture that would have been unthinkable only two years ago.
Deep worries lay behind the gestures, however. Israeli and PLO
officials said they feared the summit might be little more than a
''photo opportunity'' for leaders trying to polish images at home.
Syria and Lebanon, the main Arab parties holding out against peace on
what they see as Israeli terms, will not attend.
Peres told Israeli army radio that Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
would have been welcome. ''We aren't leaving Assad out. Assad is leaving
himself out,'' he said.
''Assad has divorced himself from the process of war and he has yet to
marry the peace process. He is at a stage of political bachelorhood.''
The current Middle East peace process was launched at a conference in
Madrid more than three years ago and has taken shape in agreements
signed by Israel to end almost 50 years of hostility with Jordan and the
Palestinians.
However the march towards peace has stumbled over Arab-Jewish
violence, mainly by Muslim militants opposed to peace with the Jewish
state, Israel's sharp reaction to this violence, and deadlock in talks
with Syria.
US Secretary of State Warren Christopher, whose country has been the
prime mover behind peace, welcomed the summit as a powerful statement
that enemies of peace will not win: ''The United States applauds and
endorses President Mubarak's bold initiative,'' he said.
Arafat told reporters as he left for Cairo: ''It's a very important
meeting and we hope to solve all the problems.''
An Israeli official in Cairo played down expectations: ''We expect
little from the summit, but the fact it is taking place sends a message
that the peace process continues.''
Israeli and PLO officials said the urgent problem was to find a way
forward in deadlocked Palestinian-Israeli negotiations, challenged by
such anti-Israeli violence as the Muslim militant bombing that killed 21
Israelis last week.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
