<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>An eye-opener for Brown</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041878</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND manager Craig Brown returned from Moscow yesterday to reveal
that his side would be facing Russia in the European Championship in a
stadium which has horrendous facilities.
Because of a new roof being erected at the national stadium in Moscow
-- the work is not expected to be completed in time for the visit of the
Scots -- Brown's men will play at the Lokomotiv ground, and will face
problems.
Said Brown: ''Honestly, I've never seen dressing-rooms like them. We
will be taking along bottles of Dettol to use in them.
''The showers are ancient, there are no hooks for the players to hang
their clothes, and we are going to have to disinfect the area before the
lads train and play.
''I was a little taken aback at the state of the stadium. The seating
is simply benches laid along concrete blocks on the terracing and some
of them are rotting.
''Neither that stadium nor the Torpedo ground, where the under-21 side
will play, would pass inspection in Scotland.''
However, there was a bonus for Brown when he had a look around the
hotel where the Scottish party will be staying. ''The hotel and the food
are excellent,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alexander next for Jacobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GARY Jacobs, the former undefeated European welterweight boxing
champion from Glasgow, was last night given the name of his opponent for
his fight in Atlantic City on March 4.
The Scot, who will be having his last bout before challenging Pernell
Whitaker for the World Boxing Council welterweight championship in the
summer, will meet Tom Alexander, from Pittsburgh, on the same bill as
Whitaker challenges Jorge Vasquez for the light-middlweight crown.
If successful, Whitaker would immediately give up that title to
concentrate on a big-money showdown with Jacobs. The Scot has for some
time been rated as the official No.1 challenger for the welterweight
crown and has waited patiently for his chance.
Alexander is a tough fighter who has a record of 25 contests, 18 wins
and seven losses. He has been in with good class opposition, such as
former world lightweight champion Hector ''Macho'' Camacho, and was
beaten on cuts in the seventh round in that bout.
The trip will give the Scot a chance to have a close look at Whitaker.
''I keep hearing how good he is,'' Jacobs said. ''He is good, but I'm
convinced that when we finally get into the ring, I'll beat him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Elleray makes a stand</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041880</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOP referee David Elleray, who sent off two Everton players and showed
the yellow card a dozen times in a stormy Premiership clash at
Newcastle, insisted yesterday that he and his fellow officials still
have the respect of the top players.
The Harrow schoolmaster, who is the designated spokesman for the 22
elite referees on the Premiership list, said: ''Overall, relationships
between players and referees this season are better than ever.
''I think players are becoming aware of the way in which referees have
to do their jobs. We are on first name-terms with a lot of them.
''But it seems that scapegoats are always needed in football and
referees are the easiest targets.
''Everybody else takes their turn at being a winner or loser, but we
can never win.
On Wednesday night Everton manager Joe Royle described Elleray's
refereeing performance at Newcastle as the most insensitive he had seen
in 30 years.
Royle's comments followed hot on the heels this week of Paul Danson
having to cancel a red card against West Ham's Alvin Martin when the FA
presented the Leicester referee with irrefutable video evidence of his
mistake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McCoist can cap his return against Russia</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALLY McCoist could be set to make a dramatic return in an
international jersey for the first time in almost two years when
Scotland travel to Moscow next month for their European Championship
qualifier against Russia -- a match from which they must take something
if they are to boost their hopes of reaching the finals in England next
summer.
The Rangers striker, despite having started only four matches for his
club this season and making another five appearances as a substitute, is
very much in the mind of Scotland manager Craig Brown, who has just
returned from a fact-finding mission to Russia.
McCoist made his last appearance for Scotland in the 5-0 defeat
against Portugal in Lisbon in April, 1993, when it was later diagnosed
he had broken a leg, and since then the man who has proved himself the
most prolific scorer in the country in recent years has been dogged by
one injury after another.
However, he continued his build-up to match fitness in a reserve match
at Easter Road on Wednesday night, where he scored twice, and Brown is
keeping in close touch with the situation.
Yesterday Rangers manager Walter Smith confirmed that McCoist had come
through the reserve match unscathed and said: ''He is fit and ready to
play against Dundee United at Ibrox on Saturday -- if selected. I'm very
pleased with his progress.''
Brown was delighted with that assessment. He said: ''I'll be going to
Ibrox next week to have a talk with Ally and Walter. It was in my mind
to give Ally a run in the B international against Northern Ireland at
Easter Road later this month, but that may not happen.
''There would be no point in overloading him with matches too soon,
but, if Ally and Walter feel that he needs an extra game, then he might
play at Easter Road.''
Scotland do not have an embarrassment of fit or in-form strikers at
the moment, and Brown is keeping all his options open. That, obviously,
includes McCoist.
''Really, I just want him back scoring goals and ready to face the
Russians,'' said the national manager. ''I would have no worries pushing
him straight back into the international side, even though he may manage
only half-a-dozen matches by that time.
''It was the best possible news I could get when I returned from
Russia, to find that he was ready for action. It would be even better
news if he continued the progress and played in Moscow.''
Meantime, Rangers' only problem, apart from long-term injuries to Andy
Goram and Alexei Mikhailichenko, for tomorrow's match against Dundee
United is midfield man Ian Ferguson, who lasted only 10 minutes of the
reserve match at Easter Road.
Ferguson has suffered a recurrence of a groin injury and, as well as
missing tomorrow's match, he is almost certain to miss out on Monday
night's Scottish Cup tie against Hamilton at Firhill.
Dundee United have a big worry over central defender defender Brian
Welsh for the trip to Ibrox. He missed training again yesterday, because
of flu and a throat infection, and a more realistic target for him may
be next Tuesday's Scottish Cup replay against Clyde at Broadwood.
Motherwell, who have recently stumbled after their commendable effort
to push Rangers in the championship, would probably see Celtic as the
main dangers for second place and will be determined to extend their
advantage when the teams meet at Fir Park tomorrow.
Looking towards that match yesterday, manager Alex McLeish asked his
players to prove Celtic's manager right in his assessment of the
Lanarkshire side.
Explained McLeish: ''We have had two hard matches against Celtic this
season, both ending in draws, and after the last one at Hampden Tommy
Burns was saying some nice things about us, saying how good we were.
It's now up to my players to go out and prove they deserve those kind of
comments.
''There could be various excuses used to explain our poor run, but I'm
not going to list them, except to say that this is a learning experience
for me as a manager. When you are on a winning run, that can hide
certain flaws and, hopefully, in defeat I have learned something. For
example, I should maybe use the horses for courses philosophy, or maybe
change our style now and again.
''Celtic are going reasonably well at the moment and the signing of
Hooydonk and the form of Falconer have given them a lift. But I won't
need to motivate my players for this one, and we have everyone available
to play.''
Notts County, who last year signed Rangers front man Gary McSwegan,
are the latest club to be linked with Celtic striker Andy Walker, who
has had to sit on the bench in recent matches. Burnley are also reported
to be keen on taking Walker, who rejoined Celtic from Bolton last
summer, back south.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Battle of Hastings is to win back his place</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, CHIEF RUGBY WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>48</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041882</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND A go for the hat trick of wins over their Irish counterparts
at Myreside today and what a tantalising feast of rugby is in store as a
fair old sprinkling of Scots with points to prove set about staking Five
Nations' and World Cup claims.
This is not to downplay the importance of the match itself -- as coach
David Johnston's side seek to get back on the winning trail after defeat
by France last time out -- but with a queue of Scotsmen seeking to force
their way back into full international contention it has all the
hallmarks of a gripping afternoon's sport.
At the head of the queue is out-of-favour Scott Hastings. Dropped from
the full side after his fifty-first outing against South Africa,
Hastings has until now kept his own counsel.
However, yesterday he told me: ''It's a different experience in the A
team compared to the build-up to a full international, but this time
around with six full caps in the team it's not just myself with a point
to prove.
''There's Derek Stark, Tony Stanger, Jeremy Richardson, and Ian Smith
for starters. There's a lot of talent there and a lot of guys who have
played and toured for Scotland. After the disappointment of losing
against France, when we could have won, the onus is on us to perform to
a higher standard and to take our changes this time around.
''After the Scotland game against South Africa the selectors
considered that I had a played poorly and I now have to prove them
wrong. I have to prove to them that I can still play full international
rugby.''
For Hastings's midfield partner Tony Stanger, too, today's game
represents a golden opportunity to show that he can cope with the
entirely different questions posed in the centre.
Stanger, who regularly plays in that berth for Hawick, decided after
36 caps on the international wing that he fancied a change. No matter
that with 16 international touchdowns he is Scotland's second top
try-scorer. Today's outing, when he will play outside Hastings,
represents the ideal forum in which to display his worth in a fresh
positional environment.
Also in the queue is Boroughmuir's Derek Stark. With his confidence on
a fresh high, the four-times capped Kilmarnock chef is out to prove that
the selectors were wrong to leave him out of the patchwork of teams
which faced the South Africans last November.
Yesterday, coach David Johnston looked back on that last defeat by
France as a game which the Scots could have won. ''I say 'could' because
I'm not sure that we should have won it,'' he said. ''But it was
definitely there to be won. We had the opportunities to do so but we
didn't take them. However, good players should get better, so from that
start we'll be looking for a better all-round performance.''
Skipper Jeremy Richardson, who is another hoping to fight his way back
into full international reckoning after a single outing against South
Africa, said: ''Against the French I wouldn't necessarily agree that we
had done enough in terms of possesion to win the game but we didn't make
the most of our chances.
''Against the French you have to play for the full 80 minutes. Against
the Irish we would be hoping to control the game from start to finish if
