<HEADLINE>Ceramic company passes to Baxi</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041883</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Baxi Partnership yesterday announced that it had taken control of
Barrhead Sanitary Ware, the ceramic company bought from Armitage Shanks
by its employees.
The company had been in financial difficulties for more than a year.
There had been fears that Baxi's ambitions would be thwarted by the
Barrhead co-operative's constitution.
However, Baxi has agreed to buy without changing the legal articles of
the company.
Mr Lawrence King, Group Finance Director of the Baxi Partnership,
said: ''We have taken control of the company without the ability to
change its articles.
''We have saved the company and given it a secure and proud future,
but we have compromised on our original objective.''
0 Under the articles of the Barrhead company 75% of all shareholders,
including those who have not voted, had to agree for a sale to go ahead.
Baxi's takeover had the unanimous support of the voting Ordinary
shareholders, in effect the workers who invested their own money into
company when it was bought over, who had agreed to accept Baxi's offer
of 40p for their #1 shares.
It also had 100% backing from its Preference shareholders who had
agreed Baxi's offer of #1 per #1 share.
However, only 53% of non-voting Ordinary shareholders supported the
deal. This category of shareholders consists mainly of local small
investors who backed the company with some of their savings. They had
been urged by Sir Albert McQuarrie, a former Barrhead chairman, to
reject the offer.
Baxi still hopes to increase its shareholding so that it can change
the articles of the company, and has therefore kept open its offer to
buy shares until the end of February.
Barrhead first approached Baxi for help at the end of 1993, and when
Baxi's bid to acquire the company failed in March 1994, Baxi gave it a
secured loan for #450,000.
Mr Ray Peedle, chief executive of Barrhead, said: ''Everyone here is
very pleased that the uncertainty is now over and that we can get on
with the business of manufacturing sanitary ware in Scotland.''
</TEXT>
