<DOCNO>GH950203-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clarke puts up rates in pre-emptive strike</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIST STONE,CITY EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The half-point increase in interest rates to 6[3/4]% yesterday was the
third rise in five months as Chancellor Kennneth Clarke made yet another
pre-emptive strike to curb future inflationary pressures.
The move was greeted comfortably in financial markets, where it had
been largely discounted, but disappointed the building societies
although, for the time being anyway, they are holding back from lifting
their own lending rates.
The Halifax, Britain's biggest society, which led a recent round of
mortgage increases in response to the December base rate rise, expressed
its disappointment, but said it saw no immediate need change interest
rates though it will have to keep the situation under review.
Abbey National, the second-largest mortage lender, said it was
reluctant to increase mortgage rates and the Nationwide Building Society
said it was reviewing the situation. Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, which held
its rates steady after previous increases, said it would not be
reviewing its rates until April, that there is no possible rise before
May 1 and that will depend on other lenders.
The trend in interest rates still looks to be up and at some stage
mortgage lenders are bound to follow suit which does not do the housing
market any favours.
Yesterday's rise, which followed the regular monthly monetary meeting
between the Chancellor and Governor of the Bank of England Eddie George,
comes hard on the heels of a similar increase in US short-term rates. It
was not only the building societies, which are influenced by the current
state of the housing market, that thought the increase in rates was
uneccessary.
Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British
Industry, commented: ''In our view domestic conditions did not require a
further rise in rates. Taking full account of recent CBI surveys and
information from the housing market and the behaviour of monetary
aggregates, our judgment is that inflation remains under control.''
He admitted that the decision was finely balanced, and the US move
certainly put pressure on the authorities here.
The general view in financial markets was probably expressed by the
Royal Bank of Scotland's chief economist Jeremy Peat as the clearing
banks hoisted their base rates.
He commented: ''The further increase is not unexpected, given the
evidence of continued strong growth of GDP and signs of some capacity
constraints emerging. The markets' expectation of such a move was
reinforced by Thursday's half-point increase in US interest rates.''
But Mr Peat also pointed to inevitable downside implications,
particularly when some aspects of the economy -- such as the housing
market -- remain weak. Even so, he regards the Chancellor's action as
prudent at this stage, aimed at enhancing the prospects of stable low
inflation growth over the next two or three years.
''It is better for the Chancellor and Governor to act pre-emptively,
rather than being seen to act reluctantly and belatedly.''
In making his move, Mr Clarke said that on the balance of risks, a
further increase in interest rates will help to keep inflation under
control. He also said that the UK's economic recovery was ''healthy and
well balanced'', founded on a remarkable improvement in competitiveness
across British industry, with growth generated by exports.
The Chancellor also emphasised, as has Mr George on several occasions,
that market perceptions through futures tend to exaggerate the risk of
sharply higher interest rates.
Further evidence, though, of the fragility of the housing market comes
with the latest Halifax House Price Index. This shows house prices fell
by 0.1% in January, less that the decline reported on Wednesday by the
Nationwide, and that the underlying trend in house prices shows a very
flat picture with no evidence of recovery.
However, recent movements in house prices remain consistent with the
Society's view that prices will rise by 2% to 3% during the course of
the year. The Nationwide is predicting much the same but both societies
had started 1994 looking for reasonable increases which fell away as the
year progressed.
The Treasury's monthly monetary report, also released yesterday, said
monthly indicators were mixed. Some pointed to a moderation in the pace
of growth, while others showed a more buoyant picture.
Retail sales continued on an upward trend although this has flattened
off recently. The report said that moderately lower output growth in the
second half of 1994 may have been concentrated in the manufacturing
sector but it also points to CBI survey data suggests an acceleration in
manufacturing output in the final quarter of last year.
Share markets ignored the rate increase with the FTSE-100 Share Index
closing up 17.4 at 3034.7. It was up 22 points at one stage but
succumbed to light profit-taking.
Government securities, which had suffered early falls, recovered on
the rate increase which was regarded as positive while in foreign
exchange markets the rise was already discounted and made little impact
on sterling.
</TEXT>
