<HEADLINE>Up the hill and round the bend</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>VIEW</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041887</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PARANOIA has always been one of the great players in Scottish
football. Old Perse Complex has been there, done it all, and worn the
shirt of just about every club in the land, but we didn't think the day
would come when he made it all the way to the top of the hill mob. Yet
there he was in midweek sharing a desk with the chief executive of the
SFA, peering over his shoulder as the Man On High rolled a few tablets
of fury down the mountain.
Whatever else he has been accused of over the years in his role as
guardian of the football proprieties, Jim Farry has never been
considered unintelligent. Pompous he can be, yes; Rigid, yes; and, yes,
he does give pronouncements from above in a kind of Farryese which only
those who compile insurance policies would comprehend. Nor is he one to
tolerate what he sees as incompetence. But foolish? No.
That is why his mass condemnation of the football writing brigade of
Scotland was so unexpected. His distaste for much of the excesses of
modern football reporting has been well known for some time and he would
find many empathetic ears in the football world when he makes that
point. He would even find a fair number of those directly employed in
that end of the business who would go along with him some of the way.
But when the man at the heart of the game insists that ''everyone''
who writes about the game in this country is ''doom laden'' and
collectively ''the worst in the world for being negative'', he has
clearly opened the door to our old pal, Perse.
The diatribe was bizarre enough in itself, but in response to a survey
of fans carried out by another newspaper, it seemed positively
eccentric. However much influence the hacks around the country may have,
it does not stretch to lobbying 1000 citizens to condemn football for
the benefit of a rival blatt.
Farry is right when he says that there is a general Scottish disease
which entails destroying something that is praiseworthy. It is a
peculiar Celtic trait which allows us to cheer ''Scots Wha' Hae'' and
then throw the singers out of the pub (Wha', indeed , is like us?). But
in terms of the standard of our football, Farry himself has expressed
his concern about the poorer quality and what it might do to our
standing in Eurrope.
It is true that he and his association have put in a lot of work and
organisation, at which he is expert, in trying to redress the balance,
to restructure the game from its grass roots. And maybe the SFA does not
get enough credit for that aspect of its duties.
They are, after all, the paid employees of the football clubs and, if
the great minds who people the board rooms of the game have better ideas
on how to bring football back to a better level, they are free to knock
on the Farry door any time.
The chief executive has every right to have a go at those who have a
go at him -- there is nothing like a good old barney to stimulate
interest -- but he did not give his usual meticulous attention to
accuracy this time. In fact, he sounded a bit sensationalist to me.
Tabloid, even.
</TEXT>
