<DOCNO>GH950203-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drug abusers hit by Operation Rumble</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCORES of drug abusers have been caught in a police operation in
Dumfries and Galloway, it was revealed yesterday.
The police launched Operation Rumble one month ago, and so far 83
people have been detained and searched and 78 offences reported to the
procurator-fiscal.
Some 48 premises have been searched, and controlled drugs with a
street value of thousands of pounds have been recovered, including
cannabis, heroin, cocaine, ecstasy, amphetamine, and temazepam. Police
said they were surprised by the quantity of drugs recovered.
A unit of 13 CID, drugs squad and uniformed officers, was formed to
carry out the operation, which is continuing.
Detective Superintendent Fred Newton, head of the CID, said yesterday:
''The initiative reflects our commitment to address the problem of drug
misuse in this region.
''Potential targets are being identified through intelligence and
information from local sources.''
He said the campaign would touch almost every community in Dumfries
and Galloway and added: ''The message is simple: if you are involved in
using or supplying controlled drugs, you could be the next target for
Operation Rumble. You have to ask yourself if it is worth the risk.''
The number of recorded drugs offences has increased in the region
during the past few years, in line with the national trend, a police
report on the operation states.
''While much speculation exists as to the extent of the problem in
thisarea, it would be foolish simply to ignore it and its impact on
local communities and families,'' it adds.
The recently published findings of the Ministerial Drugs Task Force
described drug abuse in Scotland as ''a serious and escalating
problem''.
They identified the need for more effective community action by
bringing together voluntary and statutory agencies in a co-ordinated and
positive manner to tackle the problem, the police report says.
</TEXT>
