<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ex-Ministers propose two year rule on jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041890</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS should be quarantined for two years after relinquishing
office and before taking up jobs with firms with which their departments
might have had dealings, two former Tory Cabinet members proposed
yesterday.
Speaking at the Nolan inquiry investigating standards in public life,
Lord Younger of Prestwick, the former Secretary of State in the Scottish
Office and at the Ministry of Defence, and Sir Norman Fowler, a former
chairman of the Tory party, both came up with the almost identical
suggestion about a two-year rule, similar to one enforced on senior
civil servants
Both of them made it clear that they were not criticising former
colleagues, but were instead were suggesting a new way forward.
They also proposed that any former Minister would require the approval
of an independent committee before joining a company that had dealings
with their former department within the two year period.
Had such a ruling been in force Conservative Governments might have
been spared embarrassment, following the publicity which has been
critical of former Ministers on their departure from office.
Both former Ministers have now embarked on new careers outside of
politics. Lord Younger is the chairman of the Royal Bank of Scotland.
Sir Norman said that there were certain outside jobs that should be
barred to back-bench MPs. Top of the list was a paid consultancy with a
parliamentary lobbying company, he told the Nolan inquiry team.
Lord Younger also gave evidence on remunerations to back benchers. He
had no doubt that they should be free take up such opportunities.
However, he was clear that MPs should not accept payment for answering
questions in the House of Commons.
Lord Younger said he would never have considered moving directly from
the Ministry of Defence to take up a directorship with a major
contractor in the defence industry. ''That would have been pretty
foolish and one would expect to be criticised,'' he told the committee.
Discussing the difference between Ministers and civil servants --
Ministers might have to leave office overnight whereas civil servants
might have a pension to fall back on -- Lord Younger said that Ministers
had to take the rough with the smooth. It was a phrase later echoed by
Sir Norman when he gave evidence.
Lord Armstrong, the former secretary to the Cabinet Office told the
committee that the Child Support Agency should never have been set up,
and certainly not in its current form.
The agency has involved civil servants chasing absent parents in an
unfair position, the former head of the Home Civil Service said.
He also took pains to defend former Ministers over allegations of a
misuse of powers -- not least the recent appointment of Lord Wakeham as
a non-executive director of N M Rothschild and Sons Ltd. Lord Armstrong
is also a director of the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fastest -- but Scottish athletes still second rate.    Stewart can make impact on selectors</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SENSE of injustice is powerful fuel for motivating the mind and
driving the legs, so visitors to Birmingham's National Arena this
weekend should be prepared for some aggressive Scottish running.
The AAA indoor championships, being staged there tonight and tomorrow,
will largely determine the contenders for the world indoor championships
in Barcelona next month, as well as the British team to face France next
weekend in Glasgow's Kelvin Hall.
Among those who believe they should be included are Glen Stewart and
Ian Campbell, both overlooked for the Great Britain international
against Russia last weekend, despite being ranked fastest in the UK this
year in their respective events.
Stewart, in winning the Scottish West district 3000 metres title last
month, clocked 8min 09.4sec, which put him more than a second ahead of
his nearest UK rival. Campbell was even more harshly treated. A Scottish
native record of 3-45.26 for 1500m put him more than five seconds clear
of his UK opponents. Neither made the team. Nor did Aileen McGillivray,
fastest woman in the country over 60m at the time the team was chosen.
''I'm really displeased at being overlooked,'' said Stewart, the
Scottish outdoor 1500m champion. ''The world indoor 3000m qualifying
time is 7-56, and I believe I am capable of that in the right race. I
think I can win this weekend, and that might help me get a quality race
where the time would be more readily achieved.
''I was surprised not to be in the Russia team. Phil Mowbray, who has
never beaten me on a running track was chosen -- yet has never run
indoors. Then Tony Whiteman, who is slower than me over 1500m, was
called in as a reserve.
''If I had set my sights particularly on the indoors, I would be
raging. Fortunately, it's only a means to an end. Outdoors is my main
target.''
His father, Lachie, the former Commonwealth 10,000m champion, has
heated views on the treatment meted out to Scots. ''They should remember
it is a British Athletic Federation, not an English one,'' he said.
''Even if it costs more to get Scots to meaningful races, they have an
obligation to do so.''
Likely rivals in tomorrow's final include Darius Burrows and Steffan
White, third and fourth against Russia last weekend, so Stewart has
every opportunity to make his point.
Campbell, runner-up to Tom McKean for the Scottish 800m title, also
reckons he can make it to Barcelona, but as last year, when he was
initially passed over for the European championships despite being first
Briton in the AAAs, he is having to do it the hard way. His 1500m heats
are tonight, and he looks forward tomorrow to facing Tony Morrell, who,
though slower, won the Scottish title in his absence and a reserve run
against Russia.
City of Glasgow's Mel Neef and teenage Scot Alison Curbishley go in
tonight's women's 400m heats -- Commonwealth and European finalist
Neef's first individual 400m of the winter after eight Scottish records
at shorter distances, while Brian Whittle contests the men's 400m.
</TEXT>
