<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A walk on the dark side</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041892</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Mary Brennan speaks to Michael Mayhew about the shadow of death that
has permeated his work
OF late, Michael Mayhew has been wondering just how strongly he
resembles the men in his family. His father, for instance. His father's
father. And cousin Tony. It's no use looking at photographs. They don't
give away what he wants to know. The clue to his wondering lies in their
death certificates. All three committed suicide. The thought has already
been planted from boyhood, from before he fully understood what it
meant: will he die the same way?
Death and dying have permeated Mayhew's performance work for as long
as either of us can remember. Even when the subject has publicly
declared itself as something else -- sex, religion, love -- the prospect
of death has shadowed the stage. There is, he says, with a skewed grin
crossing his gaunt features: ''No life without it''.
Now, with the latest piece, Die by Suicide, death comes centre-stage.
But a kind of death that carries with it a whole tangle of taboos. Since
the age of 15 -- from 1978, when he had to deal with his father's
suicide -- Mayhew has stalked these taboos, been haunted by them.
Instability, genetic disorder, hereditary disposition . . . You can
almost hear his brain boiling as he leans across the table, talking
rapidly, fiercely, about the medical theories that seem to label him a
likely candidate for self-inflicted death.
And yet, as he goes over the events surrounding his father's suicide,
what he remembers most is how carefully calculated, how considered, this
last act was. ''Frankly, whatever the coroner said, there didn't seem
anything unbalanced about it. His note -- 'sorry son, things didn't work
out . . .' -- was as if he'd weighed things up, decided he'd had enough,
and made his choice. If I've inherited anything, it's not some mental
illness. It's the knowledge that I can make that choice. I can take my
own life.''
That choice, in a world where individual choices seem more and more
constrained by outside agencies is, for him, empowerment. The ultimate
means of self-expression, undertaken with as much reverence, as much
thought and preparation as a work of art.
Only, of course, that's not always how it is. He agrees that, for too
many people, it's a desperate waste. A panic measure, carried out
without any real understanding of the consequences.
''People feel isolated, confused, unhappy -- and there's nowhere,
no-one to turn to. It's another taboo. We just don't open up in this
society. We don't talk about the things that really affect our lives,
the things that drive us to our deaths. And we don't talk about those
deaths either. We just shroud everything in silence and in myth.'' This
attitude obviously angers and distresses him. It compels him to take
issue with it in his work. Together with his partner, Becky Edmonds,
Mayhew has gone about exposing both the myth and the silence.
For months now they've been gathering together historical fact and
personal stories, images from lives that have been touched by suicide
(some famous, some completely unknown), statistics from reports that
itemise gender, age, method, time, and place -- but ultimately do
nothing to help us understand why. Some of this research -- including
material from their recent Glasgow residency -- will feature in an
exhibition called The Clarity of Self-Execution that can be seen while
they are performing at the CCA in early February.
''Meeting people, talking through their experiences -- and we've had a
really powerful response to this -- makes you realise how much suicide
figures in everyone's thoughts. And how hard it is to have any kind of
dispassionate conversation about it.''
Though the subject is so close to his own life, he won't actually
appear in the show itself. ''We've made it a solo for Becky. Yes, I
suppose you could say she's the melting pot for my experiences and for
the other histories we've researched. And maybe, as I'm getting older,
into my thirties, I feel I can stand back from it a bit. I can watch and
say, 'Yeah, I know that feeling. I've got some of that darkness inside
me'. I can, in a way, really claim my own life because I know that I can
end it . . .''
* Mayhew and Edmonds are appearing at the CCA, Glasgow, tonight and
tomorrow as part of the Bad Times season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vested interests at Braemar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TRIED TESTED</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The weekend snow -- and the forecast of another few days of freezing
temperatures -- brought a reminder that January and February is the time
for thermal underwear in Scotland. But is it worth paying top prices or
should you head for the chain store? We put several garments to the test
in icy Braemar in a week when the official morning temperature readings
did not rise above freezing point and reached a low of
-10C on Monday morning. Three people whose jobs involve spending a
large amount of time outside each tried three readily-available
garments.
Anti-freeze action: the long and short of it
CATHERINE Bagan and her family are experiencing their first winter in
Braemar since taking over the village garage after five years in
Australia.
''We've gone from one extreme to the other. I really was not prepared
for this degree of coldness. It is well below freezing when we open up
the garage in the morning and scrape the ice off the windows.
''People kept telling me I would need thermals in the winter, but I
thought that was a bit of an exaggeration, because we had a garage
before in Burntisland and I did not wear them then. Since I have tried
these, however, I have realised that they do make a difference. I have
tried some men's ones because they are thicker and my husband wears them
in the workshop, but the ladies' are much more comfortable.
She tried sleeveless vests from Damart and Littlewoods and a
long-sleeved one from Marks &amp; Spencer. The long-sleeved version proved
the warmest, but she thought that a long-sleeved version of the Damart
one would have rated the same on warmth. The Littlewoods version's only
plus point was the price. It was considerably shorter than the other
two, was skimpier and generally thinner. ''You just would not have known
you had on an extra layer,'' said Catherine, who usually wears a polo
neck topped by a cardigan but found that with a thermal vest she did not
always need to add her down bodywarmer when she went to the petrol
pumps.
The overall winner was the Marks &amp; Spencer vest which Catherine rated
higher than Damart on the soft feel of the material and on the prettier,
more feminine styling. ''You would not expect style to matter, but up
here it is so cold you have to wear trousers and woollies all the time
and it is nice to have something more feminine.''
Mrs Bagan's 16-year-old daughter, Bernadette, also tried out the vests
-- after a scornful initial reaction -- and also rated M&amp;S top.
Thermal factor on top at 15 below
GORDON Rattray, who spends the winter months teaching primary school
children to ski and taking them on hillwalking expeditions, realised a
20-year ambition to live and work in the mountains two years ago when he
and his wife set up the Braemar Heritage Centre.
He has always dismissed thermal underwear as unnecessary and has worn
cotton T-shirts as his bottom layer. After testing three vests, he says
all are warmer than a T-shirt. In a week when the temperature on the
hills reached -15C taking wind chill into account, he found he was
''toasting'' in both Damart and Marks &amp; Spencer.
The Littlewoods version was slightly less warm but was rated lowest
because it was the least comfortable. ''The neck was cut too high and
the edge rolled in, making it very uncomfortable under a polo neck.''
Damart also lost out on the comfort factor. ''It was beautifully made,
but because it had heavy stitching round the neck and arms, it was also
slightly uncomfortable.''
Marks &amp; Spencer took top place for comfort, warmth and fit -- and
Gordon also liked the feel of the cloth. He will buy more.
How to home in on comfort
MOUNTAINEER and Nordic ski instructor Malcolm MacIntyre wears thermal
underwear for a large part of his life -- often the ranges designed
specifically for sports, which can be very expensive. He reckons the
best value specialist range is North Cape at #25 for a long-sleeved,
zip-neck version.
He tested a short-sleeved vest from Damart, Marks &amp; Spencer and
British Home Stores and found the best performance from the cheapest. He
rated the #8.99 BHS version best for both warmth and the ability of the
material to wick sweat away from the body. By that test, Marks &amp; Spencer
performed worst with a material which trapped moisture although it was
otherwise very comfortable.
''It would be fine for someone just wearing it for going about in cold
weather, but not for winter sports,'' he said. ''On comfort alone, I
would rate BHS best, Marks &amp; Spencer second, and Damart third, but for
warmth and wicking it would be 1, BHS; 2, Damart; and 3, Marks &amp;
Spencer.'' His advice to anyone looking particularly for warmth is to
choose a fabric with a high level of viscose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
