<DOCNO>GH950203-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Full of bounce Humphrey Lyttelton Band, Music Hall, Aberdeen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON KERR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EVEN after 47 years as a band leader, Humphrey Lyttelton still bounces
on stage with the energy of a man half his age, and still presents his
audience with a programme of classily arranged tunes and a group of
world-class musicians.
Hyper Humph excelled himself on trumpet and
bopping-around-in-the-background duties, and the rest of his merry band
turned out equally creditable performances. But with the exception of
two numbers (Porgy and One Day I Met an African), it was all a little
flat -- until the arrival of special guest Joe Temperley, the New
York-based Scots-born baritone saxophonist.
It may have been Humph's band, but it was Joe's show. We knew we were
in for a treat from note one of Temperley's first featured number --
Prelude to a Kiss. Deliciously slow (and succulent), if this was just
the prelude, it must have been a helluva kiss. The undoubted highlight
of the evening was a tantalisingly short set by Temperley and a rhythm
section of Stan Greig (piano), Paul Bridge (bass), and Adrian MacIntosh
(drums).
Temperley proved why he is one of the most sought after baritone
players in the world: his sax was sophisticated and swinging.
Switching to soprano sax, Temperley gave us a magnificent version of
Jeep's Blues -- a masterpiece of majestic moaning and elegant wailing --
which was only matched in the knock-out stakes by his unaccompanied duet
with tenor saxist Kathy Stobart on There Will Never Be Another You (aka
The Sheep's Song).
Catch Joe and Humph tonight in Edinburgh's Queen's Hall and tomorrow
in Glasgow City Hall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour lead falls -- to 36%</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S lead over the Tories has slipped in the past few weeks, but
they remain a huge 36 points ahead, according to the latest poll.
The party party is down 2.5 points from last month, after suffering
internal rows over Clause 4 and education, in addition to the attack on
their devolution plans led by the Prime Minister.
Labour is now on 59.5%, the Tories on 23.5%, the Liberal Democrats on
13% and others on 4%, according to a Gallup poll for today's's Daily
Telegraph. Asked how they would react to the election of Labour under Mr
Blair, 31% of voters said they ''would be delighted'', 54% said they
''wouldn't mind'' and only 14% said they ''would be dismayed''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power-steering Scottish Chamber Orchestra, Queen's Hall, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONDUCTOR Michael Stern brought a generously proportioned programme to
Edinburgh last night, but it was Nikolai Demidenko who galvanised it
with a high-profile performance of Schumann's Piano Concerto and, as an
encore, an electrifying Erlkonig.
Nobody could accuse Demidenko of lightness of touch, and there were
moments in the first movement of the Schumann when he seemed intent on
disrupting the flow of the music with bouts of heavy expressiveness. But
when he let fly, the effect was startling, especially in so small a
concert hall.
This was power-steering of an exhilarating kind, with passage-work so
vividly articulated and so rhythmically alive that the finale crackled
like Prokofiev.
Earlier there had been Mozart's ''little'' G minor symphony, No 25, in
which the SCO sounded over-tense. But the tensions of Shostakovich's
Chamber Symphony Op 110 -- which, in Rudolf Barshai's arrangement, is an
inflation of his eighth string quartet -- were keenly captured with
strong, clear string sonorities, even if its most memorable moments were
provided by Ruth Crouch's ghostly strands of violin tone in the first
movement.
After this, at the end of a long evening, Kodaly's Galanta Dances
could only seem redundant, though they were played with considerable
verve and with pungent timbres, crisp detail, and the deftest of tempo
changes.
Concert sponsored by Caledonian Bank plc.
The programme will be repeated this evening at the Music Hall,
Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
