<HEADLINE>Ian Wood is top boss</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scottish executives vote on leader characteristics
SIR Ian Wood, one of the few local success stories in the North East's
oil service industry, is considered by his peers to be the best example
of a business leader in Scotland, a survey published today reveals.
Self-made businessman Tom Farmer, whose Kwik-Fit motor repair business
mushroomed from humble beginnings, and Lord Macfarlane of Bearsden,
executive chairman of packaging company Macfarlane Group (Clansman), are
also held in high esteem.
Sir Ian is the driving force behind Aberdeen-based John Wood Group. He
is the epitome of a business leader to nearly 17% of main board
directors in Scotland's top 500 companies.
The survey of more than 100 senior Scottish executives, conducted by
MORI for accountancy major KPMG, revealed that turning visions into
reality (45%) and the ability to motivate (39%) were considered the most
important leadership characteristics.
Meanwhile, Mr Farmer, whose Kwik-Fit chain now has nearly 800 outlets
and employs 5500 people, believes the key to leadership success is to
''make sure you surround yourself with the best people''.
On the thorny issue of executive pay levels, the survey reveals 59% of
Scots believe UK business leaders are well paid.
However, 73% of those interviewed felt the UK was short of good
business leaders, with particular admiration expressed for US captains
of industry. Failure to communicate effectively or to take risks, as
well as a lack of creativity and strong sense of purpose, were seen as
the main shortcomings in the UK business world.
Bosses in Scotland, in line with their counterparts elsewhere in
Britain, rate Virgin's Richard Branson as UK number one, in light of his
innovative approach, ability to motivate, sense of purpose,
communication skills and personality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UK and Irish teams close to agreement</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN COONEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
Dublin
BRITISH and Irish civil servants have moved signicantly closer to
agreement between London and Dublin on future political structures in
the North, according to informed political sources in Dublin last night.
However, the draft text of a Framework Document, or White Paper, will
be subject to political agreement at a ministerial meeting scheduled for
February 14 between Sir Patrick Mayhew, the Secretary of State for
Northern Ireland and Mr Dick Spring, the Irish Republic's Foreign
Minister.
In spite of rapid Ulster Unionist opposition fuelled by a leak in the
Times, ''substantial progress'' was reported to have been made at
yesterday's meeting in the Irish Department of Foreign Affairs.
However, officials last night acknowledged that the final political
decisions by the two Governments would have to be taken in the light of
their assessment of Unionist reactions in Northern Ireland to what is
meant to be a basis for all-party political talks in the Province rather
than a blueprint for Irish unification.
Last night, informed sources told the Herald that a formula will be
put to the two Governments on how the Irish Government intends to modify
its territorial claims on Northern Ireland -- expressed in articles two
and three of the Republic's constitution, and enacted in 1937.
This formula, which will commit the Irish Government to a
constitutional referendum, is regarded as crucial by London to balance
proposals for an all-Ireland executive body and for a devolved
parliamentary assembly in Belfast.
Last night, Irish Prime Minister John Bruton insisted that an
All-Ireland body with executive powers should be an essential part of
the proposals.
Earlier, further pressure on the two Governments to press ahead with
the completion of the framework document came from the Fianna Fail
leader, Bertie Ahern.
Addressing the Irish Association in Dublin Mr Ahern urged the two
Governments to publish the document as early as possible. ''Neither
Government should be deflected in any way from completing the document
in the manner in which they intended,''he said.
The Minister for Social Welfare, Mr Proinsias de Rossa, said he did
not think that the Irish Government should water-down the document
because of the Ulster Unionist objections over the leak. Mr Major's
response to the threat to the Northern Ireland peace process was praised
by Opposition leaders in the Dublin parliament.
Mr Ahern said Mr Major had adopted ''a statesmanlike approach'', and
Mary Harney, head of the Progressive Democrats, said he had reacted
positively.
She added: ''It might have been easier for Mr Major to take a
different approach -- given his domestic political difficulties.''
Meanwhile, Irish President Mary Robinson yesterday emphasised the
importance of maintaining the peace process in Ireland when she
addressed a joint session of the two houses of the Dublin parliament.
She told the Dail and Senate of the 70 million people worldwide who
could claim Irish descent.
''The truest way of cherishing our diaspora is to offer them at all
times the reality of this island as a place of peace where the many
diverse traditions are bound together in tolerance and understanding,''
she said.
Mrs Robinson was making her second joint address to parliament since
being elected president in 1990.
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams yesterday called on the Irish
Government to press London to start all-party talks. He said Irish
Premier John Bruton should ''be putting it to London that London and
Dublin lead the rest of us into all-party talks''.
Unionist opposition to the framework document reflected their desire
to retain the status quo, but there would have to be political and
constitutional change and the talks were needed now, he said.
''The framework document has been two-and-a-half years in the making.
How much longer should we wait, how much longer can we wait? How much
longer will the British delay?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
