<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Task looks stiff for Aragon Ayr</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARAGON Ayr, owned by a group of 35 members, will not lack vocal
support from his big Borders following in the Pat's Jester Morebattle
Hurdle at Kelso today.
Peter Monteith's seven-year-old was a winner six days ago at Ayr but
faces a stiff task in taking on Large Action, who won the Bula Hurdle at
Cheltenham and is second favourite for the Champion Hurdle, as well as
Mrs Mary Reveley's pair, Batabanoo and Surrey Dancer.
Although Aragon Ayr won three times last season and is an improving
type, he is 2st 8lb out of the handicap.
Batabanoo's seven victories include the Fighting Fifth Hurdle at
Newcastle, where he beat Surrey Dancer by three-and-a-half lengths.
The line-up of eight for the first prize of #7000 includes Borders
horses Coqui Lane and the lowly-rated Daphnis -- 5st 10lb out of the
handicap.
The race has been named in honour of Pat's Jester, owned by Kelso
director Geoff Adam. A former Scottish Champion Hurdler and second to
The Fellow in the King George two years ago, Pat's Jester -- winner of
#120,000 -- was retired after having broken down at Wetherby in
December.
Clay County, another Kelso favourite, will be well supported in the
Carlsberg Rutherford Handicap Chase despite carrying top weight. He has
has most to fear from Sherwood's Leotard and Mrs Reveley's triple
course-winner Terrible Gel.
Kelso hosts the season's first hunter chase, in which Norman
Dalgetty's Davy Blake will be a warm favourite to repeat last year's
success.
</TEXT>
