<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wood warns of Irish backlash.  New hero is 'just a rookie'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041901</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RATHER like ourselves, the Irish have been in a state of flux for a
few seasons, and in such times rugby heroes are quickly built up and
knocked down.
Simon Geoghegan may be the current darling of Lansdowne Road. But in
terms of ''world class'' -- a term too often thrown around in sport --
the Irish reckon they've got at least three guys in that category.
Ireland's front row of Nick Popplewell, Keith Wood, and Peter Clohessy
are promoted by some experts to be as good as any other unit in world
rugby. Certainly, they starred in the Barbarians' win over the
Springboks in Dublin last year.
But for Wood, the junior member of that triumvirate, there is still a
lot to prove before they start believing the gossip.
''The idea of us being the best in the world,'' the Garryowen hooker
mused. ''Well, I've heard that and it's nice of people to say it.
''But I still just see myself as a rookie. Twenty caps down the line
I'll be in a position to pass comment and assess where I, and those
around me, stand. Just now, I'm still trying to establish myself.''
The 22-year-old Limerick building society official has been receiving
extensive treatment on a neck injury all week to guarantee him a second
Five Nations' Championship appearance and only his fifth cap.
Following in the footsteps of dad Gordon, who played in the famous
green jersey during the 50s and 60s, Wood Jr learned his trade fast,
growing up quickly Down Under during last summer's Test series against
world champions Australia.
The 20-8 defeat by England a fortnight ago dented Irish pride. But,
says Wood, Scotland may feel the backlash.
''The Five Nations' Championship is still on offer to Ireland,''
believes Wood, even after that defeat. ''Obviously, we now need others
to do us a favour. But there are three games to be won, and we'll be
taking the lessons learned from the England experience into the game
against Scotland.''
Ireland tomorrow will be chasing their first victory in Edinburgh
since 1985, and it is a challenge Wood sees as vital to a much bigger
test this summer.
''We need a booster -- just one match to get us up and going in the
lead up to the World Cup in South Africa. We've spoken about that and we
have identified the game in Edinburgh as the one to win.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
