<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* SOUTH Africa will not support New Zealand proposals to repeal rugby
union's current amateur provisions, according to their chairman.
New Zealand chairman Eddie Tonks claimed last weekend that he favoured
performance-based contracts and added that the NZRFU would argue the
case for professionalism at next month's International Rugby Board
meeting in Bristol.
But the chairman of the South African Rugby Football Union's
disciplinary and amateur status committee, Lex Mpati, said his union
supported the current amateur regulations.
''I foresee the dangers of players striking for better pay,'' he said.
''It's a dangerous precedent and I would argue against that.''
SARFU general manager Arie Oberholzer added: ''We haven't seen New
Zealand's proposals. We think the present system should be changed, but
at the same time there is a need to protect the ethos of the game.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wellcome earnings advance to #738m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WELLCOME, battling to remain out of the clutches of Glaxo, published
annual results at the top end of City expectations yesterday, showing a
19% increase in pre-tax profits to #738m, excluding exceptional items.
Underlying group sales grew by 13% to #2276m and there is a final
dividend of 16p a share, taking the total shareholders' payment for the
year to 30.4p. A combination of cost efficiency and volume growth,
rather than price rises, was behind the increase in operating margin
from 29.5% to a record 31.5%.
Commenting on the figures John Robb, Wellcome's chairman and chief
executive, said: ''These record-breaking results for 1994 show in very
clear terms the strength of Wellcome's business and prospects''.
The results were originally scheduled for 1 March but were brought
forward to reinforce Wellcome's claim that Glaxo is trying to buy a
growth company on the cheap. Sales growth was achieved in all geographic
territories but government healthcare reforms limited growth in Europe.
Within the drug portfolio, sales of its best-selling drug Zovirax,
used to treat herpes, continued to grow. In the 12 months to December
1994, Zovirax sales were 16% higher at #858m, with a notably strong
performance in Japan.
However, Retrovir, marketed as AZT and used in the treatment of HIV
infection, showed a drop of 7% to #206m. This was attributed to lower
usage by asymptomatic patients.
Spending on research and development rose by 5% to #346m. The company
is focusing on three therapeutic areas: antiviral, central nervous
system, and oncology. During the course of 1994, filings in 27 countries
were made for Valtrex, the successor product to Zovirax for the
treatment of shingles.
The first approvals for this were granted last month in the UK and
Ireland. Wellcome's anti-depressant drug Wellbutrin is being clinically
tested as a product to help people stop smoking. The studies are
expected to be completed by April 1995.
Wellcome's balance sheet strengthened considerably during the year
with net cash rising by #163m to #781m.
Now that Wellcome's results have been published, potential white
knights may emerge from the shadows but the City is not betting on it.
Earlier this week, Hoechst, the big German chemical and pharmaceutical
group, appeared to rule itself out. This followed news that it was close
to securing a controlling stake in Marion Merrill Dow in the US.
Sandoz, the Swiss pharmaceuticals, nutrition and chemicals group, is
out of the bidding and so Wellcome's hopes of a rescue rest in America
with such companies as Bristol Myers-Squibb, Johnson and Johnson, and
Merck. A Wellcome spokesman confirmed that a rival bidder was actively
being sought. ''Our directors and advisers are travelling extensively,''
he said.
Glaxo, currently bidding #9000m for Wellcome, is expected to dispatch
its final offer document next week along with half-year results brought
forward from February 16.
Responding to the Wellcome announcement, Sir Richard Sykes, chief
executive of Glaxo, said the commercial logic of his company's bid was
still clear.
He reiterated his claim that key success factors going forward in the
pharmaceutical industry included a strong position in a consolidating
global industry, critical mass in research and development, and an
infrastructure and resources to maximise product efficiency and ensure
rapid penetration of products on an international scale.
''We remain convinced that a merged Glaxo Wellcome is the right way
forward to meet the challenges of a rapidly changing environment in the
pharmaceutical industry and to maintain a British company at the
forefront of this market,'' said Sir Richard.
Time does appear to be running out for Wellcome as an independent
entity. City analysts believe that the price Glaxo has agreed to pay for
Wellcome is probably too high for any US firm to beat.
Glaxo looks likely to win the battle for Wellcome although it may have
to pay more money to secure a recommendation from the board.
Yesterday Wellcome added 7p to 1005p while Glaxo gained 20p to 646p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Theatre's new season</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>43</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041904</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOW in its 50th anniversary year, the Citizens' Theatre across the
Clyde springs into action from February to May with a packed programme
encompassing everything from Jacobean tragedy to the effects of the
Holocaust on the new Europe.
Music and comedy play their necessary parts in the overall scheme of
things and Scotland's rival cities of Edinburgh and Glasgow enjoy their
own cameos, courtesy of The Citizens' Company. Thomas Middleton, Harold
Pinter and Virginia Woolf have their words made flesh while tear-jerking
Terry Neason and thought-provoking Wildcat leap into performance with
brand-new productions. But who is Sir Christopher Vainwean?
The new season opens with Thomas Middleton's powerful play of lust,
incest, jealousy, and power politics from a bygone age, Women Beware
from February 3 to 25 in the main theatre. With a Citizens' company
which includes rising star Anne Lambton, Gerard McArthur in Strindberg's
The Father last year and Anne Myatt from lochside TV soap Take The High
Road, this taut tale of Jacobean jiggery pokery is a key production in
every sense.
It will certainly unlock a voucher entitling patrons to a free ticket
for any one of the five Citizens' company productions later in the
season providing two tickets, either #6 or #2 have been purchased. Phone
the Box Office on 0141 429 0022 to reserve seats.
Citizens' stalwarts Giles Havergal, Robert David MacDonald and Philip
Prowse contribute to what promises to be one of the theatre's most
exciting seasons in its history. Philip Prowse has directed and designed
Women Beware, Giles Havergal has adapted and will direct The Citizens'
Company production of Jeff Torrington's award-winning Glasgow novel
Swing Hammer Swing from March 10 until April 1 and Robert David
MacDonald has written and will direct the company's persons unknown with
a haunting Casper Hauser theme from May 3 to 20.
Other Citizens' company productions are the acclaimed Edinburgh drugs
drama Train Spotting from February 23 until March 18, Harold Pinter's
incisive comedy of sexual manners Betrayal from March 30 until April 22
and Fyodor Dostoevsky's The Double from March 29 until April 22.
Among the visiting companies in the months ahead are 7:84 Theatre
Company Scotland in Born Guilty which explores the impact of the Second
World War on the new Europeans from April 27 until May 13 and Wildcat in
the two Davys -- Anderson and MacLennan's musical political farce,
Bedfellows, from April 26 until May 13.
Comic character Sir Christopher Vainwean bears a fleeting resemblance
to what some crossword addicts might loosely describe as ''a weel kent
Scots Tory MP of fair pedigree not in the nick''. The ayes have it, full
houses all round.
</TEXT>
