<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Brouzet fears that 'le crunch' could become 'le brawl'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ENGLAND v FRANCE
RECALLED France lock Olivier Brouzet fears tomorrow's Five Nations'
Championship match with England at Twickenham could turn into a brawl.
''There are many things I don't like in English rugby, starting with
their aggressive style based on rucking,'' said Brouzet, brought back
for Olivier Merle, who was dropped for butting Wales prop Ricky Evans in
Paris last month.
''I don't know if they will provoke us or if they will play rugby. It
will be physically tough, but we will not bow.''
The Merle incident sparked a number of inflammatory articles in the
English press and Brouzet hopes they will not affect tomorrow's match,
already dubbed ''le crunch'' as a possible decider for the Five Nations'
title.
Brouzet, 23, who wins his third cap on Saturday, is not worried at the
prospect of facing one of the toughest packs in the world.
''I don't know what the atmosphere will be like on the pitch,'' he
said. ''But after colliding with two or three English players in the
first three minutes, I will get an idea.''
Brouzet was a member of the French team who had a historic 2-0 series
winover New Zealand last year, but played only four minutes of Test
rugby as a replacement.
''It was a bit frustrating, but I will never forget those four
minutes,'' he said. ''I know I was called up this time because Merle was
dropped, but I want to prove what I'm really worth. It's not easy to win
a place in the team.''
England captain Will Carling refused, as always, to become involved in
the now-routine war of words that precedes Anglo-French matches.
''France are the side that I admire most and my respect has increased
since they won a Test series in New Zealand last year.
''That was a great achievement and I simply don't go along with these
anti-French feelings. In the last couple of fixtures their discipline
has been very strong, but their magic bothers me.
''We see them as the side to beat, because we have so much admiration
and respect for them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
