<DOCID>GH950203-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dons go Dutch</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND manager Craig Brown yesterday praised Aberdeen for pioneering
a Dutch-style youth programme to improve standards.
He said that the initiative by the Pittodrie club, which clinched a
major sponsorship deal with Hydro-Electric, was an example other clubs
must follow.
Brown said: ''Involving youngsters in smaller-sided games is the way
to develop skills.''
Aberdeen have set up a network of 113 coaches throughout the
north-east to operate the seven-a-side football programme and already
1400 youngsters are involved.
Dons manager Willie Miller said: ''The concept comes from Holland
where some truly magnificent players have been produced.''
</TEXT>
