<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ayr fail to halt Hawkes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>46</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041907</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ayr 5, GHK 17.
ON A rain-lashed and sodden Millbrae pitch, both sides contrived to
serve up a remarkably entertaining first half, GHK's surety in the pass
and their ability to mop up any aerial threat from Ayr giving them the
edge.
A George Breckenridge penalty gave the visitors the lead in the
seventh minute but the threats to Ayr's line foundered on solid defence
until 31 minutes, when Gerry Hawkes was impeded as he went for a
delicate Bassi chip to the line. Breckenridge converted the resultant
penalty try.
It was Hawkes, again running back a loose clearance, who set up the
move which led to Bassi, Sanderson, and Hirini putting Brown clear to
give Dom Mellor the scoring pass. Breckenridge's conversion took the
visitors to a 17-0 half-time lead.
The elements eased in the second half, but there was no more scoring,
despite the efforts of Andy Kerr and Jason Barbarich in the lineout and
some powerful Ayr scrummaging, until replacement Craig Dunlop shot
through the GHK midfield defence to put Stewart Magorian in for a
well-earned try. Etheridge's kick was wide.
</TEXT>
