<HEADLINE>Olonga earns infamy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041909</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ZIMBABWE teenager Henry Olonga became the first bowler for more than
30 years to be called for throwing in a Test match on the third day of
the first Test against Pakistan.
Olonga, the first black cricketer to play for his country, is only the
sixth specialist bowler to be called for ''chucking'' and the first
since Australian paceman Ian Meckiff against South Africa in 1963.
The 18-year-old, who was called four times while playing for a
President's XI against the tourists last weekend, was no-balled once in
his fifth over yesterday morning.
That was one of the few low points for Zimbabwe as their bowlers, even
without Olonga, who spent a lengthy period off the field with a side
strain, reduced Pakistan to 151 for six at one stage.
A seventh-wicket stand of 120 between Ijaz Ahmed and Inzamam-ul-Haq
took them to 271 for seven at the close, but they still need 74 to avoid
the follow-on.
