<DOCNO>GH950203-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murray Johnstone purchase</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>COLIN MCSEVENY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041911</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MURRAY Johnstone has underlined its growing commitment to the venture
capital sector with the purchase of SUMIT Equity Ventures, a small
Birmingham-based fund management company.
No financial details were released about the transaction though Murray
Johnstone is thought to have paid just under #500,000 for SEV which
manages the SUMIT investment trust and two venture capital funds.
SEV holds about #40m in funds under management and its absorption will
take the funds of Murray Johnstone Private Equity, the group's
specialist sector subsidiary, up to around #240m.
The acquisition also adds a final touch to the UK-wide network of MJPE
with Birmingham being added to its existing offices in Glasgow,
Manchester, and London.
''We are confident that they will complement our expanding venture
capital business with their important Birmingham presence,'' Murray
Johnstone's David MacLellan said yesterday.
The Glasgow-based company has built up a good reputation for venture
capital management and the latest acquisition takes Mr McLellan's
specialist managers team up to 20-strong.
SUMIT's injection of business capacity and deal flow will also boost
Murray Johnstone's plans for the imminent launch of a venture capital
trust under the terms of legislation being debated in the wake of the
last Budget.
In the past two years alone Murray Johnstone, which has #4500m under
management overall, took over the venture capital portfolio of Allied
Irish Bank and launched a #40m buy-out fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Air UK profits soar to #2.65m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041912</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INDEPENDENT airline Air UK increased pre-tax trading profits from a
lowly #15,000 to #2.65m in 1994, prompting an unprecedented public
showing of the private company's results.
Stansted-based Air UK, which flies out of Glasgow, Edinburgh, and
Aberdeen, increased its passenger revenue by 20% to #206.1m during the
year to end-December.
An increase of 28% took the number of Air UK customers passing through
Stansted to one million for the first time, with new routes and more
frequent flights producing economies of scale.
The airline, which recorded a 19% increase in passengers on its
Amsterdam flights to more than 700,000, achieved respective increases of
6% and 20% on its flights from Scotland to Gatwick and Stansted. It
carried a total of 2.6 million passengers.
However, managing director Andrew Gray, who put the profits surge down
to volume growth and cost control, pointed out the pre-tax return was
still only #1 per passenger.
The airline, formed in 1980 through a merger of Air Anglia, British
Island Airways, Air West and Air Wales, employs more than 500 people in
its Scottish operations. Air UK Group is 85% owned by British Air
Transport Holdings, with Dutch partner KLM holding a 14.9% stake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kulik skates away with title</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>47</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ILYA Kulik soared to the European men's figure skating title on his
first attempt with a sensational display of nine triple jumps in
Dortmund last night.
Though two were slightly flawed, the Moscow sports student confirmed
the immense promise he showed when he beat a hugely talented field in
the short programme on Wednesday.
Kulik, who won the world junior title two months ago, became only the
second skater outside the pairs since the second world war to capture a
European title on his first attempt.
The first was 1993 champion, Ukraine's Dmitry Dmitrenko, who was
seventh yesterday.
Outstanding though he was, Kulik was surpassed on the night by Olympic
champion Alexei Urmanov, his Russian compatriot, who leaped from sixth
place before the final to snatch the silver medal with a perfect score.
Ukrainian Viacheslav Zagorodniuk secured the bronze medal with
Frenchman Philippe Candeloro, second in the world last year, fourth
after a 'Godfather' routine marred by two jumping mistakes.
Meanwhile, Natalia Mishkutienok and Artur Dmitriev, the 1992 Russian
Olympic pairs champions, have decided to split up.
They also won the 1991 and 1992 European and world titles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
