<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Branson gets Delta deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RICHARD Branson has finally secured the official go-ahead for his deal
with Delta Airlines of the US which secures the position of his Virgin
Atlantic Airways in the key transatlantic market.
Virgin will receive revenue of about $150m a year from Delta
bulk-buying a fixed proportion of Virgin's seats for resale in the US.
Mr Branson said the approval from the US Department of Transportation
was so important that it ''basically guarantees Virgin's future.''
''It gives Virgin all the benefits of a big airline without losing any
of the benefits of being a small airline,'' he declared.
The deal will feed passengers from around 400 US cities on to Virgin's
transatlantic flights. A link of the sort negotiated with Delta was
vital to maintain a competitive position. Virgin's arch enemy, British
Airways, has a hub and spoke arrangement with USAir, though
unfortunately for BA the latter is losing money heavily.
The agreement was actually signed last April but the official green
light was held back while the US Department of Transportation put
pressure on the UK Government to give American airlines greater access
to Heathrow.
</TEXT>
