<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Square dasher</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>ROAD TESTS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041916</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ross Finlay finds old virtues in the Volvo 960
THERE are cars which can get you into tight corners, and other cars
which can get you out of them. It is unusual to find a big saloon which
will do both, at least in terms of manoeuvring in confined spaces. At
home, when driving a vehicle into my parking area and turning to face
again towards the road, I have found many cars which simply cannot make
it in a single three-point turn.
This particular movement has shown me what a rotten turning circle
most 4x4s have. Large-size saloons and estates usually need at least one
extra ''cut'', and it is surprising that some quite compact hatchbacks
cannot manage it either. On the other hand, one of the longest cars I
have manoeuvred there recently -- a Volvo 960 -- wheeched round easily.
I have never understood why nobody else has followed Volvo's lead in
providing its substantially proportioned cars with such excellent
turning circles.
The 960 is the biggest Volvo, and an older basic design than the
highly regarded 850. Some subtle restyling at the front end of the
latest version has taken away the previous massive look, but there is no
doubt, from any angle, that the 960 is a solid, upright and bulky piece
of work. It still struggles against wind resistance and wind noise.
Inside it is roomy without being as well packaged as the 850. As
always, though, you can stow plenty of luggage in that generous Volvo
boot. The interior stylists are cagily bringing the 960 ever so closer
to mid-1990s ideas, but I wish they would go further faster, and get rid
of the angularity which, while it may match the general exterior theme,
does make the 960, from the inside, look rather clumsy.
The 2.5-litre GLE I was driving was fitted with the splendid new
engine, a reduced-size version of the full three-litre six-cylinder.
This is a 170bhp 24-valve design which has first-class throttle
response, and a level of refinement which is not just the best Volvo has
achieved. It puts this 960 level with the best of its opposition for
smooth running and flexibility.
I might well go for the extra-cost four-speed automatic transmission,
rather than the five-speed manual which still calls for rather ponderous
movements, but the manual version puts this heavy car through its paces
well. It sprints to 60mph in just over nine seconds, and tops out at a
likely test-track maximum around 125mph. Official fuel returns for the
manual car are about 35mpg at 56mph, 29 at 75 and down to 19mpg around
town.
The GLE stands in the showroom at #22,495, while the price range for
these 2.5-litre saloons runs from #19,500 to #23,795. Volvo has recently
changed the way it prices and specifies its cars. While there are four
equipment levels in this range, all with clearly defined attractions, a
long list of extra-cost options and upgrades is also in the catalogue.
The biggest Volvos have never been the most agile, but front and rear
suspension details have been substantially modified. I thought that body
roll was much reduced, that cornering grip was really good, and that the
960 coped better than previously with mid-corner bumps. However, the
much firmer suspension does reduce the ride quality on ill-maintained
urban roads.
It remains a bulky-feeling car on the swerves, and a sports-handling
contest between the 960 and the 850 would be no real contest at all. Of
course, the 960 is bought as an executive rather than sports saloon.
Basically, the 960 is a very secure feeling car, not just in its safe
handling but also in the amount of engineering which has gone into the
robustness of its structure. The brakes are also powerful and
progressive.
In other words, all the old Volvo features are there, enhanced by an
inspired engine design. Some critics mark down the 960 because it feels
less lively at speed than its direct German rivals, but those familiar
Volvo virtues still have their own special appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>BSkyB in link with Reuters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BSKYB has contracted out its news-gathering to Reuters, the
international news agency in a deal which is expected to yield
significant savings for the satellite broadcaster.
Reuters will supply and manage UK and global news gathering for the
24-hour Sky News channel, though the latter will retain editorial
control. Reuters will also produce several programmes tailor-made for
Sky News.
No value was put on the deal but analysts predicted savings for BSkyB
in its #27m operating costs of Sky News, with one suggesting around #7m.
It will also mean more resources for Reuters. Maintaining correspondents
around the world is an expensive exercise.
The company has been supplying news on a more limited basis since Sky
News began five years ago and its chief executive Mark Wood commented:
''This agreement will lead to a significant increase in the
news-gathering resources we now commit to Sky News and provides a new
opportunity for us to develop our programme-making expertise.''
Reuters has more than 70 bureaux worldwide, providing coverage for 650
broadcasters in 80 countries, while Sky News can be seen by 70 million
people in four million homes in the UK and 19 million in Europe.
''Sky News is recognised internationally for the high quality of its
news and current affairs programming,'' said chief executive Sam
Chisholm. ''This strength coupled with Reuters' enormous international
infrastructure and facilities, will provide a platform for the global
expansion of Sky News.''
BSkyB is 40% owned by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, with Pearson
having 14% and Granada 11%. A deal with Reuters for Sky News has been
considered likely following a similar agreement with another company in
the Murdoch empire, Fox Broadcasting. The Murdoch Asian satellite
broadcaster Star TV may well follow.
Reuters is keen to do ''as many deals with as many different people as
possible'', according to its TV director David Kogan.
The latest news helped both shares, with BSkyB up 2[1/2]p at 258p and
Reuters 1[1/2]p firmer at 453[1/2]p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000048</DOCNO>
