<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coltart marches on as . . . Spotlight switches to Lawrie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>44</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041918</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Madeira
THE centre of attention, so far as the Scottish challenge for the
Madeira Island Open was concerned, shifted to Paul Lawrie yesterday when
he led the contingent of eight with a score of 68, four under par, after
the first round played mainly in bright, cool, and sometimes breezy
weather.
Andrew Coltart, who had a vintage 1994, and Brian Marchbank, who
decidedly did not, were on 69 and Brian Barnes, approaching his golfing
seniority with every evidence of relish, was satisfied with 71, also
below par. The four other Scots were all over par leaving them to
contemplate a harder struggle to survive the cut.
Andrew Sherborne looked likely to lead on his own when he reached the
sixteenth six under par. But bogeys at the last two holes bestowed the
lead on the 32-year-old Spaniard Santiago Luna, without a victory in 11
seasons on the European Tour.
Lawrie, who holed in one during the tournament last year, returned
with enthusiasm renewed after having slipped some 20 places down the
order of merit. After a seven week lay-off, during which he had keyhole
surgery to allow him to straighten his right knee, he missed the cut in
Dubai, but only by a stroke.
Having turned in the par of 36, Lawrie, soon to be a father for the
first time, made his score with four successive birdies from there.
Coltart's 69, his best score in seven rounds over the 6606-yard
precipitous course high above the Atlantic Ocean, beat Gordon Brand Jr,
his World Cup partner and in his company again, by four strokes. The
four long holes did them no favours, for both made a birdie at only one
of them.
Marchbank, who almost lost his card last autumn after a year of dismal
form, returned to the fray refreshed enough to turn in 33, three under,
and hold that figure solidly over the inward half. For his part, Barnes
looked as relieved to be off the course after five hours on it as with
his score.
Of the others who bettered 70, probably the most gratified was the
39-year-old American Bill Malley. He almost turned a nostalgic
expedition into a plundering experience when he returned to the
birthplace of his maternal grandparents. The 68 was a modest return
after he had played his first nine holes in 31, five under.
