<HEADLINE>Anderson makes a good marriage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG ECONOMICS EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041919</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANDERSON Group, the Motherwell-based mining equipment specialist, has
been sold by its parent, the Charter group, to a private US company,
Marmon, as part of a $46m cash deal.
The move to Chicago-based Marmon, which has significant mining
equipment interests already, was described by Anderson's chief executive
Alasdair MacLauchlan as ''an excellent marriage'' and good news for the
group's 800 employees, 500 of whom are based in Scotland.
Anderson has been through a tough time, because of the contraction and
rationalisation of the UK coal industry. But there is, Mr MacLauchlan
points out, no product overlap with Marmon's existing mining interests.
Having an American parent should give Anderson better access to the
near billion-tonne-a-year US market for mined coal. Equally Anderson's
existing subsidiaries in Australia and South Africa, and its fledgling
presence in Poland, will give Marmon's coal-mining subsidiary, Long
Airdox, valuable exposure in new overseas coal markets.
''I believe that, of all the companies you could have chosen for
Anderson to link up with, this has to be one of the best,'' added Mr
MacLauchlan, although he did admit that employees would be feeling the
same sense of uncertainty which accompanies any such change of
ownership.
The deal takes Charter, which acquired what was Anderson Strathclyde
in the early 1980s, out of the coal sector altogether. ''We have decided
our future doesn't lie in coal,'' a spokeswoman said.
Marmon, a diversified group with sales of around $5000m and interests
in transport equipment, distribution, and minerals as well as coal
equipment, has, by contrast, decided to play an active role in the
global rationalisation of the coal sector.
It recently bought another mining equipment business, Becorit, in the
English Midlands, from NEI. Anderson is being sold along with the
National Mine Service Company, which distributes and services mining
equipment.
The assets and liabilities being sold had a net book value last March
of #49.8m. Operating profits in the year to last March were #1.9m,
representing less than 4% of Charter's overall pre-tax profits.
Almost all of Anderson Group's Scottish operations are consolidated at
Motherwell. There is a small satellite operation still in Bridgeton,
making idlers and rollers for conveyor systems, employing 16 people. The
main Motherwell plant concentrates on new mining machines and
refurbishing existing cutting equipment for the UK coal-mining industry.
There is also a service facility in Sheffield.
Anderson's Australian and South African subsidiaries are complemented
by a Pittsburgh-based arm in the US, which manufactures hydraulic
equipment and repairs and rebuilds mining machines.
Currently the UK accounts for less than half Anderson's sales, with
American buyers taking up to a third of the new machines the group
makes. Long Airdox is based in West Virginia.
</TEXT>
