<DOCNO>GH950203-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Java Trust value falls</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041920</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH Java Trust, the only UK investment trust specialising in the
Indonesian market, saw its value drop by almost one-third as the local
stock market was hit by a range of factors.
Rising interest rates, labour unrest, high inflation, and financial
scandals all conspired to depress the once-booming Djakarta exchange
which fell by 23% in local currency terms last year.
The decline, however, was magnified by a weaker rupiah and in sterling
terms the local market virtually mirrored the 30.7% decline in Java's
net asset value per share to 42.5p.
Run by Edinburgh Fund Managers, the #13m trust generated #285,000 in
revenue, leaving a slight shortfall after #325,000 expenses were taken
into account.
Loss per share thus widened over the year from just under 0.1p to
0.27p, though the managers rightly pointed out that the trust is geared
towards capital growth rather than income. As with previous years, no
dividend is to be paid.
Java favours consumer stocks because they are non-cyclical and
infrastructure-related companies which stand to benefit from Indonesia's
on-going development.
Looking on the positive side, the managers said the latest government
budget showed solid fiscal discipline in order to encourage the private
sector and underlying growth in corporate earnings were running at 30%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ian Adam at Salvesen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041921</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTIAN Salvesen, the power plant hire to food processing and
distribution group, has appointed Ian Adam as finance director.
As previously announced, Brian Fidler, the current finance director,
is due to retire from the company on April 7.
Mr Adam, 51, a chartered accountant, has spent the majority of his
career with accountancy firm Price Waterhouse.
Salvesen chief executive Dr Chris Masters said that Mr Adam is highly
regarded in Scotland. He added that he was was responsible for building
up Price Waterhouse into the most successful of the major accountancy
firm.
The floods in Holland and Germany are not having a major impact upon
the group although there hjve been staff problems with employees unable
to get to work.
</TEXT>
