<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wholecrop wheat catching on as alternative for winter feed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHOLECROP wheat handled in a similar fashion to grass silage is fast
catching on as a cost effective alternative to straight grass as a
winter feed judging from the reaction of almost 200 farmers who
yesterday attended a conference in Stirling.
The concept of harvesting a cereal crop prior to full ripening is not
new but it is only during the last five years that the idea of using
wheat as a major constituent of the rations for dairy cattle has caught
on.
Basically the wheat can be harvested while it is primarily green with
a dry matter of around 40% and conserved like silage or alternatively
left until it becomes almost yellow with a dry matter approaching 60%.
With the latter option urea has to be applied.
Detailing the benefits nutritionist David Jacklin commented: ''It's
reliable in cold areas. It's flexible with only one harvest while the
nutritional benefits include higher dry matter intake and improvement in
milk production.''
The financial aspect was covered by John Bax of the SAC's grassland
and ruminant department at the Crichton Royal Farm at Dumfries. Mr Bax
said: ''The whole business of making grass silage is becoming extremely
expensive. For example you might conserve 10 tonnes of material but
actually only feed eight. And it is now costing #1.80 per tonne for dry
matter to make grass silage whereas using wholecrop wheat the figure is
nearer #50 and if arable aid payments can be included another #10-#15
can be knocked off that.''
Costings from SAC show that grass comes out as the most expensive
winter fodder with a total of #637 per hectare while wholecrop wheat
comes in at #602 with maize at #562.
The practical advantages of wholecrop have, however, not been
demonstrated conclusively in trials where yield improvements from dairy
cows have so far not been statistically conclusive.
Nonetheless John Owen, who farms 900 acres with 600 cattle near
Kirkintilloch is totally convinced that mixing grass silage and
wholecrop wheat is mthe right recipe.
He said: ''I know there are no strong proven advantages but you get a
feel that something is right. Inevitably it feeds better than it
analyses and besides one crop of this is a lot easier to harvest than
two or three crops of grass in our climate.''
Significantly almost every dairy farmer at the conference who has used
wholecrop cereals reported a marked improvement in herd health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Concern over cash aid for homeless</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL CAVEN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEARS were voiced yesterday that the Government was attempting to
ditch its long-standing obligation towards providing vital funding and
facilities to help the growing numbers of Scottish homeless.
If the plan to deny aid to the homeless succeeded, it was claimed,
even more people, particularly the young, would end up begging on the
streets.
Under current law, the Government must provide or fund facilities for
the homeless. However, Mr Ian Blackwood, vice president of the National
Union of Civil and Public Servants, said attempts were being made to
slip a clause through Parliament which would leave this to the Social
Security Minister's discretion.
Campaigners for the homeless argued that such a move would spell
disaster and was liable to be used to attack the ''weakest in society''.
Mr Blackwood said: ''Given this Government's scandalous attitude to
the homelessness problem, it is essential that we get this pernicious
clause amended to retain the responsibility upon the Minister to fund
services to the single homeless.''
His comments came ahead of a conference in Edinburgh today at which a
major campaign will be launched to protect services for single homeless
people. The fight is being spearheaded by trade unionists, local
authorities, and MPs who are united in outrage over a Government plan to
axe the resettlement unit at Bishopbriggs next year.
The unit is unique in Scotland and, in the past 30 years, has provided
accommodation for nearly 80 men each night who, in most circumstances,
would otherwise sleep rough.
Ms Angela Palmer, vice-president of the NUCPS, said: ''This decision
proves that this Government do not care about homeless people and are
quite prepared to condemn them to the scrapheap. We have written
promises from John Major -- all of which have been broken by this
heartless decision.''
Mr Michael Donohoe, housing convener of Strathkelvin District Council,
said his authority had drawn up proposals which would save the unit and
also millions of pounds of taxpayers' money.
</TEXT>
