<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Suckler Cow Scheme due</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041924</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRODUCERS who are eligible to apply for quota from the national
reserve under the Suckler Cow Premium Scheme must return completed forms
by March 3, according to the Scottish Office Agriculture Department.
Those who qualify for the 1994 scheme year include farmers whose
particip-ation in an environmental scheme in the base year -- 1992 -
resulted in a reduction in numbers that year.
Other categories are:- a producer taking over land from a tenant who
has taken the quota with him; those entering an ''arable reversion''
scheme; newcomers to farming; a producer entering an Organic Aid scheme;
first-time claimants under the 1994 scheme and producers taking over
land formerly used for suckler cow production but temporarily under
non-agricultural use.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crofers Union are annoyed at funding</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Crofters Union have expressed concern over the level of
funding allocated to the newly announced crofting township development
scheme funded by the Scottish Office as part of the EC Objective One
programme. SCU acting president Alistair MacIver said: ''Objective One
status was granted to the Highlands and Islands on the basis of remote
and fragile rural areas lagging behind in economic terms. These are the
crofting areas. It seems incongruous that #20m goes into agricultural
business improvement while only a small fraction -- some 3% -- goes into
the crofting township development scheme.
</TEXT>
