<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Prepare yourself for tough times</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS, FARMING EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH farmers, whose incomes were reported on Tuesday to have
reached a ten-year high, have been warned not to be lulled into
believing that the good times will last for ever.
The cautionary advice came from Mr Sean Rickard, former chief
economist with the national Farmers' Union of England and Wales, and a
member of UK farm minister William Waldegrave's ''think-tank'' on the
future of agriculture following CAP reform.
''The reason that incomes are high today is because of the 20%
devaluation of the pound in 1992 along with zero inflation,'' he told a
standing-room only meeting organised by the North-East of Scotland Farm
Management Association.
''The great mistake you could make is to believe that all the
pressures involved in the build up to 1992 have been ameliorated,'' he
said. ''They have not gone away -- just been glossed over.''
His advice to farmers was to recognise that the pre-1992 pressures
could return in a few years and there was now no mechanism in the Common
Agricultural Policy system to raise prices or payments to farmers. ''If
inflation takes off in this country you are in trouble. If you intend to
farm and believe you have a future in farming you must use your profits
to make your businesses more efficient.
''Prepare yourself for a tougher future,'' he warned. ''If I am wrong,
you will do even better. If I am right, and you have not prepared
yourself -- goodbye.''
Looking at the future for the CAP Mr Rickard said that as a result of
the GATT agreement the European Union would be forced to reduce steadily
the amount of protection it gave to farming. Current protection was at
the rate of 40% above ruling market prices.
That same 40% tariff figure had applied to industry in general when
GATT began in 1947. The level of protection was now down to three per
cent and a similar scenario could apply to farming, he suggested.
''There is a new mood abroad which says that markets have to be more
open because that is the way other parts of the world will develop.
Agriculture will be subject to the same pressures that have fallen on
other sectors.'' There was, he said, a fundamental conflict looming,
with the agriculture industry increasingly dependent on public funds and
politicians beginning to pay more and more attention to what these funds
were spent on.
Further conflicts would arise with the eastwards expansion of the EU,
he forecast. Past experience suggested that no action would be taken to
deal with such pressures until crisis point was reached. The most
favoured solution at present appeared to be ''de-coupling'' which would
involve prices being determined by the market and farmers being
compensated for income loss by direct payments. The problem with that
solution was that it would put severe strains on the agriculture budget.
National Farmers' Union of Scotland president John Ross told the
meeting that he did not subscribe to Mr Rickards ''very gloomy picture''
on the survival of the CAP. He pointed out that forecasts could be
wrong.
''We were told that 15% set-aside would not do the job in controlling
cereal output but in fact we now discover that 12% will actually balance
supply and demand in Europe in the short term. We were given dire
warnings about a substantial increase in stickpiles of beef -- and the
reverse has been the case.''
The major difference between industry and farming was that food was an
absolute basic, he said. That was why in the last round of GATT
negotiations a nine-year peace clause had been accepted, allowing
Europeam agriculture to be subsidised provided it did not over produce.
The NFUS supported the principles of the CAP reform, taking into account
the needs of farmers, consumers and the countryside.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Risking the wrath of mortgage payers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ken Smith examines why the Chancellor is prepared to inflict some pain
on his natural allies, homeowners and industrialists, for the longer
term aim of low inflation.
THE collective groans could be heard across the housing estates of
Scotland last night as the news of the third interest rate rise in six
months sank in.
If the Conservatives appeal to the property-owning classes as their
natural supporters, they have a funny way of showing their appreciation,
was the obvious reaction.
Assuming the Chancellor is not involved in a particularly complicated
political suicide, why is he risking the wrath of potential voters by
pushing up interest rates?
First, it is not automatic that building society rates will follow the
half per cent increase in bank base rates announced yesterday. Building
societies say they are sensitive to the housing market being subdued,
and will resist a rise as long as possible. But even if there is an
increase in the next few weeks, mortgage payers appear to have selective
memory loss, forgetting they are still paying far less than even just a
few years ago.
The mortgage base rate, which is higher than the bank base rate, stood
at 8.1% at the end of 1994. Certainly it is higher than the 7.7% in
place for the most part of last year, but that figure is far lower than
people have experienced for years. As recently as the end of 1992 it was
in double figures, and in fact peaked at 15.4% in only April 1990 --
nearly double the current rate.
Putting it in financial terms, mortgage payers with the Nationwide
will be repaying #365.40 a month on a #50,000 mortgage from March -- due
to the last interest rate rise. But in March 1990, the monthly figure
was #565.07, so they are still some #200 a month better off, although
no-one will believe it.
It is not just houseowners who are complaining, however. The
Government's natural allies at the Confederation of British Industry say
they do not believe the rise is justified. But they will concede it is a
fine judgment. An increase in American interest rates would have put
pressure on the pound, and that may have forced the Chancellor's hand.
Although business leaders may disagree with the Chancellor's move,
they do not disagree with his motives of keeping inflation down.
Industrialists say they do not wish to return to inflationary days when
wage increases pushed up prices, which pushed up wages, and which
latterly made business uncompetitive with foreign rivals.
The CBI's own most recent industrial trends survey revealed that
manufacturers were anticipating an increase in unit costs, which would
have fed through from the wholesaler to the retailer, and increased
inflation. Pushing up interest rates will mean a restriction on money in
circulation, people will think twice about borrowing to buy goods, and
retailers, no matter how hard pushed they are, will have to think again
about putting up prices.
So it will be tough on houseowners, tough on retailers. Is it all
worth it then? Is inflation such a bogey?
Industrialists say that if inflation remains low, they can feel more
confident about investing in the long term as there will be more price
stability. More investment will mean more goods produced at competitive
prices, and benefits for the economy. It is following the German example
of low inflation which helped their industries so much in the eighties.
While too high an interest rate will force companies to cut back,
small half-per-cent rises should not stall investment plans.
As Lex Gold, director of the CBI Scotland, put it: ''What business
wants, above everything else, is stability. We don't want to return to
boom or bust.''
Scotland, it can be argued, will suffer less from interest rate rises
than elsewhere. Both corporate and personal debt is lower than the
average in England, so while the rate of economic growth may be slowed
by the latest interest rate rise, it should not be damaged.
The Scottish National Party will argue that the medicine we are all
having to swallow has more to do with inflationary pressures in the
South-east, and while taking medicine is bad enough, having to take it
when you're not the patient leaves an even more bitter taste in the
mouth.
Ultimately there will be some gainers, in that savers, particularly
pensioners living on their investments, will receive a slightly better
return for their money. But again, if mortgage-payers have forgotten the
days of high interest rates, savers have not. Any slight increase in
savings returns will not console them when they think of the heady days
of 15% returns.
So while the Chancellor believes he is acting for the good of the
country, he gets little thanks for it. Indeed the feel-good factor
everyone talks about as being missing, was largely dependent upon
inflation pushing up house prices and wages. Low inflation means little
or no wage rises.
While it may be judged good for the country, the increase will do
little for the Chancellor in the popularity stakes. But then, if he
wanted to be popular, he wouldn't have become a politician, would he?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Potato growers hanging back</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041928</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POTATO growers remained reluctant to clear stores last week as higher
prices appeared inevitable. The Potato Marketing Board said only poor,
unattractive samples were trading below #200 a tonne. Most average
grades were between #220 and #270 a tonne. Maris Piper for frying went
as high as #310 and good-sized baking potatoes reached #400.
</TEXT>
