<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dirty play in patriot games</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041929</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN Ireland's Unionists react to the word ''betrayal'' the way an
eager hound obeys the horn. The ears prick up, instinct takes over, and
the pack, oblivious to all but its quarry, bays for blood.
It has a lot to do with political traditions in the province. For
decades such transactions as there have been between the two communities
have turned on the belief that one side's gain must always be the
other's loss; what's good for Nationalists must, in all circumstances,
be bad for Unionists. Even peace is not a neutral condition.
That said, this week's crisis should have come as no surprise.
Unionist politicians have been signalling their growing
discontentment, as only they can, for months. They hold John Major's
spectral Commons majority by the delicate extremities, they do not trust
a word the Government says, and every ancestral voice warns them against
treachery and sell-out.
So we have Dr Paisley returned, vindicated and in triumph, to the
comforting warmth of the television studios when it seemed he was
thoroughly marginalised at last. So we have his allies muttering about
forcing a General Election (would Tony Blair really deal on those
terms?). And so we have -- a peculiar humiliation, this -- the Prime
Minister broadcasting a bathetic, grovelling plea for trust. This is
Honest John talking; who could doubt him? So far, so predictable. The
Unionists flex their muscles and the stakes are raised.
The spectre, in Loyalist minds, of cross-border powers, with Dublin
having any sort of say in the province, is banished for a while longer.
The party hacks of the Ulster Unionists and the Democratic Unionists,
who have most to lose from the birth of real politics in the north of
Ireland, can sleep easy in their beds.
But the sight of Unionists fighting their corner is nothing new. It is
what they were elected to do, after all, and London and Dublin knew they
had to cross this bridge sooner or later. What is more interesting --
and much more alarming -- is to look at the other participants in the
publicity coup. Since when, and for what reasons, did the once-august
Times of London have a ''selfish interest'' in screwing the Irish peace
process? By a simple process of elimination it's easy to conclude that
the paper got its leak from Loyalist sources, from the security
services, or from disgruntled civil servants (of the Crown, never
forget) whose Unionism is literal and sectarian.
The idea that it originated in Dublin is laughable. As Dr Garret
FitzGerald, former Irish Prime Minister and no friend of Sinn Fein, said
yesterday: ''This article was deliberately devised in order to
destabilise the Unionists who obviously were at a very sensitive moment
awaiting the publication of the document.''
If nothing else, Dr FitzGerald knows how these things work. A
27-year-old leader writer close to the wilder Unionist politicians, a
participant in a right-wing debating club of hacks, flakes and
professional patriots, and author, to boot, of a fervently pro-Loyalist
pamphlet, is handed (or so we are supposed to believe) the leaked draft
by his editor.
Young Winston is then expected to turn in a neutral account of its
contents at a time when the most important issue in British politics is
at its most delicate stage. If the Times is the innocent messenger of
truth in all this, I'm Ian Paisley's father confessor.
We haven't seen the Orange card played quite so ineptly in years.
Nevertheless, this is as good a time as any to ask just who the Times
thinks it represents. Hitherto, Ireland's Unionists have seemed isolated
and embattled figures. Now it becomes clear that one of the heavyweights
of the English establishment is prepared to come out on their side, not
through argument or debate, but by means of a calculated intervention in
the political process.
For columnists accustomed to accusations of bias, this is oddly
comforting, but we can draw wider conclusions. It is a fair bet, for
example, that the Times has its supporters both within and outwith the
Government. From this we can deduce that partisans of the cause of
Unionism -- of the cause of the United Kingdom -- are more determined
than we had guessed. John Major's recent, melodramatic remarks on
Scotland's future, never mind that of Ireland, take on a new complexion.
How far will these types really go to hold the Union together? What
hope does an enfeebled Prime Minister, already mired in the connected
issue of sovereignty within Europe, have of restraining them? In any
other context the exclusive published in the Times would have been
damned as dirty tricks, plain and simple. But with Ireland, Europe, and
Scottish home rule each touching raw Establishment nerves, we can expect
much more of the same.
Having rejected a plea from Major not to publish, what did the Times
hope to achieve? If the document exists, it is plainly relevant, but the
paper's handling of the story left little doubt of the sensation it
aimed to cause. To what end? The peace process wrecked, armed conflict
resumed, and the Union preserved? Speaking as a seasoned practitioner of
irresponsible journalism, this doesn't sound, at first hearing, like a
price worth paying.
Yet there has been no suggestion, thus far, that Major really intends
to expel Northern Ireland from the Union. In Scotland, however, we talk
freely and daily (if abstractly) of the chances of quitting the UK.
Some are for, some against, but we debate the matter as though it is
our own affair. That happy state cannot be taken for granted any longer.
Ireland first, Scotland next. Some play dirty in these patriot games.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Claim for higher pay rates rejected</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOUR junior doctors have lost their fight for higher pay rates for
working long overtime hours at two Scottish hospitals.
The doctors claimed their overtime rate, half their hourly rate, was
too low when the hard-pressed nature of their extra duties and lack of
sufficient rest were taken into account.
An Edinburgh industrial tribunal dismissed the complaints under the
Wages Act against Fife and Forth Valley Health Boards.
The disputes arose following the Government's introduction of the
''New Deal'' for junior doctors to reduce their long hours. A new system
of 50% pay for on-call hours, 70% for working a partial shift, and 100%
for working a full shift, was introduced.
In the Edinburgh case, Dr Kerry Matthewson from Edinburgh and Dr
Stuart Mair from Kirkcaldy told the tribunal they were on short-term
contracts as senior house officers in obstetrics and gynaecology with
Fife Health Board.
Dr Matthewson said he had a heavy workload covering clinics, wards,
admissions and deliveries and seldom got eight hours rest in 32 hours of
duty. He could be up all night on call.
Dr Mair's experience was similar but both were paid the lowest rate of
overtime. He claimed it should have been a higher category, 70% of their
normal pay, because of the intensity of the work.
The tribunal heard the situation was now under review by the Kirkcaldy
Acute NHS Trust: the maximum on-call hours had been reduced from 83 to
72 in hard-pressed posts, but the pay rate was the same.
Dr Meryl Peat from Edinburgh and Dr Ruth Crowe from Stenhousemuir, had
similar experiences in their year-long appointments in geriatrics and
general medicine at Falkirk and District Royal Infirmary.
The tribunal, however, did not find the health boards acted
unreasonably in classifying the senior house officer posts as on-call
rota posts in a fluctuating and developing situation, and found the
posts properly assessed and renumerated .
The British Medical Association, which supported the junior doctors,
said it would likely appeal and would be pressing ahead with other cases
''with confidence''. Junior doctors are involved in a similar case at an
industrial tribunal in Glasgow against the Royal Alexandra Hospital
Trust in Paisley. Their hearing continues in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Oat drive</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041931</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONTRACT oat growers from the membership of North Eastern Farmers Ltd
have given a positive response to a recruiting drive for Scottish
Quality Cereals -- the latest of the farm commodity assurance schemes.
Twenty-five members took up the intitial offer of a free on-farm
assessment which covered record keeping, storage and production
practices.
</TEXT>
