<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospital decay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
January 25.
With the recent successful campaign to save Stobhill and the launch of
the current one to save Lenzie Hospital, the silence is deafening for
support for Lennox Castle. Which politician is speaking up for residents
there?
For most of the residents Lennox Castle is their home, safe, secure,
and warm, but not for much longer the way things are going.
A once-beautiful estate and ideal, spacious site for the mentally
handicapped is rapidly running down through lack of maintenance and
neglect despite millions of pounds poured in a few years ago. Behind the
facelift lies decay and apathy. The once-splendid grounds are
disgraceful and a favourite dump for fly-tippers.
This rape of a once-fine hospital is being carried out under the
banner of Community Care, but have the residents any say before being
discharged into the community? Split up from their friends and the
social activities of Lennox Castle, for many it is a lonely, hostile
world out there.
Is there anyone out there with political muscle who will take up the
cudgels for Lennox Castle and its residents?
Finlay Dow,
29 Netherton Oval,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Linking rail networks</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
January 27.
Mr Marsh from Glasgow for People claims the support of local MPs,
councillors, residents, and business people in criticising the choice of
station locations for the Strathclyde CrossRail scheme (January 18).
This is hardly surprising if he has described the scheme to them in the
inaccurate terms used in your columns.
He states that Glasgow Cross station will be ''isolated, unattractive,
and comprise two platforms plus bus shelters''. In fact the station will
be located on Saltmarket, adjacent to Glasgow Cross, and will be
designed to complement and, where possible, utilise existing buildings.
The platforms will be well lit and will indeed provide shelter for
passengers.
He criticises the fact that the station will not be capable of being
conveniently linked to a possible future low-level station on the Argyle
Line. In fact the location chosen facilitates any such interchange
should it be built in the future as easily as any other location.
He criticises the proposed travelator link from Glasgow Cross station
to Argyle Street station and the St Enoch Centre. The need for this will
be assessed as the scheme progresses in the context of local area
development but I would imagine that if a covered travelator walkway
were provided, many people, especially the elderly, would welcome it.
Finally he criticises the decision to relocate High Street station
into the ''remote, unattractive wastelands'' of a goods yard. In fact
the station entrance to High Street will remain where it is, although
the platforms will be moved back 80 metres to accommodate the CrossRail
junction. The short connecting path will be well lit and will be much
easier to use for many less mobile passengers than the existing stairs.
His preferred option west of High Street would cost many millions of
pounds more to construct and would involve closing the existing Airdrie
line for many months with extensive passenger disruption.
Glasgow for People acknowledges the benefit of the CrossRail scheme to
the people of Glasgow and Strathclyde in further enhancing the extensive
local network supported by Strathclyde Regional Council. It is
unfortunate that misleading information has been used to denigrate the
council's proposals.
S R Lockley,
Director General, Strathclyde
Passenger Transport Executive,
12 West George Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
