<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Teaching the Holocaust</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
January 27.
Your editorial, Degrees of Guilt, relating as it does to the fiftieth
anniversary of both the bombing of Dresden and the liberation of the
concentration camp at Auschwitz, warrants further comment (January 27).
The bombs fell on Dresden as part of Britain's response in a war that
Germany invited through a programme of ruthless military expansion in
which the invasion of Poland was ''the last straw''.
Auschwitz operated in wartime but the unspeakable campaign against the
Jews cannot be dignified by calling it part of the war. (Among those
destroyed were German Jews who had fought for Germany.) The campaign
against Jews which led to the Final Solution had begun long before the
war and, unthinkable though it may seem, would undoubtedly have
continued after the war if the Allies had been defeated.
The statement that, ''Of the Holocaust, of which Auschwitz is the main
symbol, little new can be said'', fills me with foreboding because what
has been said has made such little difference (witness Bosnia, Rwanda,
and Chechnya).
That is why what is known has to be studied, remembered, and taught.
Dresden is now safe but anti-Semitism has signed no armistice. It is
re-emerging, for instance, in Germany and France. In Britain,
well-funded glossy magazines circulate widely which exist to perpetuate
Nazi hate while denying the Holocaust.
Arthur M Shenkin,
30 Langtree Avenue,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The importance of classlessness</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
January 27.
The Herald has done better than most other papers in drawing our
attention to Robin Cook's welcome revelation that he has ''reversed his
earlier opposition to Blair's strategy'' of modernising the Labour
Party.
But I think Mr Cook must go further than he has done in his article
(January 26).
I welcome his statement: ''The foundation of Labour's ideology should
rest not on state ownership but on social solidarity.'' But I would have
much preferred to see the dropping of the Marxism-inspired name
''Labour'' and its replacement with a sign that Mr Cook now proposes to
be ''radical'' enough to become a classless democrat and perhaps inspire
merging with the Liberals.
As a believer in the urgency and absolute necessity of being
''radical'' enough to embrace a vision of ultimate global democratic
integration may I advise members of both the main opposition parties to
form a ''common ground'' (eg, social solidarity) Opposition to the
Anglo-British Tories so that, as in the US, we can have a bipartisan
approach to politics instead of a tripartisan approach.
Let nobody think or suppose that it is not the tri-party or
multi-party kind of politics in Britain that has produced the long
domination by the Tories. There can be no doubt that a split opposition
is a gift to the dinosaurish Conservatives who are now pandering to the
mega-wealthy by raising interest rates and restricting Government
spending on projects which could cut the dole queues dramatically if the
highest rates of income tax, only, were raised.
If members of the two main British parties can be brought to see the
need for a single British political Opposition, firmly founded on
''social solidarity'' (ie, democratic unionism) we can defeat Mr Major
and his band of ''anti-integration in the EU'' supporters.
Edward Graham Macfarlane,
108 Forthill Road,
Broughty Ferry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mountain safety</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
January 23.
Your coverage of the latest mountain accident (in Torridon) is
welcome, concentrating as it does on how increased information about
snow and avalanche conditions could have prevented it rather than
suggesting that the only solution is for people to stay off the hill.
If more resources are needed for the Scottish Avalanche Information
Service, then this is even more so for other areas of mountain safety.
In 1993, for example, 11 people died from slips and falls while
hillwalking in winter conditions compared with two in avalanches. Too
many people are still going to the hill in winter either without
appropriate equipment or without knowing how to use it. Yet there is no
government money allocated directly to deal with this problem.
Last year, at a seminar organised by the Scottish Mountain Safety
Group, Sir Hector Munro hinted that more government money might be made
available to try to reduce accidents in the mountains. The
Mountaineering Council of Scotland has been working on a job remit for a
Scottish Mountain Safety Officer, the aim of which would be to tackle
other causes of accidents and co-ordinate the efforts of existing
bodies, only to be told recently that no new money appears to be
available from the Scottish Office.
Surely, given the concern about mountain accidents, it is time to fund
other safety initiatives. Initiatives such as a Mountain Safety Officer
would cost even less than the Scottish Avalanche Information Service and
would have the potential to save more lives.
Nick Kempe,
President, Mountaineering
Council of Scotland,
27 Leven Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Euro-con</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
January 29.
I am sorry, but that's it! The absolute limit!
The straw that has broken this camel's back is the revelation that,
according to Europe, Britain must now compensate deliberate criminals,
poll tax dodgers, to the tune of #20,000 each. As this compensation
comes from the tax-payers' pockets -- yours and mine -- I am, I believe
justifiably, very angry.
We have been conned over the Europe question. No mention has been made
at past elections of the federalist route being taken and now we are
being denied the chance to have our say. This and previous
administrations have pooh-poohed complaints about the ever-increasing
restrictions being foisted on us by Europe.
Now enough is enough. It must be made clear to Messrs Major, Blair,
and Ashdown that most of us do not want any closer ties with Europe and,
if that cannot be, the tightening knot (noose?) must be cut.
John Douglas,
1 Chacefield Wood,
Denny.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Old boy network</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>HERALD DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Nolan Committee proceeds apace with its investigation of sleaze
and jobs for the retired Tory Cabinet boys. At yesterday's hearing it
was suggested a committee be set up to monitor such appointments.
Who would be on this committee? it was asked. Lord Thomson of
Monifieth -- former Labour Cabinet Minister, European Commissioner, and
caption writer for the Beano -- had a beezer of an idea. Why not his pal
and fellow committee member, that fine, upstanding chap Lord Nolan?
Time-saving device
WE have to report an outbreak of humour on the part of Crawford
Beveridge, chief executive of Scottish Enterprise. During an address at
the University of Paisley, where he is visiting prof, he related how a
determined inventor laid siege to the Bothwell Street offices of the
enterprise body.
Encamped in the foyer, he was adamant that he had to speak to a senior
director. The junior person given the task of dealing with the situation
was finally able to elicit the nature of his request.
The inventor had perfected a time machine and all he needed was some
enterprise funding. The message was relayed upstairs and the answer came
back from the director that he didn't have time to see the inventor that
day. But if the inventor could come back last week, the director would
have time to see him.
No bandits
YOUR average local pub could be an interesting place as we celebrate
the 50th anniversary of VE-Day later this year.
To help recapture the flavour of the great day, the Brewers and
Licensed Retailers Association is issuing a special kit to pubs. It
contains a Union Flag to hang out, portraits of the old king and queen
for the wall, and a Glenn Miller tape for suitable background music.
Also in the kit are sundry period hats, including an air raid warden's
tin helmet. The piece de resistance is an inflatable Spitfire airplane.
Unfortunately there are no inflatable Fokkers to make it more
interesting in an aerial combat sense.
Not even Fokkers in Messerschmitts. That joke, we believe, predates
VE-Day.
Nasty blow
ITV NETWORK sport has invested a substantial amount of money into the
career of a boxer called Prince Naseem Hamed. He has been chosen as the
successor to Chris Eubank in ITV's efforts to gain ratings for their
fight programme.
Although the chap is from Sheffield, Scotland was chosen as the venue
for his last fight, in the SECC in Glasgow. His next fight is scheduled
for Livingston in March.
The Scottish sporting press has given Naseem a reasonably warm
welcome. One notable exception was Gerry McNee in his Sunday Mail column
who wrote: ''Having nothing better to do, I watched the boxing mis-match
involving Naseem whatshisname on TV. Looking at the goings-on in and out
of the ring, I couldn't help but think that had I been daft enough to
attend, I would have wanted to rush home and take a very long, cleansing
shower . . .''
This criticism so incensed one ITV sport high heid yin that he
telephoned Scottish TV to ask just who is this guy McNee. ''Scottish
TV's sports editor, actually,'' was the embarrassed reply.
* The Daily Record has been conducting an investigation all week into
the state of Scottish football. The graphic image selected to accompany
the series is of a young fan with the cross of St Andrew painted on his
face. Scottish soccer must be in a bad way. The photo was taken at
Murrayfield where the young supporter was watching the game played with
the oval ball.
</TEXT>
