<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bottomley promises to make life better for junior doctors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH Secretary Virginia Bottomley has given a personal pledge to the
father of a young doctor, whose family claim he was worked to death,
that the lives of junior doctors will be improved.
Mrs Bottomley, whose daughter is a junior doctor at London's St
Thomas's Hospital, has spoken of her personal sorrow over the death of
Dr Alan Massie, 26, who collapsed and died at Warrington General
Hospital after working an 86-hour week in January last year.
In a four-page letter to his father, George, of Macclesfield,
Cheshire, Mrs Bottomley set out in detail her plans to cut doctors'
hours.
''I want to reassure you that our determination to improve the working
lives of junior doctors is far more than just a paper commitment. I
accepted in 1990 that their workload was becoming increasingly intense
and we took action to tackle the problem.''
But Mrs Bottomley said it was not realistic to change the working
patterns of more than 25,000 junior doctors in England alone in a matter
of weeks or months.
The New Deal launched in 1991 was a practical programme of action to
tackle the problem long term. She said the 83-hour ceiling of hours
imposed on all contracts at that stage was still too high to be a
lasting solution.
The next step was a lower ceiling for hard-pressed posts where out of
hours calls were heaviest. ''We are now aiming to cap contracted hours
in those posts at 72 a week and within that limit to see that no junior
doctor works on average for more than 56 hours a week,'' she said.
Mr Massie wrote to Mrs Bottomley after the inquest on his son which
ruled he died of ''sudden adult death syndrome'' -- a natural cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Beckett hits at casualty units' recruiting crisis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041942</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHADOW Health Secretary Margaret Beckett yesterday condemned the
crisis over recruitment of junior doctors for accident and emergency
departments.
Shortages throughout the UK had prompted desperate measures by NHS
trusts and managers to maintain a service, she said. Peterborough
Hospitals NHS Trust, as revealed by The Herald, had offered #50 an hour
to doctors to provide cover.
Peterborough served constituents both of Transport Secretary and
former Health Minister Dr Brian Mawhinney and of the Prime Minister, she
added.
Mrs Beckett said the incident highlighted the Government's failure to
keep its promise to provide adequate provision to meet the New Deal for
reducing junior doctors' hours.
''This is further proof of the problems in Virginia Bottomley's NHS,''
she said. ''It is absolutely appalling she is allowing vital casualty
services to reach such a stage.''
Dr Brian Potter, Scottish secretary of the British Medical
Association, said: ''It is a complex problem but it does throw into
focus the Government's health reforms.
''It is one of the direct effects of the reforms where you have got
hospitals competing against hospitals for a limited supply of labour. It
also forces them into having to make unacceptable decisions, because if
you put more money into this area you have got to take it from somewhere
else.''
The New Deal has resulted in a substantial rise in house officer posts
to cope with the reduction in working hours. However, it takes five
years to train a doctor. There has been no corresponding increase in
numbers graduating from medical schools and those coming out have been
more selective in the posts they choose.
Dr Keith Little, accident and emergency consultant at Edinburgh Royal
Infirmary, said the issue had been taken up by the British Association
for Accident and Emergency Medicine.
''It may be a failure on the Government's part to understand the
consequences of a lot of different factors coming together. I do not
know of any instant solution at all,'' he said.
Dr Little said accident and emergency departments in the UK absorbed
2800 junior staff every year, the highest of any speciality.
''We are feeling the brunt of the New Deal and a number of other
factors at the same time, but this will impact on other specialties,''
he added.
Scottish Health Minister, Lord Fraser of Carmyllie, said: ''It is
vitally important there is proper cover across Scotland and not just in
a few centres, however excellent they may be.
''There is no issue of funding here. If junior doctors with the
appropriate qualifications apply for the posts, they can be employed
immediately.''
Lord Fraser said the problem had been caused by changes in career
patterns and requirements from the Royal Colleges. ''I am meeting with
senior medical advisers to discuss the issue which is affecting the
whole of the UK,'' he added.
Neither Dr Mawhinney nor the Prime Minister's office could offer any
comment yesterday.
Mr Bryan Harty, operations director for the Peterborough NHS Trust,
said the enhanced pay, five times the usual #10 an hour rate, had
attracted interest.
''We have had a very positive response from local GPs because of their
desire to keep the accident and emergency unit open 24 hours a day,
seven days a week. The rotas for February and March are now filled,'' he
added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The price of political virtue</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE case for raising British interest rates again was evenly balanced
but the American decision to nudge theirs upwards was probably decisive
in forcing the hands of the Chancellor and the Governor of the Bank of
England. The worsening inflationary pressures identifiable in the
economy were balanced by other evidence which might have supported
waiting for another month, but the pre-emptive strategy adopted by the
Governor has prevailed and a third modest increase in less than six
months has come into action. Various bodies have protested: they are all
correct in claiming that the additional burden imposed is damaging but
the Government's defence is unassailable if one assumes that resurgent
inflation would be more damaging still, and that action before rather
than after a fresh surge is the better response. The Liberal Democrat
view that a succession of increases does not amount to a strategy is
mistaken -- it is akin to pumping on the brakes of a car so as to avoid
an abrupt halt or a skid -- but the strategy itself could be mistaken,
though it does allow the reverse process to be implemented should later
trends confound the pessimism to which Mr George is addicted.
The economy remains growing at around 4% per annum, a high rate
historically and one certainly above the post-war trend line. The
recovery which that figure exposes is real enough (and is confirmed by
the employment statistics), but the benefits are mostly going into areas
which are not obvious to popular opinion and seldom welcome where they
are. In that fact lies much of the Government's political difficulties
in the opinion polls. The recovery is fuelled by a very good export
performance but the reverse of that coin is that it is not fuelled by
that domestic demand which would help to make spenders feel better. The
jobs being created do not make enough people feel better either, since
they have to be weighed against the mood of insecurity which affects the
even larger numbers who worry about the permanency of their own jobs.
Increased mortgage charges are resented by all who have to pay them: the
amounts are far more than suggested by half-percentage point increases
and are increased by the relentless ratcheting down of the tax
concession embodied in Miras (mortgage interest rate relief). Such
changes are desirable in that we need to switch national savings away
from house purchase, but try telling that to those struggling to meet
mortgage payments. They feel hard pressed -- no wonder their lenders are
anxious to postpone passing the new rates on, at least for a bit.
The political consequence of all this is bad news for the Government.
It is not the stuff of electoral success, and as more tax rises will
pump out of the pipeline in April, it would be a brave man who would
forecast any early significant change in the political climate.
Ministers will say that they are being virtuous, putting country above
party, and so on. An electorate made cynical by disappointment (and
well-deployed Opposition skills) will not be convinced, and not least
because the virtue was imposed by our ejection from the ERM, and
therefore contrary to all the Government's original hopes. Politicians
have to work with what they have, but Ministers may be forgiven if they
suspect that popular opinion is not as hostile to inflation as they, and
their advisers, are. Will Ministers panic and settle for ''a little''
inflation? All their predecessors have done so. It may be a matter of
time but, for the moment, virtue prevails, at considerable political
cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The torment of not knowing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041944</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S the not knowing that aches more than anything. Are they alive?
Injured? Did they die with dignity? Were there moments of heroism,
comfort, reassurance from another, fear?
The family of Christopher Mannion can understand precisely the torment
that Lesley Bilinda has gone through.
The 43-year-old British monk disappeared shortly after arriving in
Rwanda to try and secure the release of a kidnapped Tutsi colleague. His
body has never been found, but his elderly parents in Darlington were
told that he had been killed and most probably buried somewhere near the
shell of his burnt-out car.
I was one of the last people to see him. We met in June as he crossed
the border into Rwanda, driving in convoy past the militia roadblocks to
the Catholic mission in Butare.
In the relative safety of the mission grounds, we sat on a windowsill
and chatted about Glasgow, where he had worked with his order, the
Marist Brothers, and about the task ahead of him. He was quiet and pale
and admitted to being a little nervous. His colleague had been held by
the militia for some time and they had managed to persuade the group
holding him to discuss his release.
''They know someone is coming for him but they don't know who or
when,'' he said. ''I don't know how long it's going to take me to get
him out.'' We said our goodbyes over dinner and left before he did the
following morning.
Not long after that he disappeared. He managed to free his colleague,
then heard about two others and negotiated their freedom as well.
Somewhere, on one of the narrow Rwandan roadways his car apparently was
hijacked. The body of his colleague, Joseph Rushigayiki, was found in
the vehicle but there was no sign of Chris.
Like Charles Bilinda, the rumours about his disappearance grew and
shrank as the weeks passed. Eventually, at the end of August, the new
prime minister, Faustin Twagiramungu, sent a fax to his order in Rome
telling them that he could confirm that Chris had been killed. It's
thought he was maybe the victim of a random mugging.
Speaking yesterday, a family friend said that his relatives are still
not satisfied that they have heard the full story, and are still
unsettled by that lingering doubt that maybe somewhere he is being held
captive.
''I think mentally they have said, yes, he's dead, but there is still
that question mark and it will remain there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DIY tax a dodger's charter?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARGARET VAUGHAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041945</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Heavy staff cuts at Inland Revenue offices could mean that in future
taxpayers will have to make their own assessments, with strict deadlines
and heavy penalties for those caught trying to beat the system. Just how
difficult will DIY taxation be, and with fewer taxmen will the cheats be
caught?
Margaret Vaughan reports.
YOU may not know this yet -- you may not want to know this -- but one
day you could regret the passing of your tax inspector. They may not be
your favourite people. They may even be the sad objects of skilled
avoidance techniques, practised especially at parties. But soon you may
miss them. You may, but then again you might be too busy wrestling with
tax tables, mortgage interest relief, married couples allowance, too
anxious about filling in the form and avoiding a hefty fine, to worry
about it.
The confirmation yesterday that 6000 jobs will be axed at the Inland
Revenue over the next three years with another 6000 to be shed by the
turn of the century is further evidence of the move to do-it-yourself
taxation, called self-assessment. The onus will shift to taxpayers
working out their own bill with strict deadlines to pay.
Will do-it-yourself taxation be a dodger's charter? Only to the extent
that, like fare dodging on a bus, the risk of the inspector jumping
aboard to check your ticket is an ever-present reality, according to the
Inland Revenue.
Others, notably the unions and Opposition politicians, argue that
#4.7billion was raked in last year by inspectors pursuing those who
evaded tax, intentionally or by mistake. John McFall, a Labour front
bencher, claimed yesterday that the job losses could lead to an extra 9p
on basic income rates through tax non-compliance.
Mr McFall quoted the 1994 Report of the Commissioners of Her Majesty's
Inland Revenue, presented to Parliament last October, which said that
the yield from action against non-compliance was #4.7b. That was the
equivalent to 2.5p in the basic rate of income tax.
The figure did not take into account the indirect yield, including the
''corrective'' effect on taxpayers on cases investigated by inspectors,
which was estimated to be a further #4.5b over five years, or the
deterrent effect of tax investigation which was said to be
unquantifiable.
Professor Alex McDougall, of Edinburgh University, a practising
accountant, believes the changes will mean more emphasis on catching tax
dodgers. He said self-assessment for companies, called Pay and File, was
already in operation.
Other factors given for the job cuts include the move to electronic
lodgment for companies, where tax practitioners will send everything to
the Inland Revenue through computer lines.
''I've no doubt these changes are behind the job losses, along with
the wish to reduce public spending,'' said Professor McDougall. He
believes most of the tax jobs to be lost will be in the clerical grades
with the emphasis switching to more sophisticated tax-raising
approaches: ''This should mean more skilled people deployed to search
for evaders.''
There are 29 million taxpayers in the UK. Of these, 20 million pay tax
through their employers in the PAYE scheme and usually will be sent a
tax return only every four or five years.
The other nine million have to fill in a return every year, because
they are self-employed or have other sources of income on top of PAYE,
perhaps investment income or capital gains.
From the end of next year, they will not only have to fill in the form
but work out what they are due in allowances, and tot up their own tax.
There will be spot checks made on tax returns and heavy penalties for
those trying to beat the system.
Alan Barr, a tax specialist who heads the Legal Practice Unit at
Edinburgh University's law faculty, says self-assessment may in the long
term justify the reduction in jobs. But, he fears, in the short to
medium term, it will mean more rather than less work in the tax offices:
''There will, inevitably, have to be a big checking exercise and big
educational exercises to explain to people how to work out their own
tax.''
The scheme is being phased in, starting in the tax year 1996/97 and
should be fully in effect the following year.
Mr Barr believes there is scope for evasion under the do-it-yourself
scheme: ''It is possible, although self-assessment will be subject to
stringent checks. The revenue will have less work to do in the sense of
shifting assessments, so in theory they should have more time to do more
in catching evaders.''
Estimates of how much tax is already lost through evasion vary.
Professor Brian Hogwood of Strathclyde University says that while #57b
was paid in income tax in 1993, another 10% was reckoned to be lost
through tax dodges.
Fiddling is the illegal way. The legal way is called tax avoidance and
involves paying professional advisers to find loopholes and ways of not
paying tax, such as setting up offshore companies and trusts.
Then there is the ''hidden economy'', estimated to be worth between
#41b and #54b a year. That involves such things as tradesmen doing
homers, working for an employer by day and painting your living room by
night. Some liberal economists claim the hidden economy oils the wheels
of the economy as a whole. An article in an edition of the Inland
Revenue magazine ReveNews last year hinted that Ministers have decided
to turn a blind eye to moonlighting.
But an opinion poll carried out for the Inland Revenue showed that
nine out of 10 taxpayers wanted more action to ensure people paid their
fair share of tax.
Alan Barr believes the move to shift the burden of tax compliance on
to the taxpayer will mean many more people needing help to sort out
their tax affairs. In America street-corner booths tout for business by
offering an instant service to fill in your tax return form.
He says the Government's stated aim of simplifying the tax system, by
moving away from complex allowances to a flat tax rate, simply has not
happened. The past three finance Acts have introduced enormously complex
changes. Last year's Budget, derided as boring, will, he says, actually
introduce another tranche of intricacies into the tax system.
He believes the move to self-assessment will bring even greater
confusion: ''It will make it more worrying and difficult for a lot of
people. It may mean that they are more likely to get it wrong, and will
end up needing expensive help to get it right.''
Much like getting on to a bus with no conductor, where you are
expected to have the right change, you risk losing out if you don't know
the fare. Maybe the redundant species of bus conductor and the vanishing
breed of tax collectors have more in common, after all, than a simple
imperative to extract money from you.
'The revenue will have less work to do, so they should have more time
to catch evaders'
</TEXT>
