<HEADLINE>Small matter of the economy adds to other troubles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER,</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041946</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR MAJOR, still struggling to keep the Northern Ireland peace process
afloat, had to take time off to defend the half-per-cent interest rate
rise of more immediate concern to most voters in Great Britain,
The Chancellor, Mr Kenneth Clarke, had earlier done the same in his
best cheeky-chappie manner, saying that the average Briton would still
be a fiver a week better off this year and warning that Labour
insouciance on inflation would throw away the economic recovery.
Labour maintains a healthy scepticism about the welfare or indeed the
existence of this recovery, which appears to be shared by most of the
electors.
Messrs Blair and Brown performed their home owners' friend routine
with which they are increasingly comfortable while not actually saying
the rise was wrong or unnecessary.
There was some intriguing European fencing on the Tory back benches
which took the form of questions to Ministers.
Mrs Anne Winterton asked Mr Clarke to declare that a single currency
was as much anathema to him as to her.
Mr Clarke, probably the keenest single currrency man in the Cabinet,
meekly referred her to an interesting speech by his morning coffee
companion Mr Eddie George, Governor of the Bank of England.
The accepted view that Euro scepticism is in the ascendant was
confirmed when Mr Alan Duncan outlined a nightmare scenario in which
some EU members set up a single currency because their economic
performances had suitably converged only for them to diverge with
catastrophic results once the wretched system had been set up.
In Mr David Heathcoat-Amory, he had a Treasury Minister happy to agree
but the Prime Minister was very right to be cautious about the whole
thing.
Some Europhiles sought to make their case to Mr Major himself but with
indifferent success.
Mr James Couchman asked if EU membership was not a very good thing, Mr
Major said it was but swiftly added that the conditions of membership
were vital. The advantage would be lost if the conditions were to
include involvement in the Social Chapter, a quote that might be worth
filing away in case some inventive member of the Commission staff finds
a way of imposing it on us.
Sir Michael Marshall suggested the time was ripe for the Commons to
have a great debate on Europe. No doubt he was thinking of the majority
of MPs who are still keen or fairly keen on the EU.
Mr Major, doubtless thinking of Mrs Teresa Gorman at Sir Edward
Heath's throat -- just one of a number of contests he could envisage --
must have shuddered.
But he bravely said it would take too long to debate Labour's
divisions on the subject.
He had earlier accused Mr Blair of ''cheek'' on interest rates and now
paid him back with interest.
He was right, of course, but apart from Mr Peter Shore, Mr Austin
Mitchell and the perpetual youthful Mr Dennis Skinner, most of Labour's
Euro sceptics are keeping their heads below the parapet thankful that
their Tory comrades-in-arms are doing such a good job.
Mrs Gorman, indeed, made Mr Major laugh as she hoped the news that the
Treasury building is to be partially privatised had nothing to do with
Mr Jacques Santer's call for ''the abolition of our national currency.''
Mr John Home-Robertson (East Lothian -- Lab.) said angrily that he and
others were getting fed up with the continuous refrain ''Ulster says
No'' being parroted by some Unionists.
Mr Major, whose need for the Unionists on Ireland and for tricky
Commons votes is extreme, said he did not doubt the sincerity of all of
them in seeking a way to permanently end the horrors their Province has
experienced for the past 25 years.
There is no need for anyone to doubt it. In Ireland and Europe, this
Parliament confronts issues on which, certainly, there is political
manoeuvring aplenty, but what ultimately matters is that real passionate
conviction which day to day politics often only simulates.
Despite the interest rate rise, the Chancellor still found something
to smile
</TEXT>
