<HEADLINE>Rebel without a pause</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041947</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
One voice has been conspicuous by its absence in Westminster. Sir
Nicholas Fairbairn is ill. But his provocative nature is as robust as
ever, ROBBIE DINWOODIE discovers
I have not been sent
to Parliament to
wink just because
John Major says wink
Benn is extremely well
read but deluded -- like
Tam Dalyell. I adore
Tam, but he's dotty
Scottish independence
in Europe would be
disastrous . . .
a frightful fantasy
At a time of unprecendented turmoil at Westminster, when his colourful
and strident voice would surely have been one of the most contentious,
Sir Nicholas Fairbairn QC has been forced by ill health to languish in
his lair at Fordell Castle in Fife. But while he has already announced
his retirement from parliamentary politics at the next General Election,
the unconventional Tory MP for Perth and Kinross has not -- as this
exclusive interview proves -- switched off his passion for controversy.
ON EUROPE
* IN STYLE and posture Fairbairn is of a different time. Defying
''political correctness'' to the last degree, capable of statements that
many would take as proof of outrageous bigotry, he refuses to conform to
norms that represent for him a dead, grey hand on individual conviction.
Talking at Fordell Castle, he is characteristically unrepentant. ''If
I had kept my nose clean and brushed my hair and wiped my bottom and
sucked up I would I no doubt have got a lot further in politics,'' he
says, ''but since the price of getting further would have been alien to
my nature, I don't regret that.''
He has made brilliant, if erratic, contributions to three different
careers since, as an adolescent, he used a catapult to smash windows of
a local Co-op bakery in protest at Labour's post-war election victory.
For that he was ''profoundly beaten'' but he has never learned a lesson.
As an advocate, MP and Government law officer, he has rarely been out of
the public eye.
A celebrated bon vivant only just past his sixty-first birthday, he is
gravely ill but without regrets, blasting at colourless conformity, and
making clear that had he been able to attend Westminster he would have
fought the Government on European policy.
''Certainly! I would not regard it as defying the leadership. I would
be doing what I was elected to Parliament to do, to exercise my judgment
if I consider something to be an unprincipled folly. I have not been
sent there to wink just because John Major says wink.
''I you had told any British subjects 20 years ago that they would
lose their currency, their flag, their foreign policy, and control over
their own army, they would have said you were insane. Anyone who says
that now is a rebel.
''Europe is a fantasy of illusion for do-gooder imaginists like Hurd
-- as if we will all speak one language, have the same thoughts. Tell
that to Russia. I have been to Pakistan and India and this idea that we
all love one another is a nonsense. There wouldn't be divorce courts if
humans were like that.
''It's a fatuous concept to have some kind of United States of Europe.
It's totally misconceived. Europe is a complex, historically diverse,
war-ridden, peace-ridden, rival-ridden, friend-ridden, battle-worn
place. You only have to look at the First and Second World Wars.''
ON OTHERS
* SIR NICKY'S distaste for slavish following of the party line led him
into an astonishing attack on the candidate selected to succeed him,
London-based merchant banker John Godfrey.
''When I stood for Kinross and West Perthshire there seemed to be
about 600 candidates and I thought I would come 599th but I won it. I
held it for 22 years and will now leave it in the strange hands of what
is to come.''
Meaning your successor as candidate? Can John Godfrey retain the seat?
''Not a chance! He is a clone. I don't think he knows anything about
about Perthshire or Scotland.
''I have had innumerable telephone calls and letters from local Tory
supporters who agree that he is totally irrelevant. I wrote to the
chairman yesterday and said, it's nothing to do with me now because I'm
offski, but I think you should know that the constituents fear he will
be an absentee -- and unelectable.
''It might not matter to Perth and Kinross whether he is electable or
not, but it might just matter as to who forms the next Government.''
This talk is reminiscent of his outburst last year when he announced he
would not be standing again, and condemned the faceless lobby fodder
which increasingly permeated the Westminster scene.
''That's the trouble, Tory Central Office in Scotland and in England
have been ordered to have only clones. What did John Major call them,
the classless society? It's his term, not mine. The classless society is
saying this is nobody and that is nobody.
''When I first went into Westminster we had dukes and dustmen,
coal-miners and lecturers. I don't care if someone is a duke or a
dustman. He is a person. I am afraid on both sides of the House people
are now selected for their non-existence. There are identical clones on
both sides. I think it's a very dangerous trend. I mean, Blair is such a
humbug.''
Is there no-one he rates as better than cloned party-fodder? ''I'm
very fond of Gordon Brown. I think he is astute and wise. And Dear Old
Benn, there's a real character, whether you agree or disagree with him.
He's got a bloody good mind, is extremely well read and knows about the
world, but completely deluded -- like Tam Dalyell. I adore Tam, but he's
dotty.''
So there are fewer and fewer MPs with an individualist streak,
prepared to stand by their convictions, show a character of their own?
Will the few who remain be driven out by the next century? ''I would
have that fear. It isn't just in politics.
''I am afraid it's a dangerous trend, not just at Westminster but in
many manifestations of human life. Look at judges and advocates and
those sort of people. They are just squashed into identicality, which I
find infuriating.
''Look at the great people who use to strut the world's stage,
Cockburn, or Churchill or Curzon. Take Curzon. He walked all over China
and India, was Governor General of India, came home and became Foreign
Secretary, bloody nearly Prime Minister. How do you fit all that into
one life?
''Churchill was the same. I look at the likes of Churchill and Curzon
and say, 'Jesus, how did they do all that?' Who is going to write a book
in the present House of Commons? They have never been to half the world,
these people. I mean, Malcolm Rifkind has actually been to Bosnia. How
decent of him!
Fairbairn has no regrets about his time at Westminster: ''Parliament I
have found absolutely fascinating as an object of human scrutiny. My
father was a psychoanalyst, so I suppose I was brought up to judge
people and dissect them. That's politics. Being a law officer in the
Government I found very fulfilling, even if it meant you had to deal
with arse-licking civil servants and their despicable sycophancy.''
But his legal career, during which he defended people facing the death
sentence 17 times and never lost one, is seen as his best of times. ''I
loved the law. It was a great challenge to do for somebody what they
can't do for themselves, and to argue your way out of the pit. Even in
divorce courts you have the responsibility of saving them from what to
them is a massive trauma. In the courts there was always to be found a
bit of humanity.
''In law, I suppose the low points were losing when I thought I should
have won. I never regretted winning when I should have lost. But losing
when I should have won got to me -- Meehan was a very good example. I
was was desperately upset when I didn't get him off.''
ON DEVOLUTION
* THE HOSTILITY of Sir Nicky to devolution in any form is tangible.
''A Scottish assembly is dotty. It means another effing Government,
another million bloody civil servants and more hangers-on. Now these
people say there should be some for England, for Rutland, for North
Wales, for South Derbyshire. Sheer madness.
''Scottish Independence in Europe would be absolutely disastrous. It
would vastly increase our expenses and our civil service and it would
involve us in a frightful fantasy.
''I remember Winnie Ewing saying . . .'' (at this point he breaks into
an alarmingly realistic impersonation of Madame Ecosse) ''. . . When
Scotland sits proudly between Saudi Arabia and Senegal at the United
Nations there will never be war any more. We will run the world.
''We don't need all that fantasy. We are a dignified, wonderful,
historic country. We are remarkably fortunate to be a little vineyard on
our own.''
But in his own profession of the law many who would not consider
themselves Nationalists still see a paradox inherent in a legal system
without a legislature.
''I agree it is a paradox, but it is a paradox that has existed since
1707, I suppose. But the Scots legal system has survived and thrived in
all its individuality and principle, which is more than can be said for
the law of England.
''One thing that infuriates me is when a radio broadcaster or someone
in a newspaper article talks about this law and that law when it is
nothing to do with Scotland and is all about English law.''
ON DRINK
* SANCTIMONY and perceived puritanism has always raised Fairbairn's
hackles, nowhere more so than in hypocrisy on drinking. ''If you look at
the history of the world, alcohol has always played its part. Take all
this crap just now about being allowed to drink in England from seven
till seven! Jesus Christ, look at any continental country, if you are
thirsty you go in and buy a drink of wine.
''This concept that it should be licensed as a poison is utterly
ridiculous. It is natural for 98% of the people. The idea that it is
some sort of permitted sin is fatuous. What are all those pubs there
for? It's a form of puritanism and self satisfied intolerance.''
Now he is taking life a few weeks at a time, setting targets a month
or two away: ''I have got an exhibition of paintings coming up in March
at in Edinburgh. That's the next hurdle to jump,'' he says. ''Then we're
looking at the second volume of my autobiography coming out. It's been
at the publisher for months. I have also written a novel called Murder
Most Manifest which is with publishers in Edinburgh.''
One goal at a time, no regrets. Sir Nicholas turns his painter's gaze
to the windows and a stunning view across Fife, savouring the clear
Scottish air.
''Isn't it lovely this winter? This sun and light and straggles of
snow. We have had it for months now. It is absolutely wonderful.''
</TEXT>
