<HEADLINE>The message of Ramadan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041948</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Middle East peace process is in the deepest trouble and the
Ramadan summit held last night will not of itself bring about
resuscitation. This is not for want of trying. The United States has
been hyperactive behind the scenes in promoting the idea of the summit
and ensuring that everyone attends. The measure of Washington's success
is the fact that Prime Minister Rabin of Israel sat down for the first
time with three key Arab leaders to discuss the process face-to-face.
Almost as important was the presence of Mr Rabin at the sunset meal with
which Muslims end a day of Ramadan fasting. Inviting him was a gesture
of acceptance by the Arab leaders which has heartening implications
which go far beyond the simple breaking of bread. That should take care
of the symbolism of the affair. The substance is quite a different
matter.
In their own way each of the four leaders faces domestic difficulty.
President Mubarak of Egypt is struggling against violent Islamic
militants and King Hussein and Yasser Arafat have similar trouble and a
lack of progress on the peace process with which to beguile their
people. Mr Rabin is losing credibility with every terrorist outrage and
Israel's inability to do much about it. To this extent their interests
meet; each would welcome a meaningful resumption of the peace process
but must carefully guard his constituency at home against the attacks of
the malign and discontent. This is reflected in the conclusions reached
at the summit which call for an end to political violence, more progress
in implementing agreements already established between Israel and the
Palestinians, and a good deal more speed and flexibility in passing
promised international aid to the Palestinians.
Mr Arafat and the Palestinians are unhappy with the stress put on
terrorism and would like to see greater importance given to extending
Palestinian control over the occupied territories. Frankly, they will
have to put up with this. The appalling terrorism of recent weeks has
drastically slowed a process which was already limping. The terrorists
are not winning but it is tempting to say that at the moment they are
ahead on points. The saddest fact underpinning that equally sad
admission is that there is little that either Mr Arafat or Mr Rabin can
do to stop the terrorism. The man who could do a great deal, and who the
latest Israeli intelligence indicates is serious in his desire to
achieve peace with Israel, is missing. President Assad of Syria was not
asked because he would only have refused. Persuading this cautious and
deeply enigmatic man to join the peace process is rapidly becoming the
key to success, as he no doubt intends. It must be managed, however it
is done. In the meantime symbolism must suffice, and the extension of
the message of Ramadan, which is peace, is still the most worthwhile aim
of all.
</TEXT>
