<HEADLINE>Facts on water deals demanded</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041949</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National Party has called on Scottish Secretary Ian Lang
to elaborate on the Scottish Office's contact with English water
companies who have expressed an interest in operating contracts for new
water authorities north of the Border.
Following the disclosure in Wednesday's Herald that Northumbrian Water
has signed a deal with John Brown Engineering to co-operate in a bid for
the contracts, SNP water spokesman Mr Andrew Welsh has tabled questions
on the deal.
Mr Welsh, MP for Angus East, said: ''It is important that people in
Scotland are kept informed about what is happening to the water industry
in Scotland. The Scottish Office must know of enquiries made by these
private companies.
''The fact that a private water company in England is interested in
investing in Scottish water will be cause for some concern.''
Northumbrian and John Brown will bid for contracts under the
Government's BOO initiative -- Build, Own, and Operate -- aimed at
passing on major capital projects to the private sector. The Scottish
Office have identified 15 such schemes.
</TEXT>
