<HEADLINE>In one woman's grief, the agony of Rwanda</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041950</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Lesley Bilinda prayed for the return of her missing husband. She has
been told he was killed.
THERE IS one particularly poignant series of photographs in Lesley
Bilinda's collection. They show her and her husband, Charles, shortly
after their wedding, walking, arms linked, through the doors of their
new home. Behind them, the lush and tranquil Rwandan countryside. Around
them, groups of smiling friends.
Less than 18 months after they were taken Lesley walked on her own
across a mass grave near her former home, found her pet dog grown fat on
human flesh, and tried to make some sense of the madness that had
apparently killed Charles and slaughtered hundreds of thousands of
others.
Rwanda has become, for most of us, the definition of horror. The
source of countless blurred and bloody nightmarish images. The gaping
slice left by a machete. A carpet of half-clothed bones on a church
floor. The ancient, agonised faces of young refugees. How many dead?
Maybe one million? One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, keep
counting, nine, 10, 11.
For Lesley Bilinda, Rwanda had been home since she was sent there in
1989 by the Tear Fund, a Christian relief and development organisation,
to work in a preventive-medicine project in the small town of Gahini,
near Kigali.
Born in Montrose and trained as a nurse and midwife in London, she
embodies the best of her stock and her profession -- a no-nonsense
north-east realism and a calm, compassionate and capable nature.
The community of Gahini took her to its heart. She made many close
friends but says she can't remember the first time she met Charles, the
young Tutsi pastor, who had been sent to the region to oversee an
environmental-health project. He was lively and outgoing and spoke
impeccable English, and they eventually came together through mutual
friends.
The Rwandan wedding is a complex and drawn-out affair, so they decided
to limit their own to a traditional ceremony in Gahini and a more formal
one in a Kigali church.
Sitting in her sister's flat in Edinburgh with Charles's face smiling
up from the photographs in her album, she says that even the riotous and
colourful rejoicing of the wedding snaps is a little misleading. There
was disquiet in Rwanda even then.
''We nearly didn't get to Kigali for the second ceremony, because
there had been a number of political rallies and they had been getting
more and more violent . . . things were certainly brewing.''
In the spring of the following year, she left for Nairobi to meet her
sister for a two-week holiday. ''Charles had other commitments and was
not able to come at that stage. It was just a two-week holiday. I had a
rucksack packed with summer clothes.''
That was March 29. Eight days later, the plane carrying the presidents
of Rwanda and Burundi was shot down and the country slipped into
anarchy.
For two days Lesley was unaware what had happened. Her sister had
taken ill and the pair were stranded in Mombasa. ''I had called in a
doctor and when he found out I was from Rwanda he said: 'Oh, that's
where the president was killed'. I thought he was confusing it with the
Burundian president who was killed last year. He said: 'No, no, they
were both killed on Wednesday'. It was the first I heard of it. I
switched on the radio and listened hour by hour. I couldn't believe what
I was hearing. By that time the killings had spread all over the
country. It was absolute madness.''
She managed to make it back to Nairobi and tried feverishly to get
information about Charles and her friends. Her home had no telephone and
she eventually reached an ex-pat in Kigali. The woman warned her that
everyone who could was leaving.
''I could not get in touch with Charles and I knew people were being
evacuated. I guess I thought that he's the husband of a British citizen
and perhaps he will be able to be evacuated.''
The next few hours and days were almost unbearable. ''I was just
frantically trying anything and everything that we possible could. It
was an awful, awful time.'' She pauses and looks away for a second,
fingers knitting, brow creasing.
Eventually Lesley realised that there was absolutely nothing she could
do. ''Then I saw that I needed not to trust in what governments can do
but to trust in what God can do.'' She turned to prayer and, in the
middle of April, returned to Scotland to be with her family.
A month later she received a call from Rwanda saying that Charles had
made it to the town of Butare in the south and had been killed there. It
was the first of several such rumours.
''To begin with I was completely knocked flat by it. I was believing
very strongly that he was going to be kept safe. Why, why should this
happen if we were praying . . . I was going up and down and not really
knowing what to believe.''
As she was gradually coming to accept that Charles might be dead, and
was preparing to go back out to Rwanda, a British friend brought word
that Charles had been staying with the bishop in Butare when the
military had come and taken him away.
''I was grateful that it was the military that had taken him and not
the militia. At least it would have been a quick death. However there
was still this tiny hope that he might be in hiding somewhere.''
Just before she left Scotland in October, she managed to get through
by phone to Charles's sister and her husband in Kigali. Out of an
extended family of 200, three of them had survived. They had no news of
Charles.
The trip back took an enormous emotional toll on her and talking about
it is clearly painful. She met friends who had survived and learned of
the deaths of others, including an infant relative clubbed to death on
her mother's back. ''I was also told about those who did the killing.
They were people I had known well, people that I would never have
suspected could have done this.''
The house she shared with Charles had been commandeered by a Rwandan
Patriotic Front official and her attempts to return and remove some of
her belongings were chillingly rebuffed. She eventually gained access to
the house but left feeling her life was in danger. ''I was walking up
the path thinking, any moment now there will be a gun in my back.''
A second home where she had lived before her marriage was now occupied
by a group of nuns and as she sat chatting with them, a dog appeared at
her side. Lesley asked if they had seen another dog, her own pet
mongrel, Isla, and the nuns motioned her to the bottom of the garden
where a dog like Isla had just given birth.
Walking over what used to be her vegetable patch, one of the sisters
turned to her and whispered: ''So many have been buried here.''
''I looked down. There were bones and bits of clothing and bits of
skull all over the garden, just buried in shallow graves. I was
absolutely gutted. I was walking in the midst of it. In what used to be
my garden.''
The dog turned out to be Isla and Lesley broke down. ''It seems stupid
when I think about it to cry over a dog when there was so much human
suffering around. It was the symbolism of it . . . she represented my
life. It was so gutting and so moving.'' The nuns told her that Isla,
now skinny and flea-ridden, had grown fat after eating the human remains
littering the land.
In Butare she learned that Charles had been arrested by the army in
Gahini shortly after the crisis started in April but had been given a
lift to Butare by an army official he knew well. At the time the
university town was quiet and the murderous Interahamwe militia kept in
check. It didn't last long and the soldiers finally came for Charles in
the church guesthouse.
''They came right to his room,'' said Lesley. ''Someone must have told
them he was there. We visited the room where he was,'' she stops herself
and takes a deep breath, ''where he had been. That was very, very sad,
very, very moving. I stood in the room on my own. There was a mat on the
floor and I knelt on the floor and prayed and wept.''
She has no idea where his body lies, but expects it to be in one of
the countless mass graves around the town. With no burial and no marked
resting place, she is keeping his name alive with the Charles Bilinda
Memorial Trust -- a fund set up to provide educational opportunities for
Rwandans in the UK.
She herself is writing a book and, at 35, is still uncertain about her
own future. She will not return to Rwanda to live.
The events of the past eight months have forced her to question but
not doubt her religious faith. Asked if she can forgive those who
murdered her husband, she looks long and hard at the floor.
''Forgiveness is not an option for a Christian. It is a command,'' she
says finally and firmly. ''There is no point in harbouring bitterness
and resentment against them. They have done wrong and they will have to
answer to God.'' There is another long pause before she lifts her head
and says quietly: ''I do not hold it against them.''
* Lesley Bilinda's experiences will be the subject of a BBC2
documentary Moment of Truth next Wednesday at 8pm. Information on the
Charles Bilinda Memorial Trust can be obtained from 3 Millerfield Place,
Edinburgh, EH9 1LW.
</TEXT>
