<HEADLINE>Chancellor starts row on Scottish spending levels</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR,PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041951</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke provoked a fresh row at Westminster last
night over the level of expenditure on Scotland.
Mr Clarke said that Government expenditure per head in 1993-94 was
#3458 in England, #3913 in Wales, #4185 in Scotland and #4781 in
Northern Ireland.
The issue was raised by Tory MP Peter Viggers, who said: ''Although we
English are happy, in present circumstances to support the Scots, do you
not agree that the substantial subsidy for Scots and others might be
different if there were a tax-raising parliament in Scotland?.
''Do you agree that the Scots may face the double jeopardy of a
Scottish tax from Edinburgh and relutance from London to pay the present
20% subsidy to Scotland?''
Mr Clarke said: ''Scotland receives a considerable subsidy from
England, but that is based on the Government's judgment of needs in the
various countries, and we judge that to be the correct level of
spending.
Mr Viggers was right to say it was proposed that the Scots should have
a parliament with the ability to raise 3p in the pound on income tax.
The Chancellor told the House: ''Why one should be taxed more heavily
for working in Scotland than for working in England I am not sure, nor
am I sure what advantage it would bring to the Scots.
''The English taxpayer might ask why, if the Scots have 3p in the
pound to spare, he should continue to shift so much money north of the
Border.''
Mr Clarke said: ''Scotland receives more by way of expenditure than it
pays in taxation, but that is entirely right if a United Kingdom
Govermment and a United Kingdom parliament decide that it reflects the
needs of the population in certain areas.
''I cannot understand why it is proposed by some that if one works in
Scotland one should pay 3p more in the pound in income tax than if one
does the same job in England. I can only imagine that that is likely to
be damaging to the Scottish economy.''
</TEXT>
