<DOCNO>GH950203-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two governments begin leak inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041952</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government yesterday launched a major inquiry into the leak that
threw the Northern Ireland peace process into jeopardy.
The Prime Minister ordered the Northern Ireland Office to investigate
the source of highly damaging disclosures about UK-Irish proposals for a
political settlement.
Downing Street said the investigation would be conducted internally by
the NIO with findings reported to Cabinet Secretary Sir Robin Butler.
Irish Premier John Bruton has ordered a similar inquiry in Dublin --
but is insisting that there is no evidence to link the leak to his
government.
Downing Street yesterday refused to be drawn on the claim by deputy
Irish Premier Dick Spring that the long-delayed framework document might
be ready for publication by the end of the month.
A senior official said: ''We have never set a time limit in any event
other than to say that we would like to have the framework document
agreed as soon as possible.''
Leak inquiries in Whitehall are renowned for failing to identify
culprits, but are launched to underline ministerial disapproval.
The Northern Ireland Office was unable to give further details about
the scope of the inquiry, but it will centre on Ministers and officials
who are kept informed of UK-Irish contacts.
It was not known how many people would be involved -- the issue has
come before a Cabinet sub-committee involving non-Northern Ireland
Ministers -- or whether people outside the Government would be
questioned.
Senior Tories yesterday kept up their criticism of the the Times'
story on the leak.
The party's ex-chairman Sir Norman Fowler (Sutton Coldfield) -- a
former journalist on the paper -- said: ''It is certainly the role of
newspapers to expose the truth.''
However, he added during during exchanges on coming parliamentary
business: ''It is a matter of public concern that the Times may have
allowed itself to be used as a vehicle for propaganda in an attempt to
wreck the talks that have been going on.''
Leader of the Commons Tony Newton, noting Sir Norman's journalistic
background, said: ''I give great weight to your remarks.''
Tory Patrick Cormack (Staffordshire South) said: ''A free responsible
press is essential to the functioning of a demacracy. But an
irresponsible press can undermine democracy.''
He urged: ''Can we have a debate on the general issue of the freedom
and ethics of the press?''
Mr Newton said he would bear the request in mind and added: ''I would
hope the points you have made will be firmly registered by those
responsible for printing this story.''
He later told the House the Government will seek to renew the
Prevention of Terrorism Act.
''The Act is due for renewal by March 22 and I expect to bring forward
the necessary motion in due course.''
The legislation, renewed each year, allows terrorist suspects to be
detained for seven days without charge
</TEXT>
