<DOCNO>GH950203-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government defeated on noisy sports</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041953</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was defeated in the Lords last night as peers backed --
by eight votes -- a move to effectively ban noisy sports, like power
boat racing and motorcycle riding, from National Parks.
Voting was 129 to 121 for an amendment during the Environment Bill's
committee stage. It calls for promotion of opportunities for the ''quiet
enjoyment and understanding'' of the parks' special qualities.
An Environment Department spokesman said the Government would reflect
on the issues raised and look at the matter again when the Bill reaches
the Commons.
The Bill includes measures to establish new independent authorities
for the 10 National Parks in England and Wales.
Tory Lord Norrie, a member of the Council of National Parks, moved the
amendment saying activities in the parks should not ''intrude on the
enjoyment of others''. Pursuits should involve ''muscle power and not
motor power'', he said.
However, Environment Minister of State Viscount Ullswater opposed a
''blanket ban''.
Lord Williams of Elvel, for Labour, urged the Government to enshrine
the principle of quiet enjoyment in the Bill.
</TEXT>
