<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cannabis dealer to learn fate in 'exceptional case'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041954</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MUSICIAN will be sentenced at the High Court in Inverness today for
dealing in drugs.
David Bremner, 43, of Tain, a former nurse, has admitted being
concerned in the supply of more than 600 grammes of cannabis, as well as
four previous convictions -- three for petty theft and another
drugs-related offence.
Defence advocate, Mr Ian Duguid, told Lord MacLean yesterday that
Bremner was an ''exceptional case'' because so many people depended upon
him.
He said Bremner, who has two children, gave up a musical career in
Edinburgh to return north to look after his ailing parents and later
care for his brother's two children.
Mr Duguid revealed the brother lost his first wife in a road accident
and committed suicide after learning that his second wife was pregnant
to another man.
However, Advocate-depute Iain Bonomy, QC, painted a picture of
Bremner, of Ivy Lane, St Duthus Street, Tain, as a major player in a
commercial drug dealing operation.
Mr Bonomy said a police raid on Bremner's house discovered the haul of
cannabis, with a street value of more than #3000, and #770 cash, the
proceeds of some of his sales.
An address book detailing other drug deals worth hundreds of pounds
was also found. Mr Bonomy said Bremner confessed to police he had bought
the drug for #2900 in Edinburgh and had sold almost #1000 of it.
However, Mr Duguid said his client now maintainted some of that
confession was lies, and that the drugs had been delivered to him in
Tain. Bremner also claimed some of the figures listed in his address
book did not refer to drugs transactions.
Mr Duguid explained Bremner's route into drugs was down to his concern
for the welfare of his family.
''Because he spent so much time looking after his family, he was
unable to fulfil as many musical engagements and the debts mounted up,
leading to his drugs involvement.
''Shortly after his arrest, his mother died and Bremner has devoted
all his days and nights to his father, who was taken into hospital
yesterday, still not knowing his son is facing this serious charge.
''His wife is also so physically and mentally ill, she cannot face
attending court today. He is also devoted to her and his two children.
Who knows what will happen to them if he is sent to jail?
''I am not suggesting that anyone dealing in drugs should escape a
lengthy custodial sentence, but Mr Bremner is an exceptional case and
may deserve an exceptional disposal.''
Deferring sentence, Lord MacLean said Bremner ''was only exceptional
because so many people around him depend upon him. I don't find this at
all easy. It is an unusual, if not an exceptional, case and I will
consider it overnight''.
</TEXT>
