<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Catholic Church cuts debt by over #2m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGINTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041956</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO years after Cardinal Winning announced that the Archdiocese of
Glasgow was #9.2m in the red, the debt has been cut by more than #2m.
Spending cuts, sales of surplus Church assets, and weekly collections
appear to be working.
Last year, weekly collections raised #950,000, bringing the total
donated since the cardinal's appeal to #2m. However, the Church urges
that the high level of donations continues.
A spokesman said: ''At this rate, we are very confident that we will
be able to reduce the debt to #4m by the end of this year.''
Since the debt was announced, the Archdiocese has undertaken a
rigorous cost-cutting operation, which involved redundancies and strict
budget cuts.
Twelve acres of land in Bearsden has been sold for #2.25m. The lion's
share will go to Glasgow but parts will be distributed to the dioceses
of Motherwell and Paisley.
The archdiocese has sold the former Pastoral Centre at Briar Road,
Newlands, for #2.1m, but will retain part of the eight-acre site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Second Scottish school clears hurdle to opt-out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY MCBAIN,EDUCATION CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041957</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PRIMARY in Dunblane is set to become the second school in Scotland
to opt out of local authority control after a dispute about the sale of
the building was resolved.
The board of the 150-year-old St Mary's Episcopalian school began
moves to secure self-governing status more than two years ago, a move
opposed by Central Region.
In a ballot more than 75% of parents voted for opting out, but this
was delayed when the then Bishop of St Andrews, Dunkeld, and Dunblane,
the Rt Rev Michael Hare Duke -- the Episcopalian-owned school's only
remaining trustee -- asked for guarantees about St Mary's future before
he would agree its sale.
Scottish Office school inspectors could not act on the opt out vote
until the sale issue was settled.
With Bishop Hare Duke's retiral, this has been resolved. The new
temporary trustee, the Very Rev Ian Watt, Dean of St Andrews, Dunkeld,
and Dunblane, confirmed last night that he had agreed to approve the
sale.
The school board chairman, Mr Alan Bateman, said he was ''quite
pleased'' by Scottish Secretary Ian Lang's announcement that he would
approve the board's proposals, subject to further consultation.
Mr Bateman said: ''It has been a long slog. After the Bishop retired
last October the Dean took over as trustee until a new Bishop is in
place. We had discussions with Mr Watt and we have agreed that we can
now go ahead.
''The school will be valued by the district valuer. If the board,
Scottish Office, and church agree a figure the Secretary of State will
provide funds to buy the school.''
But Central Region last night attacked Mr Lang's decision. Its leader,
Councillor Corrie McChord, said: ''We are very disappointed that common
sense has not prevailed. We have great concerns about the viability of
such a small school going it alone . . . a planning application is
sitting with Stirling district for a brand-new school just a quarter of
a mile away.''
Mr Lang said the board would need to change its proposals for
admissions because they favoured Episcopalian children.
But Mr Bateman, who has two children at the school but who is not
Episcopalian, said the board knew the admissions' policy would have to
be changed.
Under opting out the school will be funded directly by the Scottish
Office and run by a board of management with an in-built parental
majority.
Mr Lang said the school could be self-governing in the next school
session, which begins in August.
Central Region planned to build a new school to replace St Mary's and
cope with an expected influx of children from new housing developments
but parents fought to keep St Mary's.
The only other opted out school in Scotland is Dornoch Academy, a
two-year secondary in the Highlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041958</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MY art teacher, the legendary Ralph Cowan, once gave our class a title
and a theme for a figure composition. It was ''The Demonstration''. We
had to have at least three people and one of the figures had to be in
front of another one and the composition had to have a structure which
could be analysed in terms of Rembrandt. Ralph has awfully high
standards, believe me.
This was the mid-fifties. Mr Cowan was a well-kent chap who had
designed much of the wonderful glass work in the Queen Elizabeth the
first (the ship that is), and his work can be seen to this day, albeit
only in America. He sported lovat-coloured suits and waistcoats and
splendidly artistic woven ties, and wore his hair, proudly, long and
distinguished. It was he, who following an outrage upon my person by the
science department of my school, or at least an especially psychotic
representative of it, for my abject failure in some examination . . . it
was Ralph Cowan who drew me aside and commiserated with me. ''My boy,
they are nothing but Philistines,'' he informed me, ignorant as I was of
the tribe save for rather basic scriptural knowledge, ''but We Shall Win
in The End''.
I am not sure We ever do, but it was nice to have this awesome and
elegant dominie and artist tell me convincing and heart-warming lies at
that, even if the hands were dropping off me. And Ralph gave us this
title and theme: ''The Demonstrators''.
The mid to late fifties saw, suddenly, lots of demonstrations. By
people. They were then, and probably quite rightly too, regarded as a
touch crankish. More than that, it seemed to a generation who had seen a
deal too much public disorder during the Depression years, and too much
overheated nonsense over Spain, for instance, and too many Communist
Party members dissenting about fighting the Nazis -- and too much public
shows from the great dictatorships of the world. Crowds of demonstrators
were to be found not merely in Europe, from Soviet Russia to Hitler's
Rhinelands: the United States crowds would assemble for anything from
support for the German bunds to weeping hordes for Father Coughlan; from
evangelists to lynch mobs.
The average British citizen felt uneasy about large groups of people
gathering together to make a collective point and they were right and
wrong about it. Wrong because legitimate protest is legitimate -- if
there are elderly, for they must be by now, men and women who ever stood
in decency and a vigil outside a prison in which some unfortunate was to
be hanged in the early hours of the morning, if there are those out
there I applaud you. For the equally elderly who still get together at a
centopaph, I feel grateful to you for your display. There are, I am
sure, many worthy shows of concern and solidarity. Not the least of them
being political demos.
I yet remember the surge of concern over Vietnam, and over Ireland
when the peace people in both concerns impressed, but not enough. Or the
civil rights marches throughout the US, or even the student demos for
decent grants. I harbour a faint admiration for the frisson created by
the mass action of French students in 1968, or for the American students
who hit the Chicago Convention. But at the end of it all, I still worry
about demonstrations.
Why a group of utterly unelected people should exert so much influence
-- if they do, and sometimes it is so -- is hardly right. The churches,
for instance, have contrived to stop me from having a drink in a hotel
bar on a Sunday before half-past midday, simply because they insist on
such a process. Regular churchgoers make up less than 4% of the Scottish
population. They once had even larger powers of control over the
remaining 96% of the Scottish people. And you should worry about that.
Just as you should about the largely silly people who have been
attempting to stop the export of veal calves. One poor demonstrator has
been killed through an excess of zeal, not veal. Do not believe for one
minute that, should the demonstrators get their way and close down this
industry, they will stop there. I ate veal last night, in the splended
Idries Hotel in Forfar. A Marsala sauce it was. I eat this rather
tasteless, but beautifully textured cut often. When in Italy I eat
vitellone, which is the calf slaughtered before it stops suckling.
Dressed and dredged in flour and breadcrumbs, it is delicious. Even
better in the Hungarian style with hot cherry paprikas and noodles and a
wine vinegar sauce. Poor little calves with their big eyes, the
four-footed version of Leslie Caron. They would not even be bred if we
did not eat them.
But the demonstrators are out there, demanding, well, just demanding.
And they will not stop there at all. They will eventually try to stop
meat. Or fish. Or eggs. The oceans will be overflowing with floating
corpses of fish. Animals will not be bred at all. The farmers will kill
the animals they cannot support. They will breed no further progeny.
Vegans will have no butter or milk or cream or cheese. A sports
colleague of mine from a sister paper tells me he is going to eat
nothing but veal for a fortnight just out of badness. I think he is
being a touch cowardly. I'm thinking of eating vegans myself, sauced and
marinated. A demonstration, if you like, with a lot of style at that. I
learned it from Ralphie Cowan, my old art teacher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>London and Dublin in desperate attemps to keep the peace process going.    Major reassures MPs on document</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041959</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister yesterday urged MPs to wait for the publication of
the controversial framework document on Northern Ireland, study it in
its entirety and recognise it was for consultation.
He told the Commons nothing would be imposed on the people of Northern
Ireland and reinforced his assurances to Unionists that they had nothing
to fear from the peace process.
His comments to MPs followed his televised appeal on Wednesday night
for people in the Province to give him time and trust, in a bid to
defuse the row over a leaked draft of the document.
Mr Major earlier yesterday ordered the Northern Ireland Office to
investigate the source of the highly damaging disclosures about
Anglo-Irish proposals for a political settlement.
At Question Time, Labour leader Tony Blair offered the Prime Minister
his party's full and continued support for the peace process.
In exchanges, Mr Major said: ''There is a communal will not to be
distracted from the goal of a peaceful and permanent and agreed
settlement in Northern Ireland.''
He later added: ''The end is very straightforward and a very simple
one: to end the horrors of the last 25 years, and to make sure that
never again do people get killed month after month after month after
month, as they have in the last 25 years.''
Raising the issue, Labour's John Home Robertson said the Ulster
Unionist Party's William Ross (Londonderry East) had claimed Mr Major's
Northern Ireland initiative was now dead and buried.
Mr Home Robertson, MP for East Lothian, demanded: ''Would it not be an
affront to all the soldiers and the civilians who have been killed and
buried over the last 25 years if this initiative were to be jeopardised
as a result of a malicious, partial leak of a draft framework document?
''All our constituents are getting very weary of the ancient refrain
of 'Ulster says no', which is still being parroted by some Unionist
Members -- but thankfully only some Unionist Members.''
Mr Major replied: ''I believe there is a wish right across the House,
including those Members who represent Northern Ireland, to find a
satisfactory way forward. I have not a shred of doubt about that.
''We have all watched with dismay the activities of the last 25 years.
''Members who represent Ulster have lived through that in a way you
and I haven't.
''I've no doubt from my contact with Members in Northern Ireland -- on
points on which we agree and on points on which we do not agree -- about
their sincerity in seeking to bring to a conclusion the miseries of the
last 25 years.''
Mr Nigel Waterson (Eastbourne -- Con.) told Mr Major: ''The goal of a
peaceful settlement in Ulster is worthy of the courage and patience you
have demonstrated.
''Will you continue to assure the people of that Province that any
final decision will always rest with them?''
Mr Major replied: ''There is a communal will not to be distracted from
the goal of a peaceful and permanent and agreed settlement in Northern
Ireland.
''I am happy to repeat the assurance that I've given on occasions in
the past: the outcome of the political talks -- after the main
constiutional parties have met and agreed the outcome -- that outcome
will be put to people in a referendum before further action is taken.
''It is they who will decide, and nothing will be imposed upon them.''
After Mr Blair told him: ''On Northern Ireland, you have our full and
continued support,'' Mr Major replied: ''I appreciate the support of
Labour and other parties as far as Northern Ireland is concerned, and I
think it is a strength of the process that there is such widespread
support for it.''
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown, who as an officer once saw
service in Northern Ireland, told him: ''For as long as you put the
peace of Ireland first, you will command the overwhelming majority of
this House and the country.
''Those who would put in jeopardy the peace of Ireland to pursue
either narrow sectarian agendas, or internal party power struggles, will
meet the opposition of this House and earn the contempt of the
country.''
Mr Major said: ''I'm grateful for your support. Let me say: there is
nothing in the peace process which any party in this House need fear.
''There can be no slippery slope in any process which firstly requires
the agreement of all the parties and then, after the agreement of the
parties has been obtained, subsequently requires the agreement of the
people of Northern Ireland themselves.''
Responding to barracking from Labour left-winger Dennis Skinner
(Bolsover), the Prime Minister said: ''The end is very straightforward
and a very simple one: to end the horrors of the last 25 years, and to
make sure that never again do people get killed month after month after
month after month, as they have in the last 25 years.''
He told Mr Skinner: ''I would have hoped even you would have supported
that enterprise.''
</TEXT>
