<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lacklustre My Piece of Foreign Sky, Cottier Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SARA VILLIERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041960</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the evidence of this very lacklustre production by Irresistible
Flood the promise which young playwright Lara Jane Bunting has
previously shown would appear to be waning. It's debatable whether her
choice of subject -- pit closures in Ayrshire -- is either tired and
unimaginative or bold and defiantly unfashionable but her treatment is
vapid.
The theme is unoriginal: a crisis exposing cracks in a seemingly happy
family unit. Sanny and his son Lex, both miners, are divided in their
reaction to imminent pit closure. Sanny, emotionally diminished by the
eighties strike, sees no option but redundancy. Lex wants to fight. His
mother Nell fails to conceal her relief that the mine is to close,
thereby irritating Lex's fiance, Ellen, who discerns Nell's
disappointment that her son chose a small-town life. The resultant
domestic tensions are predictable and humdrum, with Bunting failing to
mesh the strained exchanges into any kind of dramatic climax.
She hints at more interesting dynamics but fails to focus on them,
with the result that the character's dilemmas are completely
uninvolving. There is also a heavy-handed use of symbolism; a large
wedding cake onstage is slowly stripped of decoration as the betrothed
couple's life becomes austere. Most irritating is Nell's incessant
invocation of a twee poem To My Child, the concluding line of which
inspired the play's title.
The experienced Mary McCluskey's direction is surprisingly turgid and
the lighting is appalling. The only consolation is in the performances,
with Kirsty Wells, Diane Sobolewska, David Fehilly, and David McGowan
struggling admirably to inject the proceedings with some passion and
verve.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Morris hits at Labour 'insults'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041961</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Labour hierarchy has unleashed ''the dogs of war'' on union leader
Bill Morris (above) over his opposition to redrafting Clause 4 of the
party constitution on public ownership, Mr Morris claimed yesterday.
Within hours of the Transport and General Workers' Union leader making
his position clear, anonymous senior Labour sources were briefing the
press insultingly about his ''confused, muddled and pusillanimous''
behaviour, he told the Spectator magazine.
''The dogs of war were unleashed against me but I am not bothered. My
street credibility rises every time they attack me,'' he said.
The comments will come as a bitter blow to Labour leader Tony Blair,
who is conducting a nationwide campaign to secure universal backing for
his call for the end of Clause 4.
Mr Morris said he had been waiting for ''men in white coats to take me
away because I was diagnosed as muddled and confused.''
He added: ''For them (Blair's advisers), it's got to be total victory
over people who dare contribute to the debate . . . we have got to be
trampled, crushed, annihilated and humiliated''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Making waves</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>CHECK OUT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>980041962</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE should overcome their awe of the hi-tech nature of microwave
ovens and trust their common sense as they do with conventional ovens, a
food engineer warned yesterday in the wake of fears that a voltage
reduction in mains electricity throughout the UK will affect the
performance of some microwave ovens.
Steve James, a research engineer who has been working with microwave
ovens for 15 years at Bristol University's food refrigeration and
process engineering research centre, said that only two of the five
ovens they tested remained stable down to the new minimum permissible
level of 216 volts.
The electricity companies, including Scottish Power, say that the
change from 240 volts to 230 to bring Britain into line with the rest of
Europe should have no noticeable effect on domestic appliances, although
they acknowledge that microwaves will be the most sensitive to a
reduction.
Since ordinary consumers have no way of telling which ovens are
susceptible or when the voltage is particularly low, they should apply
the obvious test of whether the food is piping hot and remember that Mr
James also found that longer cooking at a slightly lower temperature
resulted in better-tasting food.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Call for health service inquiry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041963</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Commons Select Committee on Scottish Affairs has been asked to
undertake an inquiry into the state of the health service by Mr Jimmy
Hood, Labour MP for Clydesdale.
He said Scottish Health Minister, Lord Fraser, could not offer him any
assurances that Law Hospital, Carluke, in his constituency, where the
casualty department almost closed, or any other such department, would
not be threatened with closure.
</TEXT>
