<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bringing it home</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041964</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARKS and Spencers' prestige Princes Street store is spearheading a
back-to-basics initiative that could see a return of ''corner shop''
service for millions of customers.
Along with the branches at Kensington and Marble Arch, Princes Street
is launching a food-delivery service from next Monday. For just #5 food
can be stored and delivered to homes and businesses in a wide area of
Edinburgh -- with punctuality guaranteed.
The service has been welcomed by Edinburgh District Council as an
imaginative contribution to its campaign to improve the environment in
the city centre.
''It should encourage more people to leave their cars at home,
relieving them about worries of where to park and the city of added
congestion,'' said the store's deputy general manager, Mr Paul
Stephenson, last night.
''We are proud to have been chosen from nearly 300 Marks and Spencers
stores to trial this service -- it's a return to old-fashioned values
and we are confident it will be popular with our customers.
''As fas as the #5 charge is concerned, this should be quickly
recouped on savings in petrol and parking fees -- you may also benefit
from being able to order a larger wine pack with a free extra bottle!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rolls-Royce staff to take their jobs fight to Germany and US</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN,POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041965</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STAFF at the Rolls-Royce design plant in East Kilbride faced with
redundancy will take their case to Germany and the United States in an
attempt to persuade the company's business partners of the damage the
decision to transfer 600 highly-skilled jobs to Derby will cause.
Trade union representatives told MPs at Westminster yesterday that
they have approached BRR, the German-based BMW-Rolls Royce consortium
designing the next generation of jet engine, to warn that the British
job losses will harm their project.
Mr Owen Thomas, chairman of the joint staff unions, said: ''We are
contacting partner companies in joint ventures and letting them know
what the effect will be. We know they are concerned about this.''
The transfer of the jobs, which shocked Scottish manufacturing
industry circles when it was announced last month, will have a knock-on
effect by delaying the completion of current work.
Trade unions believe BRR, and airframe manufacturer McDonnell-Douglas
in the United States, will be concerned at the implications of delays
for their own production and marketing schedules, as they are dependent
on the delivery of new engines designs from East Kilbride.
Mr Larry Brooke, national officer of the MSF science union, said:
''Highly skilled jobs are being wasted by this decision of Rolls Royce.
Slimming down has reached the point where it is becoming anorexia.''
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said the workforce would be
receiving strong support from Labour. ''It is at the cutting edge of
aerospace technology. Its highly skilled workforce has been cut back in
some blind attempt to rationalise.
''No doubt that proposal poses a real danger to those vital BRR
projects for new engines. All the indications coming back from Germany
show huge nervousness at the fact that people are going to be
dismayed.''
The trade unions, who hope to travel to Germany to meet BRR
representatives in the coming weeks, will also be seeking to enlist the
support of Mr Ken Collins, MEP for Strathclyde East and chairman of the
influential chairmens' committee in the European Parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A man of creative recreation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041966</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHETHER by word, deed or garb Sir Nicholas Fairbairn has always gone
out of his way to cultivate a richly colourful image, not least in his
many self-penned entries for Who's Who.
''Author, painter, poet, TV and radio broadcaster, dress-designer,
landscape gardener, bon viveur and wit'' was his most literal
self-descrption. Others have been more eliptical, as he has regularly
changed the list of his recreations. At one time he suggested his spare
time was spent seeking ''the cure and eradication of British tick
fever''.
On other occasions he has alluded to his affection for the opposite
sex, describing his interests as ''philanthropy and philogyny'' or
''loving beauty and beautifying love''. More obscure was ''growling,
prowling, scowling and owling'', and most recently ''drawing ships,
making quips, confounding Whips, scuttling drips''. At least there could
be no argument about confounding the Whips.
No-one has ever accused him of mincing his words or hiding his
opinions, and among those he laid into or praised during his interview
with The Herald were:
* Robert Burns -- ''a false hero, a drunken, fornicating, roustabout
and social creep. What's heroic about a lot of shit-awful poetry?
* Hugh MacDiarmid -- ''a better poet, and certainly much more of a
character.''
* Former judge Lord Grant -- ''a frightful man who used to say: 'Mr
Fairbairn, please don't be even more stupid than you can help and do not
keep misleading the jury!'''
* Former judge Lord Clyde -- ''Although he was a frightful,
unprincipled rogue, I was rather fond of Clyde.''
* Former judge Lord Wheatley -- ''that puritan fanatic, a Catholic
aesthete.''
* His son, the current Sheriff -- ''a delight, extremely amusing and
charming and very good on the Bench.''
* The current Lord President, Lord Hope -- ''To say Lord Hope is grey
is being rude to porridge.''
* The former Soviet Union -- ''It is breaking up and you will be left
with these dozens of mini-states which will be very difficult to
control. I went into a shed in Russia and there were these atomic
rockets just lying around the floor. I said: 'Please remember to close
the door after I am gone.' Terrifying!''
* Africa -- ''This vast continent, of innumerable people, ruled over
by totally corrupt dicators of one kind and another, all with millions
stashed in offshore banks.
* Britain -- ''The Commonwealth is a an extremely outmoded piece of
sentimental British left-overs. That's our dilemma really, I suppose.
The Commonwealth is irrelevant. We're left spooning around pretending to
love Europe when we don't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crumlin Road jail faces closure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041967</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Belfast's Crumlin Road jail is facing closure in a move which could
threaten prison officers' jobs, it was revealed yesterday. Authorities
confirmed they are considering a proposal to shut the facility within
three years as part of a major review of Northern Ireland's prison
system.
</TEXT>
