<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stake-out at Hilton in catnapping case</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041969</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BUILDER appeared in court yesterday accused of kidnapping a cat and
demanding #10,000 for its release.
The Persian cat was reunited with its owner on Tuesday at a meeting at
London's Hilton Hotel in Mayfair, almost a week after it was allegedly
taken.
''Are cats allowed at the Hilton?'' asked the magistrate, Mr Geoffrey
Breen, at Horseferry Road Court. ''Evidently, yes,'' replied the
prosecutor.
The case is believed to be the first of its kind in Britain.
Nigel Bass, 32, of Shepherd's Bush, was granted bail at #5000. He was
charged with demanding #10,000 with menaces from Miss Ilona Szekeres, a
property developer, for the return of her valuable and much-loved cat.
He was also charged with stealing the cat from her home in Clapham,
south London, on January 25.
Miss Szekeres accompanied undercover detectives to collect her cat at
the Hilton.
Two men who made alleged telephone threats to harm the cat are still
being sought.
The prosecution asked for Mr Bass, a former business associate of the
cat's owner, to be remanded in custody. However the magistrate bailed
him after a plea from his solicitor, who said Mr Bass would live with
his wife and two children at the family home in Devon if freed.
Mr Bass was banned from London as a condition of bail, and ordered not
to contact Miss Szekeres, 35.
Mr Bass's wife stood as a #1000 surety, but he is being kept in
custody until his mother comes forward as a second surety of #4000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Museums apply for #7m from lottery</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041970</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE weekly attempts of punters to strike it rich in the National
Lottery, could help Scotland to display the evidence of its human and
natural history.
The trustees of the National Museums of Scotland have submitted a bid
to the Heritage Lottery Fund for a #7.25m grant towards installing the
exhibitions in the Museum of Scotland being built in Edinburgh.
The printed proposal, arguing the project's case, was flown to the
Heritage Lottery Fund in London earlier this week.
It said: ''With your support, the new museum will open to
international acclaim in 1998 and provide a continuing asset of
incalculable value for generations yet to come.''
A spokeswoman for the trustees said yesterday they were optimistic
about the outcome of the application.
The grant would be equally matched with funds raised from the private
sector for the installation of the 10,000 items in the exhibitions.
The Government has already committed #30m to pay for the construction
of the building in Chambers Street and the NMS is financing expenditure
of around #17m over eight years.
The application said: ''This long cherished and deeply felt national
ambition can only be realised by a partnership between the private
sector and the Heritage Lottery Fund.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drugs garden at lighthouse that lit up with joints</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041971</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNNET in Caithness seemed sufficiently remote to the occupant of the
old lighthouse there to justify the risk of setting up a
cannabis-growing operation.
John Sutherland, 50, eventually had 192 growing plants and the
necessary lighting equipment in a cellar under lighthouse's former
engine room.
Sutherland, a musician who performs under the stage name Johnny Fats,
also had smaller amounts of the drug in the former keeper's cottage
where he lived.
At the High Court in Inverness yesterday Sutherland admitted producing
cannabis, possessing the drug, and possession with intent to supply. The
offences took place between January and July 1993 at the Dunnet
lighthouse keeper's cottages.
Advocate-depute Iain Bonomy said police who arrived for a search found
Sutherland with two friends and two bags of herbal cannabis.
They found other small amounts of the drug in Sutherland's cottage and
the one next door, then brought in a sniffer dog which took them to the
lighthouse's former engine room.
They opened a trap-door leading to the cellar and found 152 plants and
growing equipment. Then another trap-door leading to another part of the
cellar was opened to reveal 40 larger plants.
Sutherland told officers at the time: ''You have got me cold. I am
against the other drugs the same as you are, but they should legalise
cannabis.''
Mr Bonomy said it was not easy to calculate the value of the 1338g of
cannabis found, but it was estimated to be #6690. He accepted that
Sutherland was not putting the drugs on the market.
Defence advocate Ian Duguid said Sutherland, who had previous
convictions for drugs offences, had been a cannabis user for 26 years.
He said Sutherland had no intention to sell the drugs commercially.
Instead he used the cannabis himself and provided it socially for
friends who visited. He said their value to a user was closer to #1500.
''His is purely a social supply which might be the equivalent of
providing a drink at a cocktail party.''
Mr Duguid added: ''He considers himself a connoisseur because of his
experience and his use.''
Lord MacLean said Sutherland was ''something of a campaigner'' after
hearing he had used the drug for half his life and believed it should be
legalised.
He deferred sentence until February 23 in Edinburgh for a community
service report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EC approves oil centre rescue plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041972</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future of an #8m research and development drilling facility in
Aberdeen looks to have been secured following European Commission
approval for debts totalling almost #2m to be written off.
The EC backed a proposal by Scottish Enterprise to convert loans from
Scottish Enterprise and Grampian Regional Council totalling #1,825,000
into a grant to help save and financially restructure the International
Drilling and Downhole Technology Centre (IDDTC).
It employs 13 staff full-time and during special projects hires up to
six more to run its 182ft onshore rig and associated facilities.
A peculiarity of the IDDTC is that the research and development work
is conducted by the clients and not by the centre itself.
The Herald understands that talks are already at an advanced stage on
the possibility of either a joint venture agreement or a management
contract covering the centre's future operation.
Last night Mr Hamish Dingwall of Scottish Enterprise's energy group
welcomed the decision. He said: ''It is our view that the reduction of
the financial burden on the centre will encourage more private sector
participation, thereby securing its long term future to provide open
access research, development and testing facilities to the international
oil and gas industry.''
The IDDTC is a non-profit making organisation which provides an
independent facility for companies to develop drilling equipment and
techniques without the risks and costs associated with testing on live
wells.
It was conceived during the oil slump of 1986 and seemed assured of
success -- since one day's lost drilling offshore could pay for up to 20
days of testing at the centre, but loan commitments have prevented it
taking off.
When in 1990 then Industry and Education Minister Ian Lang ''spudded''
the first well just a few hundred yards from Aberdeen beach at the
Bridge of Don it was expected the IDDTC might generate 1000 jobs for
Scotland.
In spite of its anticipated potential, the turnover has never exceeded
#500,000 in the past three years' of operation.
The EC heard that the Scottish Enterprise plan was a one-off measure,
necessary to save the centre because its turnover was too small to
generate enough profits to repay its debts.
The EC was also told that the IDDTC had taken steps to assure its
future viability including the reduction of costs and the implementation
of new projects.
The Scottish Enterprise proposal had been approved by the Scottish
Office but required EC approval to ensure it did not distort European
competition.
The EC decided the conversion of the loans into grants would not
threaten or distort competition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A working class hero of the Centre Court</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>OBITUARY</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980041973</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRED Perry was a people's champion, rising from workingclass, Northern
English roots to win a hat-trick of Wimbledon titles between 1934-36.
His background was a world away from the privilege and patronage which
typified tennis between the wars, and it was once said that the
Stockport-raised son of a Labour MP was born with a wooden spoon in his
mouth.
''It didn't help to have a heavy eh-bah-goom accent and a dad who was
storming the hustings as one of those dangerous new-fangled Labour and
Trade Union candidates. They didn't like me,'' he once declared.
Perry was virtually ostracised by the tennis establishment when he
dared to turn professional shortly after completing the third of his
centre court singles triumphs.
Frederick John Perry was born on May 18, 1909. He was 25-years-old
when he beat Australian Jack Crawford in 1934 to capture the first leg
of his Wimbledon triple crown.
The following year he beat German Baron, Gottfried Von Cramm, to
retain his title and completed the hat-trick in 1936, when he demolished
Von Cramm again -- 6-1 6-1 6-0 -- in a 40-minute final, the shortest
this century.
In his teens Perry flirted for a while with table tennis, becoming
world champion in 1929, before concentrating on tennis.
His game was built on his running forehand, fitness and stamina,
something he worked on tirelessly after losing a series of five-set
finals, training at Highbury with the then great Arsenal football team.
His hard work was rewarded not only by success at Wimbledon, but with
a hat-trick of US singles titles -- in 1933, 1934 and 1936 -- and one
each at the French (1935) and Australian (1934) championships.
In 1933 he clinched the decisive fifth match victory over Andre Merlin
to bring the Davis Cup back to Britain for the first time since 1911.
Perry joined the pioneer professional ranks at the age of 27 in the US
in 1936.
Newspaper headlines had it that Perry had swapped ''Glory for Gold'',
while Wimbledon showed its disapproval by withdrawing his honorary
membership and asking for the return of its tie.
Perry became a US citizen in 1939, served as a staff sergeant in the
US Army, owned a tennis club in Hollywood, and later became director and
professional coach at a Florida hotel.
He was married for the first time in 1935 to American actress Helen
Vinson, ''on a sudden impulse'', but they were divorced five years
later.
Subsequent marriages to fashion model Sandra Breaux and to Lorraine
Pidgeon, sister of actor Walter Pidgeon, ended in divorce after four and
six years respectively.
Perry finally found happiness with fourth wife Barbara ''Bobby''
Friedman, the sister of British actress Patricia Roc. They were married
in 1953 and had two children, Penny and David.
The festering wounds inflicted by the tennis establishment ran deep --
''I can still get angry when I think of the shabby way I was treated,''
he said recently -- but Perry still felt a great attachment to Britain
and kept a home in Rottingdean, Sussex. He was also a regular tennis
commentator for BBC radio.
Shortly before his death he admitted: ''If someone said, 'Fred, you've
got one more set left before you die', I would choose the Centre Court
at Wimbledon. That would be lovely.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cash crisis threatens police cover as crime rates fall 5%</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041974</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEWS of a further drop in crime figures and an urgent cash crisis
which threatens police cover produced a bitter-sweet day for law
enforcement in Strathclyde yesterday.
While members of Strathclyde Regional Council's police and fire
committee were delighted to hear of a 5% reduction in crime last year,
they were alarmed when Chief Constable Leslie Sharp revealed a #750,000
gap in his current budget that would lead to his force being ''fully
stretched'' from now until the start of the new financial year in April.
The Chief Constable said: ''I just hope I don't get a series of
murders between now and the first of April because there's no way I can
react to them.''
The situation has arisen out of the latest pay settlement in which
inspectors and chief inspectors are no longer entitled to overtime,
although they have been given an enhanced pay award to compensate --
something in the region of #3600 per annum.
The argument is that the savings in overtime will off-set the salary
enhancement. However, it will take two years of operation to achieve the
level of savings required.
An anxious Chief Constable said: ''I'm left with #750,000 to find from
this year's current budget by the end of the financial year which is
rapidly coming upon us.
''We've been told to find that from our resources. We'll save it in
two years, but it doesn't help me in January 1995. The only option I've
got at this late stage of the financial year is to cut overtime. I'm
going to have to take policemen off the beat and use ordinary time for
things like policing football matches.''
Liberal Democrat member Keith Moody stated: ''We've been short-changed
by the Scottish Office.''
However, the Chief Constable said his forthcoming annual report would
show a further decline in the crime rate. He was particularly pleased
with the dramatic success rate in detecting housebreakings which he said
was due to Operation Turnkey.
He stated: ''In my next annual report you'll see that crime over the
year has dropped another 5% in 1994. There were over 14,000 fewer crimes
in Strathclyde last year than there were the year previously. This is
quite remarkable, because the previous year itself showed a 10.8%
reduction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tax policy is solid, says Robertson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041975</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR moved yesterday to damp down any suggestion that its policy on
tax-raising powers for a Scottish parliament was being reopened for
debate.
The Shadow Scottish Secretary, Mr George Robertson, predicted that the
issue would not even be discussed at conference in Inverness next month.
He said the policy was absolutely solid and there was no pressure to
change it. It gives a Scottish parliament the power to raise or lower
income tax by up to 3p in the pound to supplement the block grant from
the Exchequer, and was agreed with the party's Liberal Democrat partners
on the Scottish Constitutional Convention.
Mr Robertson said that even if an amendment referring the question
back to the Scottish Labour Party's national policy forum for fresh
consideration was accepted, it was unlikely that the conference would
find time to debate it.
Scottish Labour Action, a strongly pro-home rule grouping, has been
pushing resolutions to conference stressing the party's commitment to a
parliament with strong economic powers.
This prompted one amendment, essentially more cautious, from Mr Jim
Stevens, an economist at the Fraser of Allender Institute and member of
the party's Scottish executive.
Mr Jim Wallace, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, welcomed Mr
Robertson's rejection of any softening on the issue. He felt the power
to set tax rates was essential for proper accountability. ''This is the
settled and strongly held view of the SLD and the agreed policy of the
Scottish Constitutional Convention.''
Mrs Margaret Ewing, the SNP's parliamentary leader, seized on Labour's
situation as evidence that its devolution scheme was ''unravelling
before our eyes''.
She said: ''After coming under scrutiny in England, the Labour
leadership is worried about reaction to their proposals for English
regional assemblies and could well be considering trimming and hedging
on the whole package, including the Scottish assembly.''
Labour's front-bench spokesman on constitutional change, Mr Kim
Howells, said that with Scotland having separate legal and educational
systems the Scottish parliament was bound to have a greater workload
than Welsh or English regional assemblies, and therefore required
different powers.
He denied the suggestion made in some quarters that as an
anti-devolutionist in the past he had been put in to slow the pace of
change this time.
He said: ''I deny that totally,'' but added: ''I have always been know
as someone who cannot abide nationalism and that is still my attitude. I
am not interested in creating statelets. I did not join the Labour Party
to Balkanise the United Kingdom.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Supporting player who stole the show</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>OBITUARY</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980041976</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HE was master of the sinister sneer, an arch villain of the cinema
whose pale blue eyes could send shudders down the spine. But Donald
Pleasence was a much more substantial actor than any resume of his
celluloid career would suggest.
For some reason he never quite achieved the heights of his profession
in the theatre, in spite of the fact that in 1960 he created one of the
great roles of post-war drama, the malevolent tramp, Davies, in Harold
Pinter's play The Caretaker.
He was never a leading member of the National Theatre or the Royal
Shakespeare Theatre companies and, for that reason, some of the great
classic stage roles eluded him. This was in spite of the fact that the
quality of his theatre work in 1958 made him a star in the UK and on
Broadway where he won a Tony.
In the cinema, he created memorable villains, including one of James
Bond's most evil foes, Ernst Stavro Blofeld in You Only Live Twice, the
film which probably most people remember.
Oddly, he was a last minute addition to the cast after the Czech
actor, Jan Werich, fell ill. Written by Roald Dahl, it was the first
time Bond confronted the arch villain face to face.
Pleasence, who died yesterday at his home in France aged 75, was born
in Worksop, Nottinghamshire, where his father was a station master. He
started acting as a child and auditioned for the Royal Academy of
Dramatic Art when he left school, but was told to come back when he was
bigger. His size was always a factor in his career.
He turned instead to repertory, starting as an assistant stage manager
in 1939 at the Playhouse, Jersey, and made his first London appearance
three years later at the Arts theatre in Twelfth Night. He registered as
a conscientious objector, but ended up serving in the Royal Air Force
and flew 60 bomber missions over France until he was shot down in 1944,
spending the last year of the war in a German prison camp.
After the war he returned to the theatre and the usual round of
repertory companies in Bristol and Birmingham, at the Royal Court, and
Stratford. It was not until the end of the 1950s that he began to
achieve recognition.
Several small parts in British films, the first being The Beachcomber
in 1954, followed before he established himself as a notable screen
villain in 1962 as Dr Crippen opposite Coral Browne. His screen career
took off from there and he made over 130 films -- at one point in the
1970s he was making up to four a year.
His last film to go on release in Britain was Hour of the Pig, a
medieval drama in which he played a corrupt priest. His first Hollywood
film was The Great Escape, which starred Steve McQueen, made in 1963,
the same year in which he repeated the role of Davies in the screen
version of The Caretaker.
He starred in the first of the Hallowe'en films, made in 1978, as the
psychiatrist who solved the murders, and appeared in all the sequels
except Hallowe'en Three. He was doing post-production work on Hallowe'en
Six at the time of his death.
However, it would do him an injustice if he were remembered only for
roles like these, and certainly for that series, because it declined in
quality as each one appeared.
He denied being a film star, insisting, probably with some justice,
that he was a feature player who sometimes got star billing. As a
supporting player who could lend distinction to a film, he was second to
none.
His close friend, David Giles, who directed him in the BBC classic
series, The Barchester Chronicles, said he had been undervalued as an
actor, probably because his height was against him or because of the
fact he never played any of the great classic roles.
''He was a perfectionist,'' he said.
Some of his more notable films, none of them horror movies, were
Soldier Blue, Night of the Generals -- he specialised in rather nasty
Nazis -- Cul de Sac, The Black Windmill, and Woody Allen's Shadows and
Fog. On television he starred in many productions, including Blade on
the Feather, Witness for the Prosecution, and Scoop.
He repeated his role of Davies in the 1990 West End revival of the
play and reaffirmed that he had made it his own. In the London theatre
he also gave memorable performances in The Lark, The Rules of the Game,
The Man in the Glass Booth, Poor Bitos, and in New York in the
production of Wise Child.
He is survived by his fourth wife, Linda Woollan, and five daughters,
two from his first marriage, two from his second, and one from his
third. Three of them are actresses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Axe set to fall on 15,000 tax jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041977</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 15,000 tax jobs, at least 1000 of them in Scotland, are to be
cut over the next seven years.
They are the Inland Revenue's share of Government-demanded
efficiencies, expected to result in more than 50,000 job losses across
the Civil Service.
Already 10,000 revenue jobs have been shed over the past three years ,
some 500 of them in Scotland, where the revenue currently employees
around 4800. A further 500 Scottish jobs are expected to go in the next
wave of losses.
In a special announcement to the department's 54,000 staff, Inland
Revenue chairman Sir Anthony Battishill said yesterday that 6000 posts
would be cut over the next three years.
He said the aim, however, was to reduce the workforce to between
42,000 to 44,000 by the year 2002 and around 3000 other jobs could also
be axed from the revenue's valuation departments. Sir Anthony said: ''We
shall see a significantly smaller but increasingly efficient and
professional department.''
The union warned the measures would lead to a reduction in the amount
of taxes collected, although it was heartened by a Government decision
to restrict planned self-assessment to the self employed and higher-rate
tax payers and would not now be extended to the bulk of those on Pay As
You Earn.
This decision to retain the bulk of PAYE in-house will mean the
purchase of new computer software and safeguard many of the jobs at PAYE
offices including the new #24m Centre One in East Kilbride, which was
occupied only last month, and the London Provincial collection offices
in Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Livingston.
Tax collectors, white collar staff, and middle managers are to bear
the brunt of the job losses, which will lead to huge savings for the
Government. Only 90 top rank jobs are believed to be involved.
Workers were told the job losses would mainly be achieved through
natural wastage and voluntary redundancy, although management refuses to
rule out compulsory lay-offs. There have been about 80 compulsory
redundancies to date.
The Inland Revenue Staff Federation, which represents tax workers,
said it was ''angry'' at the news especially as some #2000m of tax went
uncollected last year and that if redundant staff were diverted to
collection duties they could soon justify their existence by bringing in
additional revenue for the Treasury. Members might be balloted on
industrial action.
The federation general secretary, Mr Clive Brooke, met the Chancellor
on Wednesday to try to win a pledge of no compulsory redundancies, but
Mr Kenneth Clarke refused to give that guarantee.
Deputy general secretary Jim McAuslan said he believed the number of
jobs to go would top 15,000 over the next seven years through a
combination of efficiency improvements, market testing, and ''stripping
out'' an entire level of middle management.
Mr McAuslan said union members would now have to decide whether to
accept an agreement worked out between the IRSF and the Inland Revenue
to manage the cutbacks, or to take industrial action. An initial ballot
on the redundancies will be held later this month and could be followed
by a ballot for industrial action.
The Inland Revenue cuts come under the Fundamental Expenditure Review
being demanded of every Civil Service department. Under this process,
Civil Service manpower has fallen from 530,000 last year to about
500,000 and is expected to fall to about 475,000 over the next few
years.
Civil Service unions fear that without a Labour election victory their
numbers could plummet to as low as 50,000, with that core Civil Service
buying-in most of its services.
One Labour MP has already expressed concern about the possibility of
job losses in his constituency.
In a letter to Treasury Chief Secretary Jonathan Aitken, the
Cumbernauld and Kilsyth MP, Mr Norman Hogg, said: ''I am informed that
there have been a number of innovations involving new technology and a
self-assessment scheme which could have a serious impact on employment
levels at Cumbernauld.
''It seems to me that at the very least, the Government should make
clear that there shall not be any compulsory redundancies as a result of
this announcement and that any efficiencies made should be redirected
into achieving compliance with the tax laws and even more effective tax
collection.''
Shadow Employment Secretary Harriet Harman said the huge job losses
would make worse the epidemic of insecurity at work which had swept
through the public sector as well as the private sector.
Labour claims the tax compliance efforts of the inspectors facing
redundancy are worth the equivalent of #9000m a year in revenue to the
Treasury. Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said: ''We'll be
working along with the Inland Revenue staff unions to impress upon
Government the folly of their actions in this case.''
* A Mori poll of IRSF members conducted last weekend showed that just
13% would now vote Conservative as opposed to 31% who cast their votes
for the Tories in the last election. Seventy-two per cent said they
would vote Labour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
