<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When a tiny blemish looms on the psyche</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041979</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT might be a tiny facial blemish, barely visible to anyone else, but
for some people it can be a matter of life and death.
They are sufferers from Body Dysmorphic Disorder, a morbid obsession
with a trivial or even imaginary physical defect. According to
psychiatrist Anne Boocock, 16 out of a group of 43 patients she is
treating had attempted suicide.
Others become reclusive, their chances of employment, social life, or
romance blighted.
''The prevalence is not known but it is likely to be much more
widespread than realised,'' Dr Boocock told the Royal College of
Psychiatrists' winter meeting in Glasgow yesterday.
First identified in the last century, BDD is probably more common now
as a result of the perfectionist images portrayed, and often enhanced
with airbrushes or digital techniques, in the media.
''Sexual stereotyping also contributes to some women's obsession that
their breasts -- or, in the case of men, their genitals -- are too
small,'' she added.
Dr Boocock, who works in the Royal Free Hospital in London, said 70%
of the patients were entirely normal; where there was a defect at all,
it was well within the bounds of normality.
Dr Boocock and her colleagues are now conducting a trial of cognitive
therapy on some of their patients, many of whom had been driven to seek
the help of plastic and ENT surgeons or dermatologists. However, many
BDD sufferers were too embarrassed to seek the help of their GP, let
alone a psychiatrist.
What kind of person develops such an obsession? The average age of Dr
Boocock's patients was 33, but their problem had started at about 17;
most were female (77%) and single or separated (75%); and 42% were
unemployed.
Dr Boocock's group has now developed links with Changing Faces, an
organisation which helps people with genuine disfigurements, to find out
how they learn to cope with them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Families' anger over pay-out to police in stadium disaster</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041980</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLLEAGUES of 14 South Yorkshire police officers who are to receive
compensation because of the effects of the Hillsborough stadium disaster
were said yesterday to be ''sickened'' at the pay-outs.
And relatives of the 96 soccer fans who died in the 1989 tragedy --
many of whom have still not received any compensation -- expressed
disgustat the cash awards for the trauma the officers had suffered.
Lawyers for the Municipal Mutual Insurance Company have conceded
liability in 14 out of a total of 34 cases being brought by the Police
Federation, and out-of-court settlements are to be negotiated.
But both sides yesterday dismissed as ''completely speculative''
claims that compensation would range from #10,000 to #250,000, saying
that talks on the size of payments had not yet begun.
The insurance company, which covers all three defendants in the case
-- South Yorkshire Police, Sheffield Wednesday Football Club and its
engineers Eastwood and Partners -- has conceded liability in the cases
of 14 officers who went into the pens of the Lepping Lane terrace in the
aftermath of the crush, hauling out the dead and injured.
Another 23 cases, on behalf of officers who did not go into the pens,
are to be contested at the High Court in Sheffield on March 27.
Confirming the settlement yesterday, Gillian Radcliffe, head of press
and public relations for South Yorkshire Police, said: ''It is
understandable that relatives and other people on Merseyside will be
shocked by this development.
''Many members of the South Yorkshire Police service are equally
shocked. I've had quite a lot of calls from officers who were part of
the disaster and haven't felt it necessary to make claims, and the words
they have used are that they are sickened.
''There were hundreds of officers involved in the rescue and those
pursuing these actions are a tiny minority. A lot of them have retired
as a result of the stress and their main aim is to get compensation for
the loss of earnings from losing their jobs.''
Mrs Anne Williams, whose 15-year-old son Kevin died in the disaster,
said she was ''disgusted'' at the development.
''Lord Justice Taylor blamed the police because they lost control --
my son died because they lost control,'' she said.
''Now they are getting compensation for post-traumatic stress
disorder. What about the poor families? We've lost our children and they
don't seem to care about us.''
Mr Trevor Hicks, chairman of the Hillsborough Family Support Group
which represents over half the families, said the decision represented a
''double standard''. He lost his two teenage daughters in the tragedy,
and has received no compensation and is heavily out of pocket on legal
expenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sheriff sees prison as pale alternative to fine</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041981</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SHERIFF yesterday fined a man for damaging a police van, after
describing prison as ''a holiday with no sun tan''.
Robert Moles, 32, of Gracie Crescent, Fallin, Stirlingshire, pled
guilty at Stirling Sheriff Court to kicking a grille in the van after
being arrested for shouting in the town's Baker Street on April 5th.
Before fining him #100 plus #18.50 to cover the repairs, Sheriff James
Scott told Moles: ''This is not a serious breach of the peace, but
you're still in danger of being sent for a holiday with no sun tan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dealer flooded Scotland with drug</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041982</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A DRUGS wholesaler licensed by the Home Office was in jail last night
after a jury convicted him of supplying the Scottish black market with
#5m worth of the drug Temazepam.
Sundeep Amin, 36, a recently-discharged bankrupt, flooded Scotland
with 3.8 million capsules of the drug which he had bought legitimately
for #94,000 over an eight-month period in 1993.
The court was told that the prescription-only Class C drug was
legitimately prescribed to relieve anxiety, to aid sleep and in the
treatment of epilepsy.
But drug abusers risked their health by taking massive doses in
capsules or injection form.
Temazepam is widely abused in Scotland and is fast becoming a major
problem in the rest of Britain.
Amin, of Welbeck Close, New Malden, Surrey, denied conspiracy to
supply the drug but a jury at Kingston Crown Court found him guilty.
Adjourning sentence until March 17, Judge John Bishop refused to renew
bail and remanded him in custody.
Mr Andrew Colman, prosecuting, said that after Amin bought the
Temazepam from three legitimate sources the capsules were taken to
Scotland where they were sold on the streets for between #1 and #3 each.
Mr Colman, who described Amin as a wholesale chemist, said the
defendant produced fake documents to show that he had sold the drugs to
a small chemist in West Kensington, London. But the chemist had never
heard of Amin or his company.
Amin did not give evidence but his barrister, Mr Barry Gilbert, told
the jury: ''There is not an iota of proof that the drugs went to
Scotland.''
He suggested the drugs were sold for use abroad and that Amin tried to
conceal this fact because he felt he might be acting illegally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Margarine 'not guilty'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041983</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS now doubt claims that transfatty acids found in margarine
are linked to heart disease. Two studies published in The Lancet found
heart disease victims did not have higher levels of these acids in their
tissue, compared with healthy individuals. Fears about the
factory-produced fats made with vegetable and fish oils were raised two
years ago after research involving American women showed a strong
association with coronary problems. New research carried out in eight
European countries and Israel showed no difference between levels of
transfatty acid in 671 men who had suffered a heart attack and 717
healthy men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rattle plans divorce</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041984</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIR Simon Rattle, generally regarded as Britain's brightest star of
classical music, has separated from his wife and is planning a divorce,
it was announced last night. The man who led the City of Birmingham
Symphony Orchestra to international renown while projecting a new young
image of a musical maestro made the announcement less than seven months
after being knighted. He and Lady Rattle, American soprano Elise Ross,
were married in 1980, and she later said she had put her singing career
''on hold''. They have two sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Extra runways vetoed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041985</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of villagers had threats to their homes lifted yesterday
when the Government decided against building extra runways at Heathrow
and Gatwick airports. More than 3000 homes would have been demolished if
a third runway had been built at Heathrow, while the village of
Charlwood was under threat if Gatwick got a second runway. Instead,
Transport Secretary Brian Mawhinney decided to call for a further two to
three year study to see if more use could be made of existing runways at
the two airports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seafront hotel on way</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041986</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN District Council yesterday signed a deal to lease land to an
international hotel group to build a #6m seafront hotel. The three-star
Patio Hotel will have 92 bedrooms, two restaurants, bars, a conference
centre, and a leisure club. It will create 60 jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two-year ban for 2ft drive</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041987</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 16-YEAR-OLD was put on probation for 18 months and banned from
driving for two years at Inverness Sheriff Court yesterday when he
admitted driving offences. Alexander Cooper, of Rossmuir, Croy, near
Inverness, was over the alcohol limit on Hogmanay when he drove his
father's car two feet from the driveway and hit a fence post. He
admitted taking and driving away the car, careless driving while over
the limit, and having no insurance or licence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Assault accused freed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041988</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAN was yesterday cleared at the High Court in Inverness of
assaulting a 16-year-old girl with intent to rape in Macduff last
October. Ian Elkins, 26, a labourer, of Clergy Street, Macduff, said he
had followed the girl and grabbed her but only to give her a warning
because he thought she was the friend of a family causing him trouble.
Elkins was found guilty of simple assault by seizing the girl, pushing
and pulling her, and punching her on the head. Advocate-depute Iain
Bonomy did not move for sentence and Lord MacLean set Elkins free after
hearing he had been in custody since October 22.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Girl dies on birthday</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041989</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A REPORT has been sent to the procurator-fiscal in connection with the
death from suspected solvent abuse of a West Lothian girl celebrating
her fifteenth birthday. Carrie Ann McAloon, of Chapelton Drive, Polbeth,
was found unconscious in her bedroom on Wednesday night. Lothian and
Borders Police said there were no suspicious circumstances surrounding
the incident. It is understood that the schoolgirl, a Polbeth Gala Queen
three years ago, had been out to a local youth club with friends. She
died an hour after being admitted to St John's Hospital in Livingston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Social chance for the young</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041990</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BAR for under-age drinkers is planned by Falkirk District Council.
It wants to rent the lounge of the town's Magpie hostelry two nights a
week for a three-month trial, and serve soft drinks. Alcohol
advertisements would be removed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murder hunt</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041991</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETECTIVES in Glasgow launched a murder inquiry last night after a
man's body was found in a house in Castlemilk. Police refused to give
any details of how the man, who was aged 65, had been killed. His body
was found in a house in Glenacre Terrace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Draconian regulations' force out councillor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041992</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Aberdeen District councillor last night claimed he had been forced
out of local government by draconian regulations.
Councillor Malcolm Savidge, convener of the finance and general
purposes committee, said he had reluctantly decided to withdraw from
seeking election to the new unitary authority in April.
He is a school teacher and under Government regulations council
employees cannot stand for election for the authority which employs
them.
He said he believed that the Government regulations, which also
covered school janitors, cleaners, carers, and home helps, deprived the
community of the opportunity of electing people with a wide range of
experience.
He said: ''Local government employees are being barred from standing
for office, while there is a bizarre contrast to enterprise boards with
Tory friends and backers being given places in the quangos.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bonsai collection stolen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041993</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ELEVEN bonsai trees of various sizes have been stolen from an isolated
house on the outskirts of Linlithgow. Police said the expensive potted
plants were popular with gardening enthusiasts and could be offered for
sale locally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Science on the move</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041994</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCIENCE Olympiad, part of the touring schools programme connected
with the Edinburgh International Science Festival, is to be held in
Glasgow for the first time this year. It will take place at Strathclyde
University's Jordanhill campus on March 14-16. Its attractions will
include the MadLab, a crystals workshop, and a forensics trail. The
science festival itself, whose programme is being published by The
Herald, runs from March 31 to April 17.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Legionella source untraced</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041995</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN inquiry has failed to find the source of Legionella which killed a
64-year-old man last month. Tests of water samples taken from Mr Gordon
Henderson's home in Dean Road, Bo'ness, West Lothian, have proved
negative. Scientists from Forth Valley Health Board said yesterday they
could find no evidence of the disease's origin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police hurt in animal rights protest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041996</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS MANY as three police officers were hurt during a violent
demonstration by about 200 animal welfare activists last night. A chief
inspector was understood to be in hospital after being hit by a brick
during the demonstration outside Millbay Docks, Plymouth; a constable
was believed to have a broken arm; and another constable an injured
head. They were injured as activists tried to prevent a convoy of
lorries of veal calves and sheep entering the docks to board a privately
chartered cross Channel ferry. The incident came a day after animal
rights protester Jill Phipps was killed when she fell under the wheels
of a truck during a similar protest outside Coventry airport. Masked
demonstrators also attacked the home in the village of Frankton, near
Rugby, Warwickshire, of the aviation company chiefs responsible for
airlifting live calves to France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Priest from training college is charged</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041997</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A ROMAN Catholic priest has been charged in connection with offences
alleged to have taken place at Blairs College, a former training centre
on the outskirts of Aberdeen, in the late 1970s. Grampian Police last
night confirmed that Father Desmond Lynagh, currently residing at a
centre in England, had been charged with two alleged offences of
shamelessly indecent conduct and that a report would be submitted to the
procurator-fiscal.
Father Lynagh agreed to attend an Edinburgh police station last week
to be interviewed by Grampian Police detectives after which he was
charged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#7m plan for fashion centre on school site</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041998</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A #7m development in the heart of Aberdeen which is attracting the
attention of international fashion shops like Armani and Versace could
be open by the middle of next year.
Property developers Jarlaw has unveiled plans for The Academy
development, based in a former school in Aberdeen's Belmont Street area.
If planning permission is granted in the spring, work will start on
the first phase of the development almost immediately and may be
completed within a year.
''The proposal will assist to reinforce Aberdeen as the major shopping
centre for the North-east,'' said Mr Charlie Ferrari, managing director
of Jarlaw.
The Academy is intended to offer Aberdeen shopping of the quality of
Princes Square and the Italian Centre in Glasgow.
As well as shops the development, which includes a courtyard and a
piazza, will have quality licensed bars and restaurants as well as
living accommodation.
Meanwhile, a plan to build a #3.5m supermarket on Skye creating about
50 jobs has been lodged with Highland Regional Council.
The Scottish Co-op is seeking outline planning approval for a 20,000sq
ft supermarket at Druim-na-Pairc, Dunvegan Road, Portree, about 400
yards from its existing premises.
The new store will be virtually double the size of the existing Co-op
store and have parking for 200 vehicles.
The store could open within a year of planning consent being approved
and the firm's current 55 employees would be transferred to the new
store.
The proposal is part of the Scottish Co-op's multi-million pound
development programme which includes a #4.5m Co-op in Stornoway and a
#2m store in Arran.
The proposals are being opposed by local shopkeepers, who believe the
development would kill the village community. Mr Douglas MacKenzie, a
baker in Portree, said, at time when the Government was restricting out
of town developments, it would be suprising if planners allowed it to go
ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Court finds minister not guilty of assault on 12-year-old pupil</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980041999</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MINISTER who teaches religious education was yesterday cleared at
Elgin Sheriff Court of assaulting a pupil in his class.
The Rev James Scott accused the 12-year-old girl of telling lies in
court in an attempt to convict him. He also said he suspected the girl
had bruised her own arm, then blamed the mark on him.
Outside the court, Mr Scott, who teaches in Morayshire, said: ''Some
of us have crosses to bear. This has been my particular cross.''
Mr Scott, a full-time teacher, said he had restrained the girl to stop
her hitting another pupil. He insisted he had used minimum force and
denied striking her.
Mr Scott, 46, of Morriston Road, Elgin, was acquitted at the end of a
two-day trial.
The girl told an earlier sitting Mr Scott had struck her without
warning while they were watching a video during a music lesson last
September.
She claimed she had been speaking to a classmate but had ended the
conversation before she was struck.
She said she had been aware of the teacher behind her and then felt a
pain in her arm. The girl also said that later, when she had gone to
basketball practice, she noticed a large red bruise on her upper arm.
In his evidence yesterday, Mr Scott, who has been suspended since the
allegations surfaced last September, told the court he had been
principal teacher of education since 1980.
Asked by defence agent Ian Cruickshank if he had ever struck a pupil
during his time as a teacher, he replied: ''No.''
Mr Scott told the court that on the day in question the girl was being
aggressive towards a boy. Asked by Mr Cruickshank what he had done to
intervene, he replied: ''I put my left arm on her upper arm.''
Mr Cruickshank asked: ''Would you regard it as a blow?'' He replied:
''Certainly not. No-one in that classroom could have regarded it as a
blow.''
Sheriff Donald Booker Millburn told Mr Scott: ''I do not consider that
the crown has proved the case beyond reasonable doubt. You are found not
guilty and you are free to go.''
A spokesman for Grampian Regional Council said Mr Scott would remain
suspended from his post, adding: ''A disciplinary investigation, which
was taking place, was suspended when Mr Scott was charged by the police
in connection with the alleged incident.
''That investigation has still to be concluded and Mr Scott will
remain suspended from duty meantime.''
At the resumption of the trial, procurator-fiscal James McKay drew the
sheriff's attention to an article in The Herald published on January 13
which carried a photograph of the accused while the trial was
continuing.
Sheriff Booker-Millburn agreed that identification of the accused had
not been an issue, but said the editor of The Herald should be asked to
come and explain his position on what was a possible contempt of court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deadline to save tourist steam trains</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN AND FRANCES HORSBURGH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042000</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RAILTRACK Scotland, ScotRail, and the Scottish tourist industry have
less than two weeks to save one of Scotland's most celebrated summer
tourist attractions -- the steam trains between Fort William and Mallaig
-- the service's incoming owner warned last night.
Mr Peter Waterman, owner of Waterman Railways, criticised ScotRail and
Railtrack Scotland for failing to include him in discussions on the
future of the service. He called for a concerted effort to keep the
loss-making trains running under privatisation. His company is due to
take over British Rail's Special Trains Unit, which runs the steam
trains on the West Highland Line, on April 1.
Mr Waterman denied he intended to drop the service. ''There is
skullduggery going on here. We are accused of wanting to abandon the
service but no such decision has been made. And no-one from Scotland has
met with us,'' he said.
He said he was not prepared to subsidise the service, which costs
#4600 a day to run but only has a daily income of #2800. ''There's no
way we could subsidise steam in Scotland. We would put ourselves out of
business.''
Mr Waterman, a succesful record producer whose great grandfather was a
McDonald and a train driver, called for a partnership with tourist
boards, local authorities, and ScotRail. He said: ''All it takes is for
all parties to have the will to run steam in Scotland. If we all get
together, we are quite convinced there would be a way of doing this.''
Railtrack Scotland has rejected Mr Waterman's claims that the track
access charges to run the trains would be exorbitant. Figures show they
would be less than 10% -- #565 -- of the daily running cost.
Meanwhile, Lochaber councillor Dr Michael Foxley told yesterday's
meeting of Highland Regional Council's roads and transport committee
that the time for talking about rail privatisation was past and direct
action must be taken if the service was to be maintained.
He claimed the figures used to justify the withdrawal of the summer
steam trains on the Mallaig line were totally false.
''These trains have been 75% full every year for just about every day
they are run. This is all part of the fragmentation process going on to
make each unit look unprofitable and then to close it down. We have to
start a massive campaign now. Otherwise, we'll be sitting here listening
to reports for ever.''
Edinburgh District Council leaders yesterday agreed to write to all
the city's MPs and to Transport Secretary Dr Brian Mawhinney to protest
about the threatened loss of some sleeper and Motorail services to
Scotland as a result of privatisation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Regulator may save Motorail services</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042001</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Rail Regulator might step in to save the Scottish Motorail and
sleeper services threatened with closure under privatisation, because
their future was decided without public consultation, the Liberal
Democrats claimed last night.
Mr John Swift, QC, told a delegation, led by Mr Charles Kennedy, MP
for Ross, Cromarty, and Skye, that it was still not too late to save the
services, which depend on a #3m annual subsidy.
Last December Mr Roger Salmon, the railway Franchising Director,
announced that Motorail and the Fort William sleeper would not be
included in the list of services to be provided under privatisation.
According to Mr Kennedy, Mr Swift told the MPs that he believed Mr
Salmon's announcement might have amounted to a procedural irregularity,
because it failed to allow for the public consultation called for under
the privatisation legislation.
The Rail Users' Consultative Committee has complained that it was not
given a chance to examine the issue before the decision was announced,
and has called for the Government to intervene.
Critics of privatisation have pointed out that while there was no
consultation on Motorail and the sleepers in Scotland, Mr Salmon has
announced a wide-ranging consultation exercise on the requirements for
four English franchises announced earlier this week.
Mr Kennedy said he would seek meetings with Mr Salmon and Railtrack to
discuss the future of the services. ''There is a prima facie case to say
that Mr Salmon has breached his own guidelines in pre-empting the
consultation process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man jailed for fire attack on his wife</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JEALOUS husband who set fire to his wife because she planned to
leave him was jailed for 10 years yesterday.
Leslie Beattie, 35, was found guilty of two charges of committing
arson with intent to endanger life but was cleared of a charge of
attempted murder at Durham Crown Court.
His wife, Michelle Beattie, has to wear a surgical mask 23 hours a day
to cover her facial injuries and will require years of plastic surgery
following the fire at her home in Taunton Place, Cramlington,
Northumberland, in December 1993.
Mrs Beattie was set ablaze when a policeman, Mr George Hall,
confronted her husband in a petrol-soaked bedroom.
The court heard how Beattie, before starting the fire with the flick
of a lighter, was upset that his wife planned to leave him and told her:
''If I can't have you, no one else can.''
Mr Justice Laws told Beattie he had committed ''terrible crimes'',
although he accepted his actions had not been long premeditated, but
added: ''You must have known it was inevitable that very great injury
would be caused.''
The Judge said that imprisonment was the only sentence which could be
justified, but accepted that Beattie had been of good character
previously and that at the time of the incident he was in an emotional
state because of his marriage problems.
The Judge earlier said Beattie had not shown much remorse while giving
evidence, but Mr Stephen Williamson, QC, defending, explained Beattie
had been taking anti-depressant tablets during the trial.
Mr Williamson told the court that Beattie himself had been left
scarred by the fire -- when shown photographs of the full extent of his
wife's injuries Beattie, he claimed, had been ''devastated'' by what he
saw.
During the four-day trial, the jury heard that Mrs Beattie, who has a
young daughter, had intercourse with an office colleague while her
husband was on holiday alone in Tenerife just before Christmas 1993.
When Beattie gave evidence he said he had not meant to start the fire.
He claimed he had been trying to bring about a siege situation to draw
attention to the hurt he was feeling. He said the fire had been started
in his struggle with police called to the house.
Mrs Beattie, 31, told the court: ''I felt myself ignite -- my whole
body just ablaze, just on fire. I knew I was on fire -- I could feel
myself burning.''
She managed to stagger from the room and rolled on a duvet to smother
the flames. However she was so badly injured she spent over three months
in hospital, five weeks of that on a life-support machine and was close
to death several times.
PC Hall told the court he had tried to pin Beattie's arms to his sides
and was trying to force him out of the room when the fire had suddenly
erupted.
Mr Hall was also badly burnt and was off work for 10 weeks recovering
from injuries to his face, hands and back.
The Judge commended PC Hall and two other officers called to the
incident, constables Gary Coates and Frank Clarke, for their actions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>M77 protesters claim victory in first skirmish with contractor</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROTESTERS against the M77 extension through the south side of Glasgow
claimed victory last night in the first day of serious skirmishing with
Wimpey, the construction company responsible for building the #53.6m
road.
Around 40 activists, working under the banner of environmental direct
action group Earth First!, stopped the company's sub-contractors
clearing an area of woodland, known locally as ''Pollok Castle'', near
the B769 Stewarton Road at the Newton Mearns end of the proposed
six-mile extension. The motorway will link the A77 at Malletsheugh with
the M77 at the Haggs Castle roundabout.
The protesters chained themselves to tree fellers' equipment,
vehicles, and to the tree fellers themselves, in order to halt the work,
which began two days ago.
They also dumped logs and branches from some of the 150 trees cut down
so far in a nearby Wimpey showhouse development.
Last night a Wimpey spokesman said two other crews of foresters had
been able to work at other sites unmolested by the protesters, but
admitted that playing ''cat and mouse'' with them was only a short-term
solution to an intractable problem.
''We will now be reconsidering the way we go about this contract,
particularly in terms of our approach to dealing with the protesters,''
he said.
Wimpey has engaged the security firm Securiguard to protect the
project, and yesterday around a dozen guards were quickly on the scene.
Protesters claimed yesterday they had been alerted by a source within
Wimpey that the work had started, six miles from the Pollok Estate
encampment they have set up.
They rushed to the site early yesterday morning to set up a second
camp, spiking trees with six inch nails to delay further clearing work.
When staff from Barrhead contractor John Meikle arrived at 8am, they
found themselves confronted by the protestors, who claimed they had
caught Wimpey in the act of trying to outflank them.
Protester Jake Hunter said yesterday: ''The company has gone to great
length and expense to try and appear as though they're consulting
people, and have tried to develop a relationship with us.
''All that trust's gone out the window with these sneaky and underhand
tactics. Now we'll be really gunning for them, and will man both camps
continuously.''
Police were not involved in yesterday's events but said they were
continuing to monitor the situation.
Meanwhile, the tree fellers' employer, Mr John Meikle, spoke last
night of his anger at the protesters' action.
''My men only want to do a job. People have chained themselves to my
men, stolen the keys from our van and let our tyres down. Why should
these people be allowed to interfere with our business?''
The protesters were also costing more than 20 foresters work, Mr
Meikle claimed: ''I have men standing by who want to work, who need the
money and they're not being allowed to earn a wage.''
As the main contractors, Wimpey is believed to be footing the bill for
paying any costs incurred by sub-contractors as a result of the
protesters' action.
The protest will also continue via other channels, Mr Ian Bogle of the
pressure group Glasgow for People said last night.
One of these will be contacting residents of Newton Mearns. However,
as one man who stopped to talk to protestors proved, this may not be
successful.
Mr Ronald Harris, who lives in Greenfern Estate, said: ''I think the
M77's a wonderful idea, and whilst I appreciate their arguments, there
are hundreds of us who need it to happen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Timetable for 'locals' torn up by expresses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042004</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
By IAIN WILSON
Chief Reporter
THE director of ScotRail has accused Railtrack of treating his
customers on the North Berwick to Edinburgh route as second-class
citizens.
Railtrack, responsible for providing train operators with access to
the line, is giving priority to InterCity services on the east coast
main line, which means that ScotRail's passengers are subjected to
lengthy delays regardless of timetables.
Director Chris Green, in a letter to Mr John Home Robertson, Labour MP
for East Lothian, spoke of his exasperation at passengers being ''badly
inconvenienced''.
He had ''remonstrated very firmly with Railtrack'' and would be happy
to meet the MP to discuss an issue which had led to a ''very sharp
deterioration'' in performance.
In a separate letter to a commuter, Mr Green said: ''I share your
infuriation at the totally unacceptable performance of the North Berwick
route.''
Mr Green said Railtrack's huge backlog of track engineering between
Edinburgh and Drem was the prime reason for ScotRail's unreliable
services.
''I have some sympathy with Railtrack's predicament,'' he wrote, ''but
not with their decision to give total priority to the InterCity trains
on the route under any circumstances.
''Railtrack believe the track position will be largely resolved by the
end of March, and I am determined that you cease to be treated as
second-class citizens from that date.''
His central thrust is that ScotRail has no direct control of
infrastructure problems because Railtrack took over that responsibility
in the run-up to privatisation.
The language in both letters is extraordinarily strong, given the
gagging order recently imposed by the British Railways Board in the wake
of his bleak assessment of ScotRail's fate on privatisation in an
article in The Herald.
Mr Home Robertson claimed Railtrack was giving priority to InterCity
because the Tories wanted to clear the way for the east coast line's
flagship privatisation.
He had received numerous complaints from constituents who used
ScotRail trains on the line. He said they could be forced to wait 30
minutes or more until InterCity services were clear.
He said: ''I am delighted at Mr Green's robust defence of the North
Berwick route, and will be pleased to discuss matters with him.
''The Government wants the best possible performances from InterCity.
But a point of principle is involved, with Railtrack dictating services.
Signalling staff should not be told to let InterCity through at all
costs. Services should be taken on their merits.''
The party's industry spokesman, Mr Brian Wilson, said: ''This kind of
conflict has not previously arisen because one organisation provided an
integrated public service. Now we are left with a collection of rival,
feuding factions.''
A Railtrack spokesman denied that privatisation or political concerns
were being taken into account.
He said BR regulations, even before Railtrack was created, stated that
fast trains always had to take precedence on lines, and added: ''The
faster the train, the more reason for it to go first rather than behind
a slow train.'' Railtrack proposes talks with ScotRail in a bid to
resolve complaints.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Plea to Hurd about plight of Kashmiris</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042005</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Foreign Secretary is to be pressed by Mr Yaqub Ali, a millionaire
businessman and ardent Conservative supporter, when he arrives in
Glasgow tonight about the Government's lack of support for the people of
Kashmir.
Mr Ali, owner of Castle Cash and Carry in Glasgow and chairman of the
Tory support group Focus on Scotland, says that he is disappointed at
the lack of support the British Government has given to the people of
Kashmir who are fighting for their independence from India.
It has been claimed that 11,000 people have died in the past year in
fighting with Indian forces, with many thousands unfairly detained, and
more than 5000 women raped.
Mr Douglas Hurd is having a private meeting with Conservative fund
raisers in a city hotel tonight, and Mr Ali says he will use the
occasion to raise the plight of the Kashmiris with him.
''I am going to put him in a corner as much as I can,'' Mr Ali said
yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Edinburgh warns of #40m building cuts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042006</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT action over council borrowing has blown a #40m hole in
Edinburgh's ecomomic future, the capital's Labour leaders warned
yesterday.
They claimed that with a single stroke Scottish Secretary Ian Lang had
signed away a great deal of Edinburgh's chances of economic growth.
The council has made substantial use of a loophole, which is now to be
closed, involving the use of notional capital receipts from the lease of
land to augment its capital building programme.
Labour leader Councillor Lesley Hinds said the full extent of the
damage this would do to the city's investment plans had only now been
calculated.
The four-year capital programme to invest in buildings and facilities
which the council had prepared for the years until 1999 would have to be
reduced by 70% or #40m from the projected figure of #57m.
The council is to urge Mr Lang to postpone the implementation date for
the changes from April to July, a move which it claims would save much
of next year's programme by allowing them completion of current
transactions.
In addition, Edinburgh is to ask for a major increase in its formal
capital borrowing consent for 1995-96.
