<DOCNO>GH950203-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>#96,000 top salary for new council chiefs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042010</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOCAL government leaders have agreed salaries of between #58,000 and
#96,000 for the chief executives of the new single tier councils being
established in Scotland.
The agreement, between Cosla and the trade unions, allows for a range
of salaries from the largest for Glasgow to the smallest for
Clackmannan.
The pay of chief executives in the three islands councils, which are
not being reorganised, will remain at #58,000.
The salary levels are based largely on the population and projected
budgets of the 32 unitary authorities.
Details of the agreement will be passed to the Local Government Staff
Commission and advertisements for the posts are expected to appear later
this month.
Elections to the 29 new mainland councils take place on April 6 and
the new structure will become fully operational a year later.
Under the new structure, no official will earn as much as Strathclyde
region's present chief executive who has a salary of #111,000.
The chief executive of the new Edinburgh City Council will earn
#93,000, about the same as the present Lothian regional chief executive.
Mr Mark Irvine, head of Local Government in Scotland for the public
services union Unison, said yesterday that the agreement reached with
the Scottish employers was the first step in the process of making
senior appointments in the new unitary councils.
He explained that the agreement would be reviewed next year, to ensure
that future salaries reflected accurately the duties carried out by
chief executives and other chief officers, once reorganisation had taken
place.
Mr Irvine warned that there was a great deal more to be done to
protect the interests of Scotland's 300,000 council staff.
But, he said the agreement represented a good start and set the
standard for future discussions with the employers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Police claim #163,000 was pocketed over 20 years from money that should have been burned Bank manager accused of taking cash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042011</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BANK manager pocketed used bank notes instead of burning them, it
was claimed at the High Court in Glasgow yesterday.
Mr Hector MacGillivray, 54, is alleged to have helped himself three
times a week from bags of notes waiting to be incinerated.
A police officer claimed that Mr MacGillivray had confessed during a
tape-recorded interview that he had been stealing the money for 20
years.
He ''shocked'' detectives with his sudden confession as they
investigated another theft at the Clydesdale Bank in Glasgow, it was
claimed.
Mr MacGillivray, of Thomson Drive, Bearsden, was said to have admitted
to police to taking around #600 a week from the bank's ''burning boxes''
in Glasgow.
Detective Sergeant Robert Mullarkey, told the court Mr MacGillivray
had admitted in the taped interview taking about #18,000 a year.
Mr MacGillivray denies embezzling an estimated #163,200 between
January 1, l972 and November 30, l992, at the bank's premises in
Glasogow.
Sergeant Mullarkey told Advocate-depute Mrs Valerie Stacey that
#40,000 in cash and #3000 in foreign currency was stolen from the bank.
More than 60 bank staff were interviewed by detectives and finally Mr
MacGillivray was interviewed.
He told police he knew nothing of the missing money.
Sergeant Mullarkey said he asked him if he knew of any other thefts
taking place in the bank and he replied: ''Yes, I have.''
Sergeant Mullarkey told Lord Prosser and the jury: ''I got an initial
shock. He repeated, 'I have been taking money.' ''
Mrs Stacey said another person had since been charged in connection
with the missing #40,000.
During a tape-recorded interview played to the jury it is alleged that
Mr MacGillivray told how he had been in charge of the bank's cash
burning centre in the city and had started by taking small amounts --
#10, #20, and #30, but later took about #600 a week.
It is alleged he said: ''I removed the money from the burning boxes
three times a week. It was of all denominations from #l to #100 notes.''
During the interview it is claimed Mr MacGillivray explained to
Sergeant Mullarkey how the burning boxes were filled with bags of old
notes and put in his safe.
Later they were taken out and incinerated. It is alleged that before
that happened Mr MacGillivray had helped himself from the bags.
On the tape Sergeant Mullarkey is heard asking: ''No-one checks the
checker?'' Reply: ''Correct.''
Sergeant Mullarkey: ''It appeared a fullproof scheme because there was
no documentation?''''Yes.''
Mr MacGillivray is claimed to have said there had been nothing
dramatic happening in his life to make him steal the money. He had
bought ''nothing of a substantial nature'' with the money, although he
deposited some of it in bank and building society accounts, he is
alleged to have said.
Mr MacGillivray worked for the bank as a teller in Rothesay,
Skelmorlie and Greenock before being promoted to head office in Glasgow.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thousands of young people overtaxed by computer error</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042012</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
By IAIN WILSON
Chief Reporter
A COMPUTER error has led to thousands of young people being overtaxed
for months after starting work for the first time, with the global sum
reputedly running into millions of pounds.
Until today, many of the victims will not even be aware they are due
refunds for needlessly paying tax.
The fault was uncovered only through an odd set of circumstances -- a
financial expert trawled his daughter's tax demands after she found a
job and had stopped claiming benefit.
Several more ''teething problems'' exist within the Employment
Services Agency computer, the largest non-military system in Europe and
subjected to programming updates for the last two years.
An ESA spokesman last night denied the other problems may have serious
implications for an even wider range of taxpayers.
The original blunder has been exposed by Mr Thomas Docherty, a
taxation lecturer at Glasgow Caledonian University.
He had questioned why his daughter Caroline should pay tax immediately
after finding work. The Inland Revenue has now ordered the ESA to alter
its computer programme ''as a matter of priority''.
Mr Docherty said yesterday: ''No-one else seemed to have picked up the
error, affecting a vulnerable section of the community with little or no
access to advice or help. You would probably have to be an accountant
with a son or daughter on income support to know something was wrong.''
His daughter, on graduating from Glasgow University last June, claimed
benefit until taking up a librarian's post in October -- accumulating
tax allowances on the way.
This meant that no deductions should have been made on earnings for at
least a few months. Her complaint led to more than #100 being refunded.
But many other former students in a similar position are still losing
money which is rightfully theirs.
An Inland Revenue investigation blames the ESA for wrongly programming
a computer to issue emergency code numbers to people who stopped
claiming unemployment benefit or income support after getting jobs.
In a letter to Mr Docherty, the Inland Revenue's head of operational
systems and support added that the fault was one of ''several teething
problems'' in the computer.
He estimates that people on income support who started work last
October, earning #8400-a-year -- #161-a-week -- will have wrongly paid
#270 in tax by December alone.
He stressed that the Inland Revenue was blameless and were to be
congratulated for speedily reacting to his complaint that no tax should
have been deducted until gross pay exceeded tax-free alowances.
However, Mr Docherty added: ''It is a serious cause for concern that
the error, built into the ESA system, had not been picked up by anyone
-- and has resulted in presumably thousands of youngsters being
overtaxed for a number of months.''
The Inland Revenue last night described the ESA errors as unfortunate,
but insisted they would have been revealed when tax records are checked
in April, the financial year's end. An official said: ''No-one need wait
until then to seek a refund. They can approach us at any time.''
A spokesman for the ESA, whose main job is to find work for the
unemployed but also issues benefit payments, said steps are being taken
to assess how a number of computer ''problems and difficulties'' can be
resolved.
Action on overcoming the fault affecting students who had started work
also was underway. The numbers involved were not known.
* Mr Docherty advised anyone coming off income support to carefully
check if their P45 shows a Week 1 (emergency) code number. If it does,
they should go to the ESA and ''insist on being given a correct code
number''. Only after the change should the P45 be given to employers.
</TEXT>
