<HEADLINE>Judge guilty of sexual harassment suspended</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A QC who sits as a part-time judge was yesterday suspended from
practice for three months after a Bar disciplinary tribunal found him
guilty of sexually harassing a client and a solicitor's clerk.
Mr Nigel Hamilton, 57, a member of the Bar's ruling General Council,
had ''smacked the backside'' of the defendant and ''touched the
backside'' of the clerk employed by the defendant's solicitors, the
tribunal found.
He also made indecent remarks to both women.
The decision of the Council of the Inns of Court was announced nearly
a month after its disciplinary body had found him guilty of two charges
of ''conduct discreditable to a barrister''.
The suspension would take effect from yesterday after a period during
which Mr Hamilton could have given notice of an appeal but did not do
so, the Council said.
Mr Hamilton was also ordered to pay #400 costs.
The tribunal, chaired by Mr Justice Morison, gave brief particulars of
the behaviour which had led to the two charges.
It occurred during the trial of the female defendant in an unnamed
Crown Court between September 16 and October 20, 1992.
Mr Hamilton, married with two grown-up sons, was a schoolmaster before
being called to the Bar in 1965.
He was appointed to the General Council in 1989.
He is a former Conservative member of Avon County Council and lives in
the village of Compton Martin, Avon. He has chambers in London and
Bristol.
Yesterday's statement said Mr Hamilton had faced four charges, but did
not give details of the two remaining charges.
A Bar spokesman said: ''The role of the Bar Council in matters such as
this is to prosecute cases where counsel's conduct discloses a prima
facie case of professional misconduct.
''The Bar Council considers sexual harassment a serious breach of its
code of conduct.
''We cannot, however, comment on the sentence imposed by the
disciplinary tribunal.''
The Lord Chancellor is to consider whether to withdraw Mr Hamilton's
authorisation to sit as assistant recorder, the Lord Chancellor's office
said yesterday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
