<DOCNO>GH950203-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pouring a pint of beer fit for a Prince</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prince of Wales proved himself an expert barman yesterday when he
pulled a perfect pint during a tour of a brewery.
Not known for his beer drinking, the Prince won praise for his
bartending skills at Fuller's Brewery in Chiswick, west London, which he
visited to mark its 150th anniversary.
The Prince, whose favourite tipple is Martini, sipped his pint of
Fuller's London Pride and admitted it tasted ''very strong''.
Tim and Frank Gale, bar staff whose family have contributed nearly 300
years of service to the brewery, said that the Prince admitted he was
not a beer connoisseur.
Tim Gale, 78, said: ''The Prince, pulled a great pint -- one long pull
and then a short one to give it its head. He said he was not an expert
but he liked the taste even though he said it tasted very strong.''
His brother, Frank, 68, added: ''He must have a bar of his own at home
-- he's a bit of an expert -- or perhaps he's done it before on other
visits to breweries.''
Earlier, the Prince helped to create a special celebratory bitter for
the brewery by pouring some Kent hops into a brewing vessel.
The 1845 Ale in bottles is being brewed to an ancient recipe, found in
old books from the time the Fuller's brewery was set up.
Beer has been brewed on the Chiswick site for more than 325 years --
since the time of Oliver Cromwell -- and the present company was formed
by an amalgamation of brewers 150 years ago.
The Prince spent more than an hour touring the plant, inspecting the
laboratories, and viewing the bottling process.
In the brewery's bar, he was applauded by employees as he pulled the
pint and unveiled a plaque recording his visit.
He asked Mr Anthony Fuller, the brewery chairman, if all those present
were going to get a beer ''on the house''. Mr Fuller said employees had
drawn lots to be in the bar and the beer was free.
He also assured the Prince that he would be sent him a crate of the
1845 Ale as soon as it was ready.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Victim art' dance show for festival</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042015</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONTROVERSIAL dance show, featuring filmed interviews with dying
people, is to run at the Edinburgh International Festival this summer.
Still/Here, produced by the American choreographer Bill T Jones, has
provoked a heated debate in the US with one eminent critic refusing to
review the show, labelling it ''victim art''.
The work involves dancers performing against a backdrop of large
screens on which are shown a number of patients discussing their
situations and emotions. All are terminally ill, some with Aids.
Jones, who is HIV positive and whose partner, dancer Arnie Zane, died
of Aids, appeared at the Edinburgh Festival in 1993, when his company
played to large audiences at the King's Theatre.
Still/Here is understood to have been booked for a three-night slot in
August at the Playhouse Theatre.
However, Edinburgh Councillor Christine Richard said last night that,
after reading about the production in a magazine, she had serious
misgivings about its inclusion in the festival.
''The festival is, by its very nature, a celebration of what is best
in theatre, opera, and dance. I find it very distasteful and rather
prurient that someone is making art or entertainment out of suffering.
''I think that, by using real people who are terminally ill, it
crosses the divide between art and exploitation. I can't imagine who
will want to see this show.''
Mrs Richard, a former Tory group leader on the council, admitted she
had not seen the performance and said she did not want to act as a
censor. She has discussed the show with festival director Mr Brian
McMaster and said she would be contacting Lord Provost Norman Irons, who
chairs the festival society board.
Mr McMaster yesterday defended the production and said its artistic
merits made it appropriate for the festival. He said: ''I saw it last
year. I didn't find it harrowing and I chose it because of its
quality.''
Mary Brennan, dance critic of The Herald, said: ''Jones is a
formidable talent. He makes dance that is fast, energetic, athletic --
very exciting to watch and yet full of recognisable emotions and
conflicts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Iran offers gold for best story on Rushdie's fear</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042016</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nicosia, Thursday
IRANIANS can win gold coins for short stories capturing the ''moments
of fear and anxiety'' of British author Salman Rushdie when he learned
the ayatollahs wanted him killed.
The Islamic Propagation Organisation, an Iranian quango, has announced
the competition this month, the sixth anniversary of the death edict
issued against Indian-born Rushdie by Tehran's late Ayatollah Khomeini
over the novel The Satanic Verses. Khomeini claimed Rushdie's book
blasphemed Islam.
The IPO is offering 10 gold coins for the best effort, five for the
second best, three for the third, and one apiece for seven runners up,
the IRNA news agency said.
''According to his own confession he (Rushdie) cannot leave his
residence without permission,'' IRNA gloated in the broadcast, monitored
in Cyprus.
A semi-official organisation, Khordad 15, has placed a bounty
exceeding #1m plus expenses for anyone who kills Rushdie.
Another Iranian organisation in 1993 offered gold coins worth about
#10,000 for the best caricatures of Rushdie, who has lived under tight
security since the death threat was issued but makes unannounced public
appearances and continues to write.--AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UN urges junta to free jailed heroine</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Geneva, Thursday
A UNITED Nations human rights investigator called on Burma immediately
to release dissident Aung San Suu Kyi and to stop its soldiers and
prison guards from committing killings and torture.
He also urged the ruling military junta, which took power in 1988, to
complete drafting of a constitution, hold promised free elections, and
allow a civilian government to be formed.
Yozo Yokota, special reporter to the UN Human Rights Commission,
echoed recent criticism of Burma's record by the US State Department and
London-based Amnesty International.
Yokota said Burmese Ministers had denied him access to Suu Kyi, the
1991 Nobel Peace Prize winner now in her sixth year of house arrest,
during his visit in November.
''With respect to Daw Aung San Suu Kyi, the government should release
her immediately and unconditionally,'' he reported.
The junta has scotched speculation in recent weeks that it might be
about to release Suu Kyi, telling Thailand's Foreign Minister that she
would not be freed until the constitution now being drafted was
complete. Diplomats in Rangoon say that could take years.
Yokota reported that the junta's reign of fear continued unabated,
with widespread executions, torture, slave labour, and forced
relocations of innocent villagers.
Suu Kyi, who is married to the British academic Dr Michael Aris, was
jailed by the junta a year before her National People's Party won a
landslide victory in elections.
In a move agreed with the Burmese Government last year, a UN
delegation will visit the country this weekend to act as intermediary in
three days of discussions on human rights and democracy.
Meanwhile, the media in Norway report that the jailed Chinese
dissident Wei Jingsheng and former US President Jimmy Carter are among
nominees for this year's Nobel Peace Prize.
Carter, the US president from 1976-80, has helped defuse crises
between the United States and North Korea, and mediated during the US
invasion of Haiti last year.
Russia's leading human rights campaigner Sergei Kovalyov, a disciple
of the late Nobel laureate Andrei Sakharov, has been nominated for
defending Chechens in Grozny and berating President Boris Yeltsin for
Russia's war on the rebel region.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato warns West of Islamic threat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bonn, Thursday
ISLAMIC fundamentalism poses just as great a threat to the West as
communism once did, Nato Secretary-General Willy Claes said today.
''Fundamentalism is at least as dangerous as communism was. Please do
not underestimate this risk,'' he told a German newspaper.
He said he did not see how fundamentalism and democracy could be
reconciled. However, he added that Nato could help to counter the threat
posed by Islamic extremists as the Alliance redefined its role after
winning the Cold War.
Asked what Nato could do, he said: ''Initiatives have just begun in
the field of restricting the spread of weapons of mass destruction. A
dialogue with Mediterranean countries is also beginning. How can we help
them meet the challenges of fundamentalism?
''Nato is much more than a military alliance,'' he said. ''It has
committed itself to defending basic principles of civilisation that bind
North America and Western Europe.''
After decades with its big guns facing towards the east, Nato has
begun to turn more attention towards the south, opening informal
contacts with northern African countries such as Egypt, Tunisia, and
Morocco.
Claes arrived in Bonn today for his first visit to Germany since
taking over as Nato chief last year.
He later met Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and they agreed that the Alliance
must co-operate with the emerging democracies in Eastern Europe to
stabilise the region.
''Integration and co-operation, above all an intensive partnership
with Russia and Ukraine, must complement each other so that no dividing
lines are created in Europe,'' said German Government spokesman Dieter
Vogel.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Turkey poised for deal with Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042019</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREEK objections to Turkey signing a Customs union with the European
Union look like being lifted when the EU Foreign Ministers meet in
Brussels on Monday.
The Foreign Ministers of Britain, France, Germany, Italy, and Turkey
made progress yesterday in winning the necessary assurances from Ankara
about a negotiated settlement on Cyprus.
Greece has blocked progress on the Customs union, due to take effect
at the end of this year. It used the veto when EU Foreign Ministers met
in December in Ankara, and also blocked the release to Turkey of
millions in EU grants and loans.
Yesterday's talks in London, which did not involve Greece, indicated
that the necessary breakthrough should come next week. An EU-Turkish
pact would give Ankara closer relations with Brussels than any country
other than Norway and Iceland. In return for dropping its tariffs on EU
goods, Turkey would gain access for its products to the vast EU market.
The diplomatic initiative has been inspired by the growing anxiety
within the EU about instability on its southern flank, particularly from
Muslim fundamentalism.
Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said there was a need for action on
Cyprus because the problem, instead of solving itself, would become
dangerous again. Negotiations about the entry of Cyprus and Malta to the
EU should start after the 1986 inter-governmental conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Britain signs up for new plane</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN last night announced plans to buy up to 50 European military
transport planes after France warned that British firms could lose out
on helping to build it.
France, Germany, and Italy are partners in a plan to develop the
so-called Future Large Aircraft to replace existing military transport
planes.
French Defence Minister Francois Leotard said today: ''If the British
do not buy the proposed plane, well, there is no reason why they should
make it, and on that basis, we would look at production arrangements
with the Germans and other Europeans, notably Italy.''
Defence Procurement Minister Roger Freeman said after talks with Mr
Leotard that Britain planned to sign an agreement by the end of the year
to buy up to 50 of the new European military transporters.
Mr Freeman told a Paris news conference: ''It is our intention to put
ourselves in a position to rejoin the project and sign an agreement by
the end of the year.''
He said Britain needed between 40 and 50 FLAs to replace the ageing
fleet of Hercules 130 transporters as well as VC10 and Tristar military
freighters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Newt Gingrich comes clean over contract</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042021</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
From PATRICK BROGAN
Washington, Thursday
SPEAKER Newt Gingrich admitted last night that his ''Contract with
America'' is in trouble. This is the legislative programme he hopes to
push through Congress by mid-April, or within 100 days. The deadline is
receding rapidly.
The contract won the Republicans the elections last November. They
have discovered that, despite their majorities in both houses, passing
the Bills is far more difficult than they expected.
Mr Gingrich told a meeting here: ''I'll be quite frank with you. I
think term-limits is going to be very hard to pass and I think
litigation reform is just going to be a brawl. We need your help on the
balanced budget amendment, which I think is in serious difficulty.''
That amendment was halved in the House and now faces difficulties in
the Senate. It needs 67 votes out of 100 to pass there, and the result
may turn on the votes of one or two senators.
As for term-limitation, that is very popular in many states: the
proposal is that Congressmen and Senators should serve no more than 12
years.
There are strong arguments against it: it is undemocratic, because it
limits citizens' rights to choose their representatives; it is
hypocritical, because it does not apply to senior Republicans like Mr
Gingrich, who have already served more than 12 years (Strom Thurmond was
elected to the Senate in 1954); and if voters want to throw the bums
out, they have regular opportunities to do so, and availed themselves of
that right last November.
It will be defeated in Congress, however, because most Congressmen and
Senators see no reason to vote themselves out of jobs they worked hard
to win.
Another ''Contract'' proposal, the line-item veto to allow presidents
to knock single items out of spending Bills, is going through easily,
but has been emasculated.
As for litigation reform, to limit liability awards and change the
lawyer-ridden American system, it faces ferocious opposition from the
law lobby, which carries great weight on Capitol Hill.
Other items in the ''Contract'' are in difficulty: the gun lobbyists
wants to repeal gun control laws, thus amending the Crime Bill in the
Contract, and will provoke a sustained battle if they try.
Most problematic of all, the contract proposes tax cuts, chiefly for
the rich, and a first step to balancing the budget. Battle starts next
week when President Clinton submits his budget to Congress.
</TEXT>
