<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dutch dikes 'could collapse like overcooked puddings'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042022</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Amsterdam, Thursday
BLOATED Dutch rivers which had threatened to flood over weakened
defences are tonight receding so fast that the fear is now of saturated
dikes collapsing.
Officials said water levels along the Rhine, Waal, Meuse, and IJssel
rivers were falling fast, but ancient dikes that have been under intense
pressure from flood waters for days could still collapse.
''The situation is stable now, but that does not mean the danger's
gone,'' Interior Minister Hans Dijkstal told Parliament. ''There are
still several places where dikes could be breached.''
A spokeswoman said: ''We're worried by the speed at which the water is
going down, because although that removes the pressure on the bottom of
the dikes, it means the heavily-soaked tops can fall inwards -- like an
overcooked plum pudding.''
Water levels at Lobith where the Rhine enters the Netherlands from
Germany had fallen more than a foot to 53ft 5in above sea-level by
mid-afternoon.
Officials predicted the water was likely to subside by 20in a day over
the weekend.
Hundreds of soldiers and volunteers who battled through the night to
buttress crumbling dikes appeared to have gained the upper hand today.
Fears that dikes would burst led to a quarter of a million people
being ordered to flee their homes in Holland's biggest peacetime
evacuation.
Some have since tried to get back to their homes to feed animals or
salvage valuables. One elderly farmer said today he was trying to reach
his home in the village of Ingen, where he had left behind #12,000.
Police mobilised from all over the Netherlands said they had sealed
off and were patrolling villages to deter looting.
As the water continued to subside across France, Belgium, and Germany,
authorities declared the worst of the crisis over.
Vast tracts of countryside and riverside villages in north-west Europe
remain submerged by the floods, which have claimed at least 26 lives,
but there was a sense of relief today as bright sunshine replaced days
of persistent rain.
In Brussels the European Investment Bank, the European Commission's
lending arm, said it was ready to help repair flood damage.
''We stand ready, if major reconstruction work is necessary, to make
available long-term finance,'' said Sir Brian Unwin, the bank's
president.
* The Dutch tulip harvest has escaped the floods. ''Almost 100% of our
tulip production is outside the flooding area,'' said marketing director
Bert Nollen at the International Flower Bulb Centre.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
