<HEADLINE>Leaders renew pledge to peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JEFFREY HELLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042026</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
From JEFFREY HELLER
Cairo, Thursday
ISRAEL and the Palestinians agreed at a four-nation summit in Cairo
today to press on with their self-rule agreements, while PLO leader
Yasser Arafat promised Israel he would take a strong line against
violent opponents of peace.
After more than five hours of talks, Arafat and the leaders of Israel,
Egypt, and Jordan made a fresh commitment to the goal of a full Middle
East peace, including Syria and Lebanon.
Egypt said it had called the historic one-day summit to save the
Middle East peace process from collapse over disputes such as Jewish
settlements, Islamic militant attacks on Israeli targets, and Israel's
refusal to sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
Asked if it had achieved this objective, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said: ''Yes. I believe the Palestinian-Israeli peace process is
back on track.''
PLO chairman Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin,
attending the summit with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and King
Hussein of Jordan, would meet again next Thursday on the border between
Gaza and Israel for more talks, he added.
Today was the leaders' first time for such a four-way meeting.
In a step towards what Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres has
called a ''coalition for peace'', the four nations would hold the first
of a series of regular meetings at foreign minister level in Washington
next week, a joint communique said.
Moussa said the summit failed to persuade Israel to ease the closure
of the Palestinian territories or to change its controversial policy on
Jewish settlement there.
On the peace process, a joint communique said: ''The leaders . . .
reaffirmed their determination to continue the Middle East peace process
towards the fulfilment of a just, lasting, and comprehensive peace . . .
The parties are committed to honour and implement fully in letter and
spirit the historic accords reached between them.
''(They) condemned all the outbreaks of bloodshed, terror, and
violence in the region and reaffirmed their intention to stand staunchly
against and put an end to all such acts,'' it added.
Moussa, asked what practical steps would be taken on violence, said:
''Such a meeting cannot discuss specifically ways and means but we
reaffirm our stand against all kinds of violence that would undermine
the peace process.''
The Palestinians had tried to steer the meeting away from the question
of violence and towards the next stage in Israel giving the Palestinians
more autonomy in the West Bank.
Asked what Arafat had won in exchange for his promise to act against
violent groups, Moussa said: ''The prompt activation of the peace
process between the Palestinians and the Israelis.''
The communique indicated that the leaders made little progress on the
dispute over Israel's nuclear programme, an issue gaining urgency as the
April deadline for renewing the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty
approaches.
''After appreciating President Mubarak's disarmament proposals on
weapons of mass destruction, the parties shall pursue a mutually viable
Middle East zone, free of weapons of mass destruction -- nuclear,
chemical, and biological,'' it said.
Moussa described the nuclear dispute as ''very serious'' and said
Egypt would keep talking about it with the Israelis.
Egypt has so far strongly resisted American pressure to agree an
extension of the Non-Proliferation Treaty unless it is signed by the
Jewish state. Israel, which is widely believed to possess nuclear arms,
has consistently refused to sign the treaty.
Peres said today that Israel and Egypt were close to resolving the
dispute over the treaty, but Moussa denied this.
The communique said the four leaders ''expressed the hope that the
near future will witness the achievement of peace accords between
Israel, Syria, and Lebanon''.
Asked if the summit had tried to influence Syria into compromising in
its peace talks with Israel, Moussa said: ''I don't think Syria needs
convincing because they believe in peace. But of course they stick to
the principle that we all agree on -- land for peace, all for all,'' he
said.
He was referring to Syria's insistence on a complete Israeli
withdrawal from the Golan Heights in exchange for full peace with the
Jewish state.--Reuter.
Leader comment 18
</TEXT>
