<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>O J 'dream' witness has drink problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Los Angeles, Thursday
THE retired policeman who claimed that ex-footballer turned film star
O J Simpson had told him he dreamed about killing his ex-wife admitted
that he had a drinking problem and had been disciplined for alcohol
abuse.
Ronald Shipp, giving evidence for the second day in Simpson's double
murder trial in Los Angeles, said he had drunk at Simpson's home while
consoling him and members of his family in the week after the murders of
Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend Ronald Goldman.
''Almost everyone in that house was drunk,'' he said.
He also admitted, under cross-examination by defence lawyer Carl
Douglas, to drunken outbursts at the home of Simpson's personal
secretary Cathy Randa in the two months after Nicole's death.
He said he had gone to Randa's house drunk and banged loudly on her
door because when he was under the influence of alcohol he had a habit
of turning up at people's homes unannounced.
Shipp said yesterday that, following a conversation about DNA tests on
the night after the murders, Simpson ''kind of jokingly just said, 'To
be honest Shipp, I've had some dreams of killing her'.''
Judge Lance Ito allowed the defence to establish that the dream
statement did not in fact follow the DNA conversation, but came after
Simpson had talked about not knowing whether he wanted to take a lie
detector test.
Prosecutor Marcia Clark argued that it was the dream statement that
was important, not when it was said.
''Walt Disney said it best in Sleeping Beauty. 'A dream is a wish your
heart makes','' she said.
Simpson denies the June 12 1994 murders of his ex-wife and Goldman.
In a dramatic and often emotional exchange with Douglas yesterday,
Shipp said he felt personal guilt over Nicole's death ''because perhaps
I didn't do as much as I could have''.
A friend of both Simpsons, Shipp said he counselled them after an
incident on New Year's Day 1989 in which Simpson did not contest a
charge of beating his wife.
At one point today Shipp was seen mouthing the words ''Tell the
truth'' to Simpson.
The judge ordered him not to try to make contact with the defendant.
The trial continues.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
