<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cancer deaths set to increase, warns health watchdog</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MAGEE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042030</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CANCER cases in Scotland will rise by 12% for men and 7% for women in
the decade up to the year 2000, a report predicted yesterday.
The document, produced by Lothian Health's public health medicine
department, says that more health promotion campaign work is required to
highlight death from cancer.
The report which states the potential for prevention is great
especially among smokers, highlights the differences in incidence rates
evident between the deprived and affluent areas.
It emphasises the importance of health promotion programmes, and
maintains that although there are existing national campaigns, promotion
work locally needed to be enhanced.
Acknowledging cancer as a major cause of illness and death with a
large proportion of resources spent every year on services, Lothian
Health pointed out that 90% of lung cancers and 30% of all cancers were
caused by smoking.
Cancers are responsible for about one in four of all deaths in Lothian
and every year more than 1000 men and 1000 women die from cancer.
Lothian Health said that it would be considering what action was
required in the light of the report.
Meanwhile, scientists fear a new cancer risk from motor vehicle
exhaust fumes after the discovery of radioactivity in children's teeth.
The pollutant, polonium-210, is derived from lead and was found after
tests on youngsters living near motorways, according to The Lancet.
Dr Denis Henshaw of Bristol University said: ''We were astounded to
find an association like this. It is the first time that variations of
it have been seen in the human body.''
He wants polonium-210 added to the list of potential cancer causing
substances in exhaust fumes. Dr Henshaw said the amounts detected cannot
be linked with any certainty to cancer cases.
However, evidence of its potential to cause tumours comes from
research linking exposure to high concentrations of naturally occurring
radon gas -- which also gives off radiation -- and leukemia, brain
tumours, and kidney cancer especially in children.
Concern about petrol pollution was heightened last October when a
committee of MPs called for super unleaded petrol which contains cancer
causing chemicals to be banned.
* As few as a third of women in the UK are benefitting from breast
cancer screening, a conference in Glasgow was told yesterday.
Dr Alastair Kirkpatrick, director of the South-East Scotland Breast
Screening Programme, said that the UK uptake for mammography screening
was about 70%. The Scottish figure is 72%.
''If 100% attended for screening, then we might expect to see a
reduction in mortality of 40%,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Residents challenge trust over payments</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042031</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESIDENTS are considering legal action against a health trust over its
management of a maintenance fund.
A condition of the sale two years ago of the former health board
houses in Netherton Oval, in the grounds of Lennox Castle Hospital near
Glasgow, was that residents pay at least #135 a year into a maintenance
fund.
However, the Netherton Residents' Association claims that about
#12,000 of payments remain unaccounted for and that only about #2000 has
been spent on repairs since the fund was established.
A solicitor for the residents claimed that the Greater Glasgow
Community and Mental Health Services NHS Trust has admitted that the
monies are going straight into a common fund used by the trust.
The contract involves the health board maintaining the water and
drainage systems, electricity for street lighting, roads, pavements, and
grass cutting in communal areas.
Mr Finlay Dow, chairman of the residents' association, said yesterday:
''We don't believe we are getting the service that we were promised. We
have to wait months just to get a street light bulb replaced.''
Health trust officials have allegedly conceded that only #60 had been
spent on street lighting, and the same again on road and pavement
repairs in the past year, although residents had contributed #850 and
#1000 respectively.
The residents want the condition of sale waived by the Scottish
Secretary so that they can be free to appoint their own factor.
A health trust official rejected allegations that the fund had been
mismanaged.
She said: ''The #2000 only covers the payment for road and pavement
repairs. The total figure spent on all of these services is considerably
higher.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major gets Blair's backing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE,POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042032</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ULSTER Unionists were silenced in the Commons yesterday in the face of
overwhelming cross-party support for the Prime Minister's battle to keep
the peace process alive.
Last night Labour leader Tony Blair, in a national broadcast,
supported Mr Major in his historic attempt to end the killing.
In a series of passionate exchanges in the Commons concerning the
controversial leak of a draft document, the Ulster Unionists had few
friends.
Later Viscount Cranbourne, a central ally of the Unionists brought
into the Cabinet by the Prime Minister, told a private meeting of
Ministers in the Lords that he will not resign on this issue. He will
support the Prime Minister whatever happens in the delicate and
dangerous pursuit of a final peace in Northern Ireland.
Viscount Cranbourne had been reported as threatening resignation on
this issue.
The political drift at Westminster last night, backed by Mr Blair and
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown, was for Mr Major's campaign for
peace.
The Northern Ireland Secretary, Sir Patrick Mayhew, told the Cabinet
yesterday morning he is launching an inquiry to try to discover who
leaked a partial draft document to The Times concerning the
London-Dublin negotiations to produce a next-stage platform for
constitutional negotiations.
Mr Blair told the nation last night: ''There are some areas of
Government activity which should rise above traditional party politics.
Seeking to bring peace to Northern Ireland is one of them. We are not
talking about differences of opinion here. We're talking about the
difference between life and death.''
Mr Blair acknowledged that London-Dublin negotiations were not yet
complete and it was sensible for people to wait for the full agreed
document before passing judgment.
In the Commons, Mr Blair gave immediate support to the Prime Minister.
As questioning built up from Tory and Labour benches the Prime
Minister's position improved. ''There is a communal will not to be
distracted from the goal of peaceful and permanent and agreed settlement
in Northern Ireland.''
To begin Ulster Unionist MPs were standing to attract the Speaker's
eye to be called. But by the end of the 15-minute question time they had
ceased to try to intervene.
Now the hunt for the leaker has been established by the Irish Premier,
Mr John Bruton, and by the British Government. The Northern Ireland
Office will report its findings to the Cabinet Secretary, Sir Robin
Butler, who will decide if further action needs to be taken.
The Ulster Unionists are still regarded as the ones most likely to
have leaked a draft document.
Meanwhile, the Irish Government last night confirmed the early release
of five IRA prisoners as part of its continuing response to terrorist
ceasefires in Northern Ireland.
The five will include Pamela Kane, 30, the only jailed IRA woman in
the Irish Republic. Kane, from Dublin, is serving a 10-year sentence for
her part in a bank raid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mystery of children left with stranger</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042033</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUNG child and a six-month-old baby were last night being cared for
by foster parents for the second night running after being abandoned by
a woman in the home of a stranger in the East End of Glasgow.
Strathclyde police issued an appeal for help in identifying the
children and the woman who left them.
Mr George McKenna, 38, unemployed, of Appin Road, Haghill told last
night how a woman in her late 40s had come to his door looking for his
next door neighbour's friend Pearl.
She asked him to look after the boys for a few minutes. More than
three hours later, she still had not returned.
One is aged between three and four; the baby aged between three and
six months.
Mr McKenna decided to contact the police. On his way to a phone-box in
Alexandra Parade, he stopped at a fish-and-chip shop to ask for advice,
and staff there called the police for him. The little boy was given some
chips.
''He was hungry. He wasn't long in eating them,'' said Mr McKenna.
''Most of the time the baby was sleeping, but sometimes it was crying.
The little boy kept on saying Mummy. I would have said he was missing
her.''
It was thought unlikely last night that the woman was the children's
mother, given her age. Police described her as 40 or 50 years of age, of
thin build, and with short, streaked hair. She was wearing black
leggings, a dark anorak, and white Hi-Tec training boots.
The older boy was of thin build, with black or brown hair, and brown
eyes.
He was wearing red tracksuit trousers, a two-tone blue top with the
logo ''Cricket New York Team'', black trainers, and a navy anorak with
an ''Arctic Region'' logo.
The baby also had black or brown hair, was slightly built, and had
brown eyes.
He was wearing a size 10 light grey body suit, a white jacket, light
blue padded trousers, and white socks.
Anyone with information is asked to contact London Road police station
on 041-554-1113.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fred Perry dies after fall in hotel</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>OBITUARY</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042034</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FRED PERRY, the last British man to lift the Wimbledon singles title,
died yesterday in hospital in Australia. He was 85.
Perry, who completed a hat-trick of titles between 1934-36, fell and
cracked four ribs in an accident in his hotel bathroom in Melbourne last
week.
He was released from hospital, but readmitted shortly afterwards after
reportedly suffering another fall.
A statement released by Wimbledon last night described him as ''one of
the most famous names in sport and revered throughout the tennis
world''.
Perry's fourth wife Barbara was with him in Melbourne where he had
been watching the Australian Open tennis championships. His daughter,
Penny, was on her way from London to Australia when he died.
The achievement which Perry himself treasured most was the Davis Cup
triumph over the French in Paris in 1933 when he helped bring the trophy
back to Britain for the first time since 1911.
Perry was one of the first players to make fitness a central plank of
his tournament preparation: he even trained with Arsenal.
His dedication spurred him to join the professional ranks in 1936,
earning the displeasure of Wimbledon who withdrew his honorary
membership and asked for the return of their tie.
The rift between Club and player was finally healed in 1984 when All
England chiefs erected a statue in his honour. The gates next to his
bronze figure bear his name.
He remained active until his death, and was a regular member of BBC
Radio's commentary team at Wimbledon and other major championships from
1949.
All England Club chairman John Curry said: ''Fred Perry was a
superlative ambassador for our sport throughout the world. He was a
great character, big-hearted and a true champion in every sense.''
A statement from the Lawn Tennis Association said: ''His playing
record commanded universal respect and his wit and warm personality
rightly earned him a special place in the affections of everyone
involved in tennis.''
Mr Brian Tobin, president of the International Tennis Federation,
said: ''Not only was he a great champion, he was also a great friend to
so many players and national tennis associations over the years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Donald Pleasence</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>OBITUARY</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>980042035</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACTOR Donald Pleasence has died, aged 75.
He had surgery to have a heart valve replaced shortly before
Christmas. He died at his home at St. Paul de Vence in the south of
France.
Pleasence had a distinguished career on the stage, before making
scores of films, including various notable Hollywood villains.
He is survived by his fourth wife, Linda, and six daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950203-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950203-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950203</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fairbairn gives Tory no chance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE,SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Tories have ''not a chance'' of holding on to Perth and Kinross
when the seat is next contested, according to the sitting MP, Sir
Nicholas Fairbairn.
Sir Nicholas, the self-styled bon viveur who is gravely ill with
hepatitis, announced last year that he would not be standing for
Parliament again. The liver disease has prevented him from attending
Westminster for several months.
In an interview with The Herald he was scathing about the choice of
candidate to succeed him, claiming that he had received ''innumerable
telephone calls and letters from local Tory supporters'' maintaining
that Mr John Godfrey, a London-based banker with no Perthshire
connections, would prove ''unelectable''.
Mr Godfrey was surprised by the criticism and said: ''I have had some
extremely useful chats with Sir Nicky, including some fatherly advice,
but he is a bit unpredictable.''
He pointed out that, since being adopted in October, he had bought a
home in Perthshire and builders would be finished doing work on it in a
fortnight. His wife and family would then move north and he would be
able to spend long weekends in Scotland meeting people in the
constituency.
''I have been up at weekends and the feedback I have had so far has
been absolutely fine,'' he added.
The constituency chairman, Mr Martin Robb, also thought Sir Nicholas
was being ''unreasonably critical'', adding: ''John has been up and down
like a yo-yo and no-one could say other than that he has done very well.
The reception recently from the Chamber of Commerce was fantastic, and
once he finds his feet on the ground I am sure he will do well.''
Speaking at Fordell Castle in Fife, Sir Nicholas said he saw his
successor as the kind of ''identical clone found on both sides of the
House'' which meant he was not sorry to be leaving Parliament.
Given the damage to his health, he was also frank about his attitude
to drinking, calling criticism of alcohol ''a form of puritanism and
self-satisfied intolerance''.
He added: ''If you look at the history of the world, alcohol has
always played its part. This concept that it should be licensed as a
poison is utterly ridiculous. The idea that it is some sort of permitted
sin is fatuous.''
He was also scathing of his party's attitude to Europe as ''a fantasy
of illusion for do-gooder imaginists like Hurd''. He made clear that,
had he been well enough to attend the Commons, he would have been one of
the party's Euro-rebels.
He said: ''I would not regard it as defying the leadership. I would be
doing what I was elected to Parliament to do, to exercise my judgment if
I consider something to be an unprincipled folly. I have not been sent
there to wink just because John Major says wink.
''If you had told any British subject 20 years ago that they would
lose their currency, their flag, their foreign policy, and control over
their own Army, they would have said you were insane. Anyone says that
now and they are a rebel.''
Repenting nothing of his roller-coaster career, he said: ''In politics
if I had kept my nose clean and brushed my hair and wiped my bottom and
sucked up I would no doubt have got a lot further but since the price of
getting further would have been alien to my nature, I don't regret
that.''
</TEXT>
