<HEADLINE>Safety fears over emergencies.    Scots 999 gas calls go South</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>980042037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Gas is to switch emergency calls from offices in Scotland to a
new centre based in Newcastle upon Tyne.
The move has angered unions, consumers, and politicians concerned
about the safety implications.
It is being seen as a further blow to a workforce who, it is claimed
by unions and consumer groups, are already demoralised by cutback plans.
These include cutting the salaries of showroom staff, shutting
showrooms, loss of Scottish Gas headquarters in Edinburgh, and shedding
thousands of jobs over the next three to five years.
The decision was confirmed as Mr Cedric Brown the company's
#475,000-a-year chief executive flew into Scotland last night.
He will entertain top management to dinner before visiting district
offices. He will also meet a number of staff to discuss the company's
current position.
After arriving in Edinburgh, he placed a question mark over the future
of the British Gas Scottish operations when he warned that the
privatised utility had to undergo change because of increased
competition coming into the gas market.
He said at Edinburgh Airport: ''I am here for a routine visit because
I believe in getting out and meeting staff. A lot of changes are taking
place within British Gas as competition comes into the market. The
company has to change.''
Mr Brown invited British Gas Scottish staff to be both open and frank
with him whilst he was in Scotland.
There was a frank statement from Mr Alex Salmond, SNP leader, who
said: ''The way Cedric Brown is going British Gas staff will be stuck in
a bunker somewhere running the whole operation.
''This is a further retrenchment from an already reduced position. We
have already seen that there is a question mark over British Gas's
emergency response following the explosion in Inverness last month.
''Emergency calls require some degree of familiarity with the areas
concerned. Quite often in an emergency a caller does not have the time
or ability to give an absolutely detailed description. That is clearly
not going to be avaliable.''
Mr Jim Waller, senior regional officer of Unison, said union members
were concerned at the implications of implementing an untried system
from Newcastle. ''Our members are certainly concerned about the safety
implication of this moving the emergency calls to Newcastle. Nobody
quite knows if it is going to work.
''British Gas have moved their headquarters out of Scotland, they have
done away with one stop shops where people can get all the services
including help and assistance, and now this.''
Mr Waller said he had asked if he could meet Mr Brown on his current
visit to put union concerns to him but had had his request turned down.
''I was told he would only be meeting employees. I wanted to discuss
with him the situation that British Gas employees find themselves in.
They don't know where they stand.''
The proposal has also been attacked by the Gas Consumer Council. Mr
Euan Robson, Scottish manager, said: ''We don't like this.
''We can see a number of problems developing. In particular we are
concerned about back-up in the event of the system failing. They are
going to introduce the system and take off the various district systems
at the same time.
''There is also the question of local accents. In an emergency how
will a Geordie understand a Glaswegian?''
Mr Robson said there was huge public concern with the way Scottish Gas
was operating in Scotland. ''I have no idea where Mr Brown is going or
who he is going to talk to. But he is welcome to come in here and we
will show him what his customers are saying to us. Standards are
slipping badly.
''The foundation of British Gas's success in the past has been a
quality service delivered in a safe manner. The wheels are now starting
to come off that.''
Mr Hamish McPherson, Scottish communications manager for British Gas,
said there would be no loss of service when the emergency calls service
moved to Newcastle.
''From around May if you dial a local emergency number in Scotland
your call will be rerouted to a central bureau in Newcastle who will
reroute it on to the people in Scotland.
''There is nothing new in that. Within Scotland and other areas calls
are already rerouted to various emergency bureaux. The important thing
is that safety is paramount and response times will be exactly the same
as before.
''The staff employed in these offices at the moment might go into
other jobs within the company. All staff are offered other opportunities
within the company. Any redundancies are purely voluntary.''
One third of British Gas staff in Scottish showrooms have applied for
voluntary redundancy rather than opt for pay cuts, claimed to be up to
16%.
Mr McPherson said: ''Approximately 50 retail staff out of 150 have
applied for voluntary redundancy. The majority of these have long
service with British Gas and were happy to take an attractive package.''
On the issue of wages, Mr Brown emphasised that no-one in British Gas
had had their wages cut. When asked about his own salary he said no
staff member he met whilst in Scotland should feel inhibited about
talking to him, either about his or their wage.
</TEXT>
