<HEADLINE>Clarke hint on single Euro currency</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>980042038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor last night raised the prospect of a single European
currency before the end of the century.
The Cabinet has reportedly ruled out a single currency by 1997, but Mr
Kenneth Clarke said there ''might'' be one two years later.
Mr Major has insisted it is so far off in the future there is no need
to address it before the next election.
The Government negotiated an opt-out of the single currency provisions
of the Maastricht Treaty which set a target of 1997, with 1999 as the
latest date.
Mr Clarke told Channel 4 News: ''The British are not committed. It's a
two-way choice.
''It's a choice that I hope we'll exercise sensibly if others go ahead
with a single currency, which I believe will certainly not be possible
in 1996-97.
''It might be in 1999.''
However, European Commission President Jacques Santer last weekend
insisted the Maastricht timetable must be stuck to.
Mr Clarke insisted a single currency by 1997 was ''an academic
question''. Only the UK, Luxembourg, and possibly Germany would meet the
economic convergence criteria in time, he said.
Earlier the Chancellor had more immediate monetary issues in mind when
he lifted interest rates half a point to 6[3/4]%, his third rise in five
months as he strives to subdue inflationary pressures in the economy.
Building societies appeared to take the move in their stride, and
there was no sign they would follow through with increases in their
mortgage lending rates.
The Halifax saw no need to make any changes, though it said it would
keep the situation under review. The Abbey National bank said it was
''reluctant'' to increase rates, while the Nationwide said it was
reviewing the situation.
However, the trend in interest rates is still upward and house buyers
are likely to suffer eventually. Businesses will now have to pay more
for their borrowings.
The decision to lift rates was taken at the regular monthly meeting
between Mr Clarke and the Governor of the Bank of England, Mr Eddie
George. It was expected in financial markets and generally welcomed.
Mr Major defended the Chancellor's move, saying it was necessary to
keep inflation under control, but he admitted it would cause extra
hardship to homeowners.
Labour leader Tony Blair asked him in the Commons to confirm that the
typical homeowner would be #800 worse off since last April, because of
interest rate rises and Budget changes, and noted that Mr Major did not
dispute his figure.
Mr Blair asked: ''What kind of recovery is it which peaks when it has
hardly begun?'' He said it was no good Ministers ''scrabbling around to
find the feel-good factor'', adding ''people feel insecure because they
know they are worse off under the Tories''.
Mr Major retorted that he ''had cheek'' considering that the new
interest rate level equalled the lowest achieved at any stage by the
last Labour Government.
Labour calculates that, assuming no further rate increases, by April
1995 average housing costs will have risen by #785 or 25% in one year.
